honeyDew;\"|0.65% ''4''\n|-\n|  style=\"text-align:center;\" {{Party shading/Democratic}}|'''[[1924 United States presidential election|1924]]'''\n|  style=\"text-align:center;\" {{Party shading/Republican}}|23.92% ''83''\n|  style=\"text-align:center;\" {{Party shading/Democratic}}|'''61.10%''' ''212''\n|  style=\"text-align:center; background:honeyDew;\"|14.98% ''52''\n|}\n{{Hidden end}}\n\n==Energy and environment==\n[[Florida Public Service Commission]] voted unanimously to deny a request by Florida Power and Light to build a huge [[coal-fired power plant]] in Glades County, that was to be located several miles to the west of [[Lake Okeechobee]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.sierraclub.org/grassroots/stories/00017.asp |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2008-09-11 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081010233908/http://www.sierraclub.org/grassroots/stories/00017.asp |archivedate=2008-10-10 }}</ref>\nThe Glades County Commission also allowed the construction in 2007 of a {{convert|200|acre|km2|adj=on}} landfill on the southwest shore of [[Lake Okeechobee]].\n\n==Libraries==\nGlades County is part of the Heartland Library Cooperative which has 7 branches that serve Glades county and some of the surrounding counties, including [[DeSoto County, Florida|DeSoto]], [[Highlands County, Florida|Highlands]], [[Hardee County, Florida|Hardee]], and [[Okeechobee County, Florida|Okeechobee]].\n\n*Avon Park\n*DeSoto\n*Glades\n*Hardee\n*Lake Placid\n*Okeechobee\n*Sebring\n\n==Communities==\n===Indian reservation===\n*[[Brighton Seminole Indian Reservation]]\n\n===County Seat===\n*[[Moore Haven, Florida|Moore Haven]]\n\n===Census-designated place===\n*[[Buckhead Ridge, Florida|Buckhead Ridge]]\n\n===Other unincorporated communities===\n*[[Lakeport, Florida|Lakeport]]\n*[[Muse, Florida|Muse]]\n*[[Palmdale, Florida|Palmdale]]\n\n== Memorials ==\n\n* The Community Center features a veteran memorial to Jim J. Greer at the base of the flagpole. Memorial reads as follows:   ''In Memory of,'' ''[[Senior master sergeant|SMSGT]] Jim J. Greer, [[United States Air Force|USAF]] RET.,'' ''Glades County Tax Collector,'' ''January 1994 to October 2000,'' ''For His Outstanding Service, To'' ''Muse and Glades County, The Muse Community Association,'' ''April 18, 2002.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.waymarking.com/waymarks/WMZ2NB_Jim_J_Greer_Muse_Florida_USA|title=Jim J. Greer - Muse, Florida, USA - Specific Veteran Memorials|last=|first=|date=|website=|access-date=}}</ref>''\n\n==See also==\n*[[Florida Heartland]]\n*[[National Register of Historic Places listings in Glades County, Florida]]\n\n==References==\n<references />\n\n==External links==\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20090213143900/http://www.gladesgop.org/ \"The Glades County Republican Party\"] Primary website for the Glades County Republican Party.\n* [http://ufdc.ufl.edu/UF00028301 ''Glades County Democrat''] newspaper that serves Glades County, Florida available in full-text with images in [http://ufdc.ufl.edu/fdnl1 Florida Digital Newspaper Library]\n{{commons category}}\n\n===Government links/Constitutional offices===\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20140305171254/http://election.dos.state.fl.us/county/countyInfo.asp?county=GLA Glades County Supervisor of Elections info]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20120716211200/http://www.flsheriffs.org/sheriffs/glades.htm Glades County Sheriff bio]\n* [http://www.mygladescountytaxcollector.com/ Glades County Tax Collector info]\n* [http://www.gladessheriff.org Glades County Sheriff's Office Official Website]\n\n====Special districts====\n* [http://www.glades-schools.org Glades County School District]\n* [http://www.gladesswcd.com/index.html Glades Soil and Water Conservation District]\n* [http://www.sfwmd.gov South Florida Water Management District]\n* [http://www.myhlc.org Heartland Library Cooperative]\n\n====Judicial branch====\n* [http://www.gladesclerk.com/ Glades County Clerk of Courts]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20041209093650/http://publicdefender.cjis20.org/  Public Defender, 20th Judicial Circuit of Florida] serving [[Charlotte County, Florida|Charlotte]], [[Collier County, Florida|Collier]], Glades, [[Hendry County, Florida|Hendry]] and [[Lee County, Florida|Lee]] Counties\n* [http://sao.cjis20.org/  Office of the State Attorney, 20th Judicial Circuit of Florida]\n* [http://www.ca.cjis20.org/  Circuit and County Court for the 20th Judicial Circuit of Florida]\n\n{{Geographic Location\n|Centre    = Glades County, Florida\n|North     = [[Highlands County, Florida|Highlands County]]\n|Northeast = [[Okeechobee County, Florida|Okeechobee County]]\n|East      = [[Martin County, Florida|Martin County]]\n|Southeast = [[Palm Beach County, Florida|Palm Beach County]]\n|South     = [[Hendry County, Florida|Hendry County]]\n|Southwest = [[Lee County, Florida|Lee County]]\n|West      = [[Charlotte County, Florida|Charlotte County]]\n|Northwest = [[DeSoto County, Florida|DeSoto County]]\n}} \n{{Glades County, Florida}}\n{{Florida}}\n\n{{coord|26.95|-81.19|display=title|type:adm2nd_region:US-FL_source:UScensus1990}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Florida counties]]\n[[Category:Glades County, Florida| ]]\n[[Category:1921 establishments in Florida]]\n[[Category:Populated places established in 1921]]\n", "name_user": "Whoisjohngalt", "label": "safe", "comment": "Cleaned up usingAutoEd", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Glades_County,_Florida"}
{"title_page": "Heather Wheeler", "text_new": "{{short description|British Conservative politician}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=January 2020}}\n{{Use British English|date=January 2020}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n| image             =Official portrait of Mrs Heather Wheeler MP crop 2.jpg\n| honorific-prefix  =\n| name              = Heather Wheeler\n| honorific-suffix  = [[Member of Parliament (United Kingdom)|MP]]\n|office             = [[Under-Secretary of State for Foreign Affairs|Parliamentary Under-Secretary of State for Asia and the Pacific]]\n|primeminister      = [[Boris Johnson]]\n|term_start         = 26 July 2019\n|term_end           = 13 February 2020\n|predecessor        = [[Mark Field]]\n|successor          = [[Nigel Adams]] {{small|(Asia)}}<br/>[[Zac Goldsmith|The Lord Goldsmith of Richmond Park]] {{small|(Pacific)}}\n|office1            = [[Ministry of Housing, Communities and Local Government|Parliamentary Under-Secretary of State for Housing and Homelessness]]\n|primeminister1     = [[Theresa May]]\n|term_start1        = 9 January 2018\n|term_end1          = 26 July 2019\n|predecessor1       = [[Marcus Jones (politician)|Marcus Jones]]\n|successor1         = [[Luke Hall (politician)|Luke Hall]]\n|office2            = [[Lords Commissioners of the Treasury|Lord Commissioner of the Treasury]]\n|primeminister2     = [[Theresa May]]\n|term_start2        = 15 June 2017\n|term_end2          = 9 January 2018\n|predecessor2       = [[Guy Opperman]]\n|successor2         = [[Rebecca Harris]]\n| office3           = [[Member of Parliament (United Kingdom)|Member of Parliament]] <br /> for [[South Derbyshire (UK Parliament constituency)|South Derbyshire]]\n| majority3         = 19,335 (36.3%)\n| predecessor3      = [[Mark Todd (politician)|Mark Todd]]\n| successor3        = \n| term_start3       = 6 May 2010\n| term_end3         = \n| birth_date        = {{Birth date and age|1959|05|14|df=yes}}<ref>{{cite web|url= http://news.bbc.co.uk/democracylive/hi/representatives/profiles/35319.stm |title=Heather Wheeler MP |publisher=BBC |work=BBC Democracy Live |date= |accessdate=25 July 2010}}</ref>\n| birth_place       = [[Norwich]], [[Norfolk]], England<ref>{{cite web |title= Who's Who 2015: WHEELER, Heather |url= http://www.ukwhoswho.com/view/article/oupww/whoswho/U251302/ | website           = ukwhoswho.com | publisher = [[Who's Who (UK)]] }}</ref>\n| death_date        =\n| death_place       =\n| nationality       = British  \n| spouse            = Bob\n| children          = Harriet\n| party             = [[Conservative Party (UK)|Conservatives]]\n| website           = [http://www.heatherwheeler.org.uk/ www.heatherwheeler.org.uk]\n}}\n'''Heather Kay Wheeler'''<ref>{{London Gazette |issue=59418 |pages=8740\u20138740  |date= 13 May 2010 }}</ref> (born 14 May 1959) is a British [[Conservative Party (UK)|Conservative Party]] politician, who was first elected at the [[2010 United Kingdom general election|2010 general election]] as the [[Member of Parliament (United Kingdom)|Member of Parliament]] (MP) for [[South Derbyshire (UK Parliament constituency)|South Derbyshire]], taking the seat from the [[Labour Party (UK)|Labour Party]] after 13 years.<ref name=\"BBC-eln2010\">{{cite news |url=http://www.thisisderbyshire.co.uk/news/Wheeler-wins-turn-South-Derbys-blue-time-13-years/article-2128809-detail/article.html |title=Election 2010: South Derbyshire |work=thisisderbyshire.co.uk |accessdate=7 May 2010}}</ref> She served as [[Parliamentary Under-Secretary of State]] at the [[Ministry of Housing, Communities and Local Government]] from January 2018 to July 2019. She served as the [[Under-Secretary of State for Foreign Affairs|Parliamentary Under-Secretary of State for Asia and the Pacific]] in the [[Second Johnson ministry|Johnson administration]] until her resignation on 13 February 2020 due to family commitments.\n\n==Early life and local government career==\nWheeler, n\u00e9e Wilkinson, was born in Norwich on 14 May 1959. She was brought up and state educated in [[Wandsworth]] and was elected a Conservative member for West Hill ward on [[Wandsworth London Borough Council]] at the age of 22 in May 1982.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.electionscentre.co.uk/wp-content/uploads/2015/06/Wandsworth-1964-2010.pdf|title= Wandsworth Council Election Results 1964-2010 |publisher= Plymouth University|accessdate=12 July 2018}}</ref> After serving a full council term, she married her husband Bob, moving in 1986 to [[Bretby]], South Derbyshire.<ref name=aboutheatherwheeler>{{cite web |url=https://www.heatherwheeler.org.uk/about-heather-wheeler |title=About Heather Wheeler |access-date=23 August 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170406083647/https://www.heatherwheeler.org.uk/about-heather-wheeler |archive-date=6 April 2017 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\nAfter working for Lloyds insurance brokers for 10 years, qualifying by exam as an Associate, she became a member of The Chartered Insurance Institute.<ref name=aboutheatherwheeler/>\n\nWheeler was first elected to [[South Derbyshire District Council]] in 1995 for the safe Conservative seat of Repton. She went on to become leader of the council's Conservative group and became Leader of the Council between 2007\u20132010. She was successfully re-elected as a councillor for Repton ward until 2011; her daughter Harriet unsuccessfully stood as a Conservative candidate in Swadlincote ward in 2011, whilst husband Bob successfully defended his marginal Linton ward and continued as Leader of the council.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.electionscentre.co.uk/wp-content/uploads/2015/06/South-Derbyshire-1973-2011.pdf|title= South Derbyshire Council Election Results 1973-2011|publisher= Plymouth University |accessdate=12 July 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Parliamentary career==\nWheeler stood unsuccessfully at the [[2001 United Kingdom general election|2001]] and [[2005 United Kingdom general election|2005 general elections]] as her party's candidate for [[Coventry South (UK Parliament constituency)|Coventry South]].<ref name=parliamentbiowheeler/> Wheeler was a member of the Conservative Party's [[A-List (Conservative)|A-List]]<ref>{{cite web | title = Seats and candidates: Where are the original A-Listers now? The 27 who have been selected for target seats | website = conservativehome.blogs.com | publisher = [[ConservativeHome]] | url = http://conservativehome.blogs.com/goldlist/2009/04/where-are-the-original-alisters-now-the-27-who-have-been-selected-for-target-seats.html }}</ref> prior to being selected to contest the [[South Derbyshire (UK Parliament constituency)|South Derbyshire]] constituency. At the [[2010 United Kingdom general election|2010 general election]], she gained the seat from [[Labour Party (UK)|Labour]] with a majority of 7,128; there was a 9.8% swing to the Conservatives. Following her election as a [[Member of Parliament (United Kingdom)|Member of Parliament]] she stood aside as Conservative council group leader. She was re-elected in 2015 and 2017, with the former defying polling that suggested her seat would be vulnerable following the Conservative Government's failure to award a major contract to local train manufacturer Bombardier.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite news|url=http://www.burtonmail.co.uk/heather-wheeler-wins-her-seat-in-south-derbyshire-with-a-comfortable-majority/story-30380598-detail/story.html|title=Heather Wheeler wins her seat in South Derbyshire|date=2017-06-09|work=Burton Mail|access-date=2017-06-10|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://conservativehome.blogs.com/goldlist/2011/08/poll-boosts-labour-hopes-of-ousting-heather-wheeler-mp-on-back-of-siemens-trains-deal.html|title=Poll boosts Labour hopes of ousting Heather Wheeler MP on back of Siemens trains deal|publisher=Conservative Home|accessdate=12 July 2018}}</ref>\n\nIn the [[House of Commons of the United Kingdom|House of Commons]] she sat on the [[Standards and Privileges Committee]], the European Scrutiny Committee and the [[Communities and Local Government Committee]].<ref name=parliamentbiowheeler>{{cite web|title=Heather Wheeler|url=http://www.parliament.uk/biographies/commons/heather-wheeler/4053|website=Parliament UK|accessdate=8 April 2015}}</ref> She was also a member of the [[Public Bill Committee]] for the [[Defence Reform Act 2014]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://services.parliament.uk/bills/2013-14/defencereform/committees/houseofcommonspublicbillcommitteeonthedefencereformbill201314.html|title=House of Commons Public Bill Committee on the Defence Reform Bill 2013-14 |publisher=Parliament.uk |date= |accessdate=17 September 2013}}</ref>\n\nWheeler was one of 79 Conservative MPs who supported a 2011 rebel motion calling for a [[2016 United Kingdom European Union membership referendum|referendum on the European Union]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Rebel MPs: the full list|url=http://www.newstatesman.com/blogs/the-staggers/2011/10/north-mps-south-referendum|accessdate=8 April 2015 | work = [[New Statesman]]|publisher= Progressive Media International |date=25 October 2011}}</ref> She also joined a 2013 rebel amendment expressing regret at not including the referendum in the government's plans.<ref>{{cite news|title=The 114 Tory rebels in EU protest vote|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/worldnews/europe/eu/10060827/The-114-Tory-rebels-in-EU-protest-vote.html|accessdate=8 April 2015|work= [[The Daily Telegraph]] | publisher = [[Telegraph Media Group]] | location = London |date=15 May 2013}}</ref> She subsequently backed the government's plans to hold a referendum in 2017 and opposed a proposal to hold it in 2014.<ref>{{cite web|title=Craig Whittaker: Referendum on the UK's membership of the EU|url=http://www.publicwhip.org.uk/mp.php?mpn=Craig_Whittaker&mpc=Calder_Valley&house=commons&dmp=1027&display=motions|website=Public Whip|accessdate=8 April 2015}}</ref> Wheeler backed Leave in the referendum.<ref>https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-eu-referendum-35616946</ref>\n\nIn January 2018,  Wheeler was appointed as a Parliamentary Under Secretary of State at the Ministry of Housing, Communities and Local Government, with responsibility for homelessness and rough sleeping as well as the private rented and leasehold sectors.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.gov.uk/government/people/heather-wheeler#biography|title=Heather Wheeler MP - GOV.UK|website=www.gov.uk|language=en|access-date=2018-03-18}}</ref>\n\nIn July 2019, Wheeler was appointed as the [[Parliamentary Under-Secretary of State]] for Asia and the Pacific at the [[Foreign and Commonwealth Office]].  She was dismissed in February 2020.\n\n==Controversies==\nIn August 2016, following the [[2016 Rio Olympics]], the European Union social media account shared a modified medals table showing its combined member states in first place. Wheeler tweeted in response that the [[British Empire]] had won the 2016 Rio Olympics along with a map of former imperial territories.<ref>{{citation|url = https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/politics/conservative-mp-heather-wheeler-brexit-british-empire-won-the-olympics-a7204546.html | title = 'British Empire' won the Olympics, claims Conservative MP Heather Wheeler | last = Withnall | first = Adam | date = August 23, 2016 | work = [[The Independent]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Muir|first=Rod|url=https://www.totalpolitics.com/articles/news/conservative-mp-celebrates-performance-%E2%80%98british-empire%E2%80%99-rio|title=Conservative MP celebrates performance of 'British Empire' in Rio|work=Total Politics|date=23 August 2016|accessdate=23 August 2016}}</ref> Her comments were attacked by critics as being \"deeply offensive to so many people and their ancestors\" and \"insensitive and ignorant\", but she rejected calls to apologise, instead arguing that her comments were \"tongue-in-cheek\".<ref name=\"BBC\">{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-derbyshire-37163416|publisher=BBC|title=MP Heather Wheeler sparks Twitter backlash with British Empire post|accessdate=12 July 2018}}</ref>\n\nIn September 2017, Wheeler was criticised for claiming expenses for first-class tickets when she travelled by rail, despite official guidance from the [[Independent Parliamentary Standards Authority]] \u2013 set up in the wake of the 2009 expenses scandal \u2013 saying politicians should \u201cconsider value for money\u201d when booking tickets. However, she argued that her claims were permissible within the expenses rules and that the first-class tickets were cheaper than some standard class tickets available.<ref>{{cite news|title=Three Tory Derbyshire MPs claim \u00a310k on first-class train tickets in a year|url=https://www.derbytelegraph.co.uk/news/local-news/three-tory-derbyshire-mps-claim-449373|work=Derby Telegraph|accessdate=12 July 2018|author=|date=8 September 2017}}</ref>\n\nIn March 2018, following her promotion to a Government position with responsibility for homelessness, Wheeler told ''[[The Guardian]]'' newspaper that she did not know why the number of rough sleepers had increased in recent years. Wheeler rejected the suggestion that welfare reforms and council cuts relating to her Government had contributed to the rise.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/society/2018/mar/18/homelessness-minister-heather-wheeler-rough-sleeping-housing-first|title=Homelessness minister: I don't know why rough sleeper numbers are up|last=Brooks|first=Libby|date=2018-03-18|website=the Guardian|language=en|access-date=2018-03-18}}</ref> Earlier in the same month, Wheeler promised to resign if the number of people rough sleeping got worse while she was in office.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/av/uk-politics-43288585/heather-wheeler-to-resign-if-rough-sleeping-gets-worse|title=Homelessness minister gives herself ultimatum|website=BBC News|language=en-GB|access-date=2018-03-18}}</ref>\n\nIn June 2019, it was revealed that in October 2017, three months before she became minister, Wheeler described rough sleepers in her constituency as \u201cthe traditional type, old tinkers, knife-cutters wandering through\u201d. In response, Wheeler faced calls to resign from Stephen Robertson, the chief executive of the [[The Big Issue|Big Issue Foundation]] and a representative from a leading national charity which works on behalf of Gypsies, Travellers and Roma described the language as \u201cdisgraceful\u201d. Wheeler issued an apology for her \u201cinappropriate language\u201d, and said it \u201cis not at all representative of the great cultural contribution and rich heritage that the Gypsy, Roma and Traveller communities make to this country\u201d.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/society/2019/jun/20/homelessness-minister-accused-of-racist-remarks-in-email|title=Homelessness minister accused of racist remarks about rough sleepers|last=Greenfield|first=Patrick|date=2019-06-20|work=The Guardian|access-date=2019-06-20|last2=Marsh|first2=Sarah|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077|last3=McDevitt|first3=Johnny}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nWheeler's late husband Bob was a Conservative councillor who was made leader of South Derbyshire District Council in 2010, after his wife stepped down from the role on becoming an MP. He stood down as Leader of the Council in January 2018; he died in late 2018.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://south-derbys.cmis.uk.com/south-derbys/Councillors/tabid/63/ctl/ViewCMIS_Person/mid/383/id/5/ScreenMode/Alphabetical/Default.aspx|title=Cllr Robert Wheeler|publisher=South Derbyshire Council|accessdate=12 July 2018}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category}}\n*[http://www.heatherwheeler.org.uk/ Official website]\n*{{UK MP links | parliament =  heather-wheeler/4053 | publicwhip = heather_wheeler | theywork = heather_wheeler}}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-par|uk}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Mark Todd (politician)|Mark Todd]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Member of Parliament (United Kingdom)|Member of Parliament]] for [[South Derbyshire (UK Parliament constituency)|South Derbyshire]]|years=[[2010 United Kingdom general election|2010]]\u2013present}}\n{{s-inc}} \n{{s-end}}\n\n{{East Midlands Conservative Party MPs}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Wheeler, Heather}}\n[[Category:1959 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Conservative Party (UK) MPs for English constituencies]]\n[[Category:Councillors in the London Borough of Wandsworth]]\n[[Category:Councillors in Derbyshire]]\n[[Category:Members of the Parliament of the United Kingdom for constituencies in Derbyshire]]\n[[Category:Female members of the Parliament of the United Kingdom for English constituencies]]\n[[Category:People educated at Grey Coat Hospital]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 2010\u20132015]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 2015\u20132017]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 2017\u20132019]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 2019\u2013]]\n[[Category:21st-century British women politicians]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|British Conservative politician}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=January 2020}}\n{{Use British English|date=January 2020}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n| image             =Official portrait of Mrs Heather Wheeler MP crop 2.jpg\n| honorific-prefix  =\n| name              = Heather Wheeler\n| honorific-suffix  = [[Member of Parliament (United Kingdom)|MP]]\n|office             = [[Under-Secretary of State for Foreign Affairs|Parliamentary Under-Secretary of State for Asia and the Pacific]]\n|primeminister      = [[Boris Johnson]]\n|term_start         = 26 July 2019\n|term_end           = 13 February 2020\n|predecessor        = [[Mark Field]]\n|successor          = [[Nigel Adams]] {{small|(Asia)}}<br/>[[Zac Goldsmith|The Lord Goldsmith of Richmond Park]] {{small|(Pacific)}}\n|office1            = [[Ministry of Housing, Communities and Local Government|Parliamentary Under-Secretary of State for Housing and Homelessness]]\n|primeminister1     = [[Theresa May]]\n|term_start1        = 9 January 2018\n|term_end1          = 26 July 2019\n|predecessor1       = [[Marcus Jones (politician)|Marcus Jones]]\n|successor1         = [[Luke Hall (politician)|Luke Hall]]\n|office2            = [[Lords Commissioners of the Treasury|Lord Commissioner of the Treasury]]\n|primeminister2     = [[Theresa May]]\n|term_start2        = 15 June 2017\n|term_end2          = 9 January 2018\n|predecessor2       = [[Guy Opperman]]\n|successor2         = [[Rebecca Harris]]\n| office3           = [[Member of Parliament (United Kingdom)|Member of Parliament]] <br /> for [[South Derbyshire (UK Parliament constituency)|South Derbyshire]]\n| majority3         = 19,335 (36.3%)\n| predecessor3      = [[Mark Todd (politician)|Mark Todd]]\n| successor3        = \n| term_start3       = 6 May 2010\n| term_end3         = \n| birth_date        = {{Birth date and age|1959|05|14|df=yes}}<ref>{{cite web|url= http://news.bbc.co.uk/democracylive/hi/representatives/profiles/35319.stm |title=Heather Wheeler MP |publisher=BBC |work=BBC Democracy Live |date= |accessdate=25 July 2010}}</ref>\n| birth_place       = [[Norwich]], [[Norfolk]], England<ref>{{cite web |title= Who's Who 2015: WHEELER, Heather |url= http://www.ukwhoswho.com/view/article/oupww/whoswho/U251302/ | website           = ukwhoswho.com | publisher = [[Who's Who (UK)]] }}</ref>\n| death_date        =\n| death_place       =\n| nationality       = British  \n| spouse            = Bob\n| children          = Harriet\n| party             = [[Conservative Party (UK)|Conservatives]]\n| website           = [http://www.heatherwheeler.org.uk/ www.heatherwheeler.org.uk]\n}}\n'''Heather Kay Wheeler'''<ref>{{London Gazette |issue=59418 |pages=8740\u20138740  |date= 13 May 2010 }}</ref> (born 14 May 1959) is a British [[Conservative Party (UK)|Conservative Party]] politician, who was first elected at the [[2010 United Kingdom general election|2010 general election]] as the [[Member of Parliament (United Kingdom)|Member of Parliament]] (MP) for [[South Derbyshire (UK Parliament constituency)|South Derbyshire]], taking the seat from the [[Labour Party (UK)|Labour Party]] after 13 years.<ref name=\"BBC-eln2010\">{{cite news |url=http://www.thisisderbyshire.co.uk/news/Wheeler-wins-turn-South-Derbys-blue-time-13-years/article-2128809-detail/article.html |title=Election 2010: South Derbyshire |work=thisisderbyshire.co.uk |accessdate=7 May 2010}}</ref> She served as [[Parliamentary Under-Secretary of State]] at the [[Ministry of Housing, Communities and Local Government]] from January 2018 to July 2019. She served as the [[Under-Secretary of State for Foreign Affairs|Parliamentary Under-Secretary of State for Asia and the Pacific]] in the [[Second Johnson ministry|Johnson administration]] until her resignation on 13 February 2020 due to family commitments.\n\n==Early life and local government career==\nWheeler, n\u00e9e Wilkinson, was born in Norwich on 14 May 1959. She was brought up and state educated in [[Wandsworth]] and was elected a Conservative member for West Hill ward on [[Wandsworth London Borough Council]] at the age of 22 in May 1982.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.electionscentre.co.uk/wp-content/uploads/2015/06/Wandsworth-1964-2010.pdf|title= Wandsworth Council Election Results 1964-2010 |publisher= Plymouth University|accessdate=12 July 2018}}</ref> After serving a full council term, she married her husband Bob, moving in 1986 to [[Bretby]], South Derbyshire.<ref name=aboutheatherwheeler>{{cite web |url=https://www.heatherwheeler.org.uk/about-heather-wheeler |title=About Heather Wheeler |access-date=23 August 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170406083647/https://www.heatherwheeler.org.uk/about-heather-wheeler |archive-date=6 April 2017 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\nAfter working for Lloyds insurance brokers for 10 years, qualifying by exam as an Associate, she became a member of The Chartered Insurance Institute.<ref name=aboutheatherwheeler/>\n\nWheeler was first elected to [[South Derbyshire District Council]] in 1995 for the safe Conservative seat of Repton. She went on to become leader of the council's Conservative group and became Leader of the Council between 2007-2010. She was successfully re-elected as a councillor for Repton ward until 2011; her daughter Harriet unsuccessfully stood as a Conservative candidate in Swadlincote ward in 2011, whilst husband Bob successfully defended his marginal Linton ward and continued as Leader of the council.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.electionscentre.co.uk/wp-content/uploads/2015/06/South-Derbyshire-1973-2011.pdf|title= South Derbyshire Council Election Results 1973-2011|publisher= Plymouth University |accessdate=12 July 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Parliamentary career==\nWheeler stood unsuccessfully at the [[2001 United Kingdom general election|2001]] and [[2005 United Kingdom general election|2005 general elections]] as her party's candidate for [[Coventry South (UK Parliament constituency)|Coventry South]].<ref name=parliamentbiowheeler/> Wheeler was a member of the Conservative Party's [[A-List (Conservative)|A-List]]<ref>{{cite web | title = Seats and candidates: Where are the original A-Listers now? The 27 who have been selected for target seats | website = conservativehome.blogs.com | publisher = [[ConservativeHome]] | url = http://conservativehome.blogs.com/goldlist/2009/04/where-are-the-original-alisters-now-the-27-who-have-been-selected-for-target-seats.html }}</ref> prior to being selected to contest the [[South Derbyshire (UK Parliament constituency)|South Derbyshire]] constituency. At the [[2010 United Kingdom general election|2010 general election]], she gained the seat from [[Labour Party (UK)|Labour]] with a majority of 7,128; there was a 9.8% swing to the Conservatives. Following her election as a [[Member of Parliament (United Kingdom)|Member of Parliament]] she stood aside as Conservative council group leader. She was re-elected in 2015 and 2017, with the former defying polling that suggested her seat would be vulnerable following the Conservative Government's failure to award a major contract to local train manufacturer Bombardier.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite news|url=http://www.burtonmail.co.uk/heather-wheeler-wins-her-seat-in-south-derbyshire-with-a-comfortable-majority/story-30380598-detail/story.html|title=Heather Wheeler wins her seat in South Derbyshire|date=2017-06-09|work=Burton Mail|access-date=2017-06-10|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://conservativehome.blogs.com/goldlist/2011/08/poll-boosts-labour-hopes-of-ousting-heather-wheeler-mp-on-back-of-siemens-trains-deal.html|title=Poll boosts Labour hopes of ousting Heather Wheeler MP on back of Siemens trains deal|publisher=Conservative Home|accessdate=12 July 2018}}</ref>\n\nIn the [[House of Commons of the United Kingdom|House of Commons]] she sat on the [[Standards and Privileges Committee]], the European Scrutiny Committee and the [[Communities and Local Government Committee]].<ref name=parliamentbiowheeler>{{cite web|title=Heather Wheeler|url=http://www.parliament.uk/biographies/commons/heather-wheeler/4053|website=Parliament UK|accessdate=8 April 2015}}</ref> She was also a member of the [[Public Bill Committee]] for the [[Defence Reform Act 2014]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://services.parliament.uk/bills/2013-14/defencereform/committees/houseofcommonspublicbillcommitteeonthedefencereformbill201314.html|title=House of Commons Public Bill Committee on the Defence Reform Bill 2013-14 |publisher=Parliament.uk |date= |accessdate=17 September 2013}}</ref>\n\nWheeler was one of 79 Conservative MPs who supported a 2011 rebel motion calling for a [[2016 United Kingdom European Union membership referendum|referendum on the European Union]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Rebel MPs: the full list|url=http://www.newstatesman.com/blogs/the-staggers/2011/10/north-mps-south-referendum|accessdate=8 April 2015 | work = [[New Statesman]]|publisher= Progressive Media International |date=25 October 2011}}</ref> She also joined a 2013 rebel amendment expressing regret at not including the referendum in the government's plans.<ref>{{cite news|title=The 114 Tory rebels in EU protest vote|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/worldnews/europe/eu/10060827/The-114-Tory-rebels-in-EU-protest-vote.html|accessdate=8 April 2015|work= [[The Daily Telegraph]] | publisher = [[Telegraph Media Group]] | location = London |date=15 May 2013}}</ref> She subsequently backed the government's plans to hold a referendum in 2017 and opposed a proposal to hold it in 2014.<ref>{{cite web|title=Craig Whittaker: Referendum on the UK's membership of the EU|url=http://www.publicwhip.org.uk/mp.php?mpn=Craig_Whittaker&mpc=Calder_Valley&house=commons&dmp=1027&display=motions|website=Public Whip|accessdate=8 April 2015}}</ref> Wheeler backed Leave in the referendum.<ref>https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-eu-referendum-35616946</ref>\n\nIn January 2018,  Wheeler was appointed as a Parliamentary Under Secretary of State at the Ministry of Housing, Communities and Local Government, with responsibility for homelessness and rough sleeping as well as the private rented and leasehold sectors.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.gov.uk/government/people/heather-wheeler#biography|title=Heather Wheeler MP - GOV.UK|website=www.gov.uk|language=en|access-date=2018-03-18}}</ref>\n\nIn July 2019, Wheeler was appointed as the [[Parliamentary Under-Secretary of State]] for Asia and the Pacific at the [[Foreign and Commonwealth Office]].  She was dismissed in February 2020.\n\n==Controversies==\nIn August 2016, following the [[2016 Rio Olympics]], the European Union social media account shared a modified medals table showing its combined member states in first place. Wheeler tweeted in response that the [[British Empire]] had won the 2016 Rio Olympics along with a map of former imperial territories.<ref>{{citation|url = https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/politics/conservative-mp-heather-wheeler-brexit-british-empire-won-the-olympics-a7204546.html | title = 'British Empire' won the Olympics, claims Conservative MP Heather Wheeler | last = Withnall | first = Adam | date = August 23, 2016 | work = [[The Independent]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Muir|first=Rod|url=https://www.totalpolitics.com/articles/news/conservative-mp-celebrates-performance-%E2%80%98british-empire%E2%80%99-rio|title=Conservative MP celebrates performance of 'British Empire' in Rio|work=Total Politics|date=23 August 2016|accessdate=23 August 2016}}</ref> Her comments were attacked by critics as being \"deeply offensive to so many people and their ancestors\" and \"insensitive and ignorant\", but she rejected calls to apologise, instead arguing that her comments were \"tongue-in-cheek\".<ref name=\"BBC\">{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-derbyshire-37163416|publisher=BBC|title=MP Heather Wheeler sparks Twitter backlash with British Empire post|accessdate=12 July 2018}}</ref>\n\nIn September 2017, Wheeler was criticised for claiming expenses for first-class tickets when she travelled by rail, despite official guidance from the [[Independent Parliamentary Standards Authority]] \u2013 set up in the wake of the 2009 expenses scandal \u2013 saying politicians should \u201cconsider value for money\u201d when booking tickets. However, she argued that her claims were permissible within the expenses rules and that the first-class tickets were cheaper than some standard class tickets available.<ref>{{cite news|title=Three Tory Derbyshire MPs claim \u00a310k on first-class train tickets in a year|url=https://www.derbytelegraph.co.uk/news/local-news/three-tory-derbyshire-mps-claim-449373|work=Derby Telegraph|accessdate=12 July 2018|author=|date=8 September 2017}}</ref>\n\nIn March 2018, following her promotion to a Government position with responsibility for homelessness, Wheeler told ''[[The Guardian]]'' newspaper that she did not know why the number of rough sleepers had increased in recent years. Wheeler rejected the suggestion that welfare reforms and council cuts relating to her Government had contributed to the rise.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/society/2018/mar/18/homelessness-minister-heather-wheeler-rough-sleeping-housing-first|title=Homelessness minister: I don't know why rough sleeper numbers are up|last=Brooks|first=Libby|date=2018-03-18|website=the Guardian|language=en|access-date=2018-03-18}}</ref> Earlier in the same month, Wheeler promised to resign if the number of people rough sleeping got worse while she was in office.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/av/uk-politics-43288585/heather-wheeler-to-resign-if-rough-sleeping-gets-worse|title=Homelessness minister gives herself ultimatum|website=BBC News|language=en-GB|access-date=2018-03-18}}</ref>\n\nIn June 2019, it was revealed that in October 2017, three months before she became minister, Wheeler described rough sleepers in her constituency as \u201cthe traditional type, old tinkers, knife-cutters wandering through\u201d. In response, Wheeler faced calls to resign from Stephen Robertson, the chief executive of the [[The Big Issue|Big Issue Foundation]] and a representative from a leading national charity which works on behalf of Gypsies, Travellers and Roma described the language as \u201cdisgraceful\u201d. Wheeler issued an apology for her \u201cinappropriate language\u201d, and said it \u201cis not at all representative of the great cultural contribution and rich heritage that the Gypsy, Roma and Traveller communities make to this country\u201d.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/society/2019/jun/20/homelessness-minister-accused-of-racist-remarks-in-email|title=Homelessness minister accused of racist remarks about rough sleepers|last=Greenfield|first=Patrick|date=2019-06-20|work=The Guardian|access-date=2019-06-20|last2=Marsh|first2=Sarah|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077|last3=McDevitt|first3=Johnny}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nWheeler's late husband Bob was a Conservative councillor who was made leader of South Derbyshire District Council in 2010, after his wife stepped down from the role on becoming an MP. He stood down as Leader of the Council in January 2018; he died in late 2018.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://south-derbys.cmis.uk.com/south-derbys/Councillors/tabid/63/ctl/ViewCMIS_Person/mid/383/id/5/ScreenMode/Alphabetical/Default.aspx|title=Cllr Robert Wheeler|publisher=South Derbyshire Council|accessdate=12 July 2018}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category}}\n*[http://www.heatherwheeler.org.uk/ Official website]\n*{{UK MP links | parliament =  heather-wheeler/4053 | publicwhip = heather_wheeler | theywork = heather_wheeler}}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-par|uk}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Mark Todd (politician)|Mark Todd]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Member of Parliament (United Kingdom)|Member of Parliament]] for [[South Derbyshire (UK Parliament constituency)|South Derbyshire]]|years=[[2010 United Kingdom general election|2010]]\u2013present}}\n{{s-inc}} \n{{s-end}}\n\n{{East Midlands Conservative Party MPs}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Wheeler, Heather}}\n[[Category:1959 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Conservative Party (UK) MPs for English constituencies]]\n[[Category:Councillors in the London Borough of Wandsworth]]\n[[Category:Councillors in Derbyshire]]\n[[Category:Members of the Parliament of the United Kingdom for constituencies in Derbyshire]]\n[[Category:Female members of the Parliament of the United Kingdom for English constituencies]]\n[[Category:People educated at Grey Coat Hospital]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 2010\u20132015]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 2015\u20132017]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 2017\u20132019]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 2019\u2013]]\n[[Category:21st-century British women politicians]]\n", "name_user": "Iridescent", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eEarly life and local government career:Cleanup andtypo fixing,typo(s) fixed: 2007-2010 \u2192 2007\u20132010", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Heather_Wheeler"}
{"title_page": "David Ward (British politician)", "text_new": "{{For|the General Secretary of the Communication Workers\u2019 Union|Dave Ward (trade unionist)}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=January 2015}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n| image = Mr David Ward MP.jpg\n| honorific-prefix =\n| name = David Ward\n| honorific-suffix =  \n| office = [[Member of Parliament (United Kingdom)|Member of Parliament]] <br /> for [[Bradford East (UK Parliament constituency)|Bradford East]]\n| parliament = \n| majority =\n| predecessor =  Constituency created\n| successor = [[Imran Hussain (British politician)|Imran Hussain]]\n| term_start = 6 May 2010\n| term_end =  30 March 2015\n|office3          = Member of the [[City of Bradford Metropolitan District Council]] for <br />[[Bolton and Undercliffe]] Ward\n|term_start3      = 5 May 2016\n|term_end3        = \n|predecessor3     = Tracey Leeming (LibDem)\n|successor3       = \n|majority3         = 874 (21.9%)\n\n| birth_date = {{Birth date and age|1953|06|24|df=yes}}\n| birth_place = [[Lincoln, England|Lincoln]], [[Lincolnshire]], England\n| death_date =\n| death_place =\n| nationality = [[United Kingdom|British]]\n| spouse = Jackie\n| party = [[Independent politician|Independent]] \n| relations =\n| children = 2 sons\n| residence = \n| alma_mater = \n| occupation = Politician\n| profession =\n| religion = \n| signature =\n| website = \n| footnotes =\n}}\n'''David Ward''' (born 24 June 1953) is a [[United Kingdom|British]] politician who was elected as the [[Liberal Democrats (UK)|Liberal Democrat]] [[Member of Parliament (United Kingdom)|Member of Parliament]] (MP) for [[Bradford East (UK Parliament constituency)|Bradford East]] at the [[2010 United Kingdom general election|2010 general election]].<ref name=\"BBC-eln2010\">{{cite news |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/shared/election2010/results/constituency/a58.stm |title=Election 2010: Bradford East |work=[[BBC News]] |accessdate=7 May 2010 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170904232258/http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/shared/election2010/results/constituency/a58.stm |archive-date=4 September 2017 |url-status=live }}</ref> He lost his seat in [[2015 United Kingdom general election|2015]] when  the [[Labour Party (UK)|Labour Party]] candidate [[Imran Hussain (British politician)|Imran Hussain]] defeated him by 7,000 votes.<ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/politics/constituencies/E14000587 | title=Bradford East Parliamentary constituency | work=[[BBC News]] | accessdate=7 May 2015 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190508081529/https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/politics/constituencies/E14000587 | archive-date=8 May 2019 | url-status=live }}</ref> Before his election to parliament, he was a councillor in Bradford for 26 years, and returned to local politics in 2016.<ref name=\"Young\">{{cite news|last=Young|first=Chris|url=http://www.thetelegraphandargus.co.uk/news/14477148.Former_Bradford_East_MP_returns_to_local_politics_after_winning_seat_on_Bradford_Council/|title=Former Bradford East MP David Ward returns to local politics after winning seat on Bradford Council|work=[[Telegraph & Argus]]|location=Bradford|date=6 May 2016|accessdate=25 April 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180804051000/http://www.thetelegraphandargus.co.uk/news/14477148.Former_Bradford_East_MP_returns_to_local_politics_after_winning_seat_on_Bradford_Council/|archive-date=4 August 2018|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nIn July 2013, he was suspended from the [[List of United Kingdom Liberal Democrat MPs (2010\u2013)|Liberal Democrats Parliamentary party]] until September 2013, after questioning the continuing existence of the state of [[Israel]] and refusing to apologise for his remarks.<ref name=\"Parliament\">{{cite news | url=http://findyourmp.parliament.uk/constituencies/bradford-east | title=Find your MP \u2013 David Ward | work=Parliament UK | accessdate=6 November 2013 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141029230323/http://findyourmp.parliament.uk/constituencies/bradford-east | archive-date=29 October 2014 | url-status=live }}</ref><ref name=\"Whip\">{{cite news|last=Syal|first=Rajeev|url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2013/jul/18/david-ward-whip-israel-apartheid-state|title=Lib Dems withdraw party whip from MP David Ward over Israel comment|work=[[The Guardian]]|date=18 July 2013|accessdate=22 July 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130730123836/http://www.theguardian.com/politics/2013/jul/18/david-ward-whip-israel-apartheid-state|archive-date=30 July 2013|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\"Suspension\">{{cite news | last=O'Donoghue | first=Gary | url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-23361380 | title=MP David Ward has Lib Dem whip withdrawn over Israel comment | work=[[BBC News]] | date=18 July 2013 | accessdate=22 July 2013 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130721214319/http://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-23361380 | archive-date=21 July 2013 | url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n==Early life and career==\n===Early life: lecturer and Bradford City F.C.===\nDavid Ward was born in [[Lincoln, England|Lincoln]]; his father was a plumber, and his mother worked on farms, in a canning factory and then in a care home.<ref name=\"Edemariam\">{{cite news|last=Edemariam|first=Aida|url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2013/feb/06/david-ward-not-racist|title=David Ward: 'The solid ground I stand on is that I am not a racist'|work=The Guardian|date=6 February 2013|accessdate=25 April 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170426063750/https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2013/feb/06/david-ward-not-racist|archive-date=26 April 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> He attended [[Boston Grammar School]] in [[Boston, Lincolnshire]], and then qualified as a member of the [[Chartered Institute of Public Finance and Accountancy]] (CIPFA) in 1976.<ref name=\"bradfordbusinessconference.co.uk\">{{cite web|title=Business Innovation in Bradford \u2013 Panel Q&A with Key Bradford Business Leaders|url=http://bradfordbusinessconference.co.uk/seminar-shining-lights.php|accessdate=3 October 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120902145354/http://www.bradfordbusinessconference.co.uk/seminar-shining-lights.php|archive-date=2 September 2012|url-status=dead}}</ref> He attended the [[University of Bradford]] Management Centre to complete an [[Master of Business Administration|MBA]] and an [[Master of Philosophy|MPhil]] by research.<ref name=\"bradfordbusinessconference.co.uk\"/><ref>{{cite news|title=University of Bradford Guide|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/education/universityeducation/universities-and-colleges/8473460/University-of-Bradford-guide.html|location=London|work=The Daily Telegraph|first=Charlotte|last=Lytton|date=17 April 2013|access-date=3 April 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120531224621/http://www.telegraph.co.uk/education/universityeducation/universities-and-colleges/8473460/University-of-Bradford-guide.html|archive-date=31 May 2012|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nHe began working at Leeds Polytechnic (later [[Leeds Metropolitan University]]) in 1985, remaining there for the next 18 years as a Principal Lecturer in finance and strategic management, and as a Business Development Manager in charge of External Income Generation.<ref name=\"pumr.pascalobservatory.org\">{{cite web|title=Pascal Universities for a Modern Renaissance|url=http://pumr.pascalobservatory.org/pascalnow/pascal-projects/pumr/david-ward|access-date=3 October 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160304042201/http://pumr.pascalobservatory.org/pascalnow/pascal-projects/pumr/david-ward|archive-date=4 March 2016|url-status=live}}</ref> In 1996, he obtained an [[Master of Science|MSc]] from the [[University of Leicester]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Lib Dems \u2013 Who We Are|url=http://www.libdems.org.uk/parliamentary_candidates_detail.aspx?name=David_Ward_MP&pPK=17eeef9e-e7a3-42d5-bd13-5bbb2151ec57|archive-url=https://archive.today/20121225023520/http://www.libdems.org.uk/parliamentary_candidates_detail.aspx?name=David_Ward_MP&pPK=17eeef9e-e7a3-42d5-bd13-5bbb2151ec57|url-status=dead|archive-date=2012-12-25}}</ref>\n\nIn July 2004, he was seconded from Leeds Metropolitan University to work at [[Bradford City Football Club]] on a full-time basis<ref name=\"pumr.pascalobservatory.org\"/> to help the club to build links with the local community  and to engage with the predominantly Pakistani-Bangladeshi community that surrounds the club in Manningham.<ref>{{cite web|title=The Times Higher Awards 2006 \u2013 The Shortlisted Candidates (Page 5)|url=http://www.bris.ac.uk/pwe/thes2006award|access-date=4 October 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20081204084436/http://www.bris.ac.uk/pwe/thes2006award|archive-date=4 December 2008|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Universities' Third Mission|url=http://pascalobservatory.org/pascalnow/term/pascal-themes/universities-third-mission?page=7|access-date=4 October 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160602085139/http://pascalobservatory.org/pascalnow/term/pascal-themes/universities-third-mission?page=7|archive-date=2 June 2016|url-status=live}}</ref> It is now host to a positive lifestyle centre, which has run programmes for more than 11,000 school children in the past seven years. There is also the football club in the community scheme, which works with 130 of Bradford's schools.<ref>{{cite web|title=David Ward MP's Maiden Speech|url=http://www.libdemvoice.org/david-ward-mps-maiden-speech-19822.html|access-date=20 October 2011|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120405160108/http://www.libdemvoice.org/david-ward-mps-maiden-speech-19822.html|archive-date=5 April 2012|url-status=live}}</ref> On 5 May 2012, the football museum{{which|date=May 2016}} was closed down.<ref>{{cite web|title=bantamspast \u2013 a kind of ending|url=http://www.bantamspast.co.uk/index.php?id=1876810492935767147|access-date=3 October 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160308203314/http://bantamspast.co.uk/index.php?id=1876810492935767147|archive-date=8 March 2016|url-status=dead}}</ref> Work began to turn the museum into a free school to be run by the One in a Million charity,<ref>{{cite web|title=Working under Way On Free School|url=http://www.oneinamillion.org.uk/work-under-way-on-free-school/|access-date=3 October 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121117105522/http://www.oneinamillion.org.uk/work-under-way-on-free-school/|archive-date=17 November 2012|url-status=live}}</ref> but a week before the start of the school term in September the funding was pulled for the school.<ref>{{cite web|title=Free School Funding Pulled|url=http://www.oneinamillion.org.uk/free-school-funding-pulled/|access-date=3 October 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121004105059/http://www.oneinamillion.org.uk/free-school-funding-pulled/|archive-date=4 October 2012|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Bradford free school loses funding one week before opening|url=https://www.theguardian.com/education/2012/aug/28/bradford-free-school-government-funding|location=London|work=The Guardian|first=Helen|last=Nugent|date=28 August 2012|access-date=11 December 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160916150454/https://www.theguardian.com/education/2012/aug/28/bradford-free-school-government-funding|archive-date=16 September 2016|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Parents rage as Michael Gove pulls free school funding days before opening|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/education/education-news/parents-rage-as-michael-gove-pulls-free-school-funding-days-before-opening-8082614.html|location=London|work=The Independent|first=Rob|last=Hastings|date=28 August 2012|access-date=26 August 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160603030013/http://www.independent.co.uk/news/education/education-news/parents-rage-as-michael-gove-pulls-free-school-funding-days-before-opening-8082614.html|archive-date=3 June 2016|url-status=live}}</ref> Ward called the move to pull the funding for the school as being \"callous, cruel and quite stupid...and incredibly unfair on the parents and children and One in a Million.\"<ref>{{cite news|title=Bradford free school One In A Million has funding cut|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-leeds-19396745|work=BBC News|date=28 August 2012|access-date=20 June 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141021170544/http://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-leeds-19396745|archive-date=21 October 2014|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=David Ward MP speaks about cruel decision to pull funding for free school in Bradford|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=2F1GQwUvsCk|access-date=25 November 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160409162902/https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=2F1GQwUvsCk|archive-date=9 April 2016|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n===Bradford public career===\nWard was first elected to [[City of Bradford Metropolitan District Council|Bradford Metropolitan District Councillor]] in 1984, and served for 26 years until he was elected to Parliament in 2010.<ref name=\"Young\"/><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.thetelegraphandargus.co.uk/news/8074215.display/|title=Former civic leader dies|work=[[Telegraph & Argus]]|location=Bradford|date=20 August 1998|accessdate=25 April 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170426064812/http://www.thetelegraphandargus.co.uk/news/8074215.display/|archive-date=26 April 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> His specialist area was education;<ref name=\"Edemariam\"/> he was a governor for 30 years at several special, primary and secondary schools<ref>{{cite web|title=Schools' joy over \u00a3500,000 reprieve|url=http://www.thetelegraphandargus.co.uk/news/local/localbrad/4090511.Schools____joy_over___500_000_reprieve/|accessdate=4 October 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130708142800/http://www.thetelegraphandargus.co.uk/news/local/localbrad/4090511.Schools____joy_over___500_000_reprieve/|archive-date=8 July 2013|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Schools to pay back \u00a3466,000|url=http://www.thetelegraphandargus.co.uk/news/local/localbrad/3760856.Schools_to_pay_back___466_000/|accessdate=4 October 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130708143843/http://www.thetelegraphandargus.co.uk/news/local/localbrad/3760856.Schools_to_pay_back___466_000/|archive-date=8 July 2013|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=College drops plans to become academy|url=http://www.thetelegraphandargus.co.uk/archive/2006/09/29/bradford_education+(bradford_education)/946201.College_drops_plans_to_become_academy/|access-date=4 October 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130708144826/http://www.thetelegraphandargus.co.uk/archive/2006/09/29/bradford_education+(bradford_education)/946201.College_drops_plans_to_become_academy/|archive-date=8 July 2013|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Clawback amnesty declared on school cash|url=http://davidward.org.uk/en/article/2009/150973/clawback-amnesty-declared-on-school-cash|accessdate=4 October 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130103083612/http://davidward.org.uk/en/article/2009/150973/clawback-amnesty-declared-on-school-cash|archive-date=3 January 2013|url-status=dead}}</ref> and held the Education Portfolio on the council for four years.<ref>{{cite web|title=Lost exam papers blow to college|url=http://www.thetelegraphandargus.co.uk/news/local/localbrad/1226713.Lost_exam_papers_blow_to_college/|accessdate=4 October 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130708145717/http://www.thetelegraphandargus.co.uk/news/local/localbrad/1226713.Lost_exam_papers_blow_to_college/|archive-date=8 July 2013|url-status=live}}</ref> Whilst holding this post he visited [[Kashmir]] with a Primary school and Secondary school headteacher to try to forge links with local schools.<ref>{{cite web|title=David Ward MP speech on Maqbool Butt Shaheed Day 2012|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=eLHmCWXjPmM&t=4m9s|access-date=25 November 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170817095922/https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=eLHmCWXjPmM&t=4m9s|archive-date=17 August 2017|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nIn 2006, he worked with others to organise the first-ever community day for the Manningham area, and his work at the club was acknowledged later that year when Leeds Metropolitan University won the <!-- Name change dates from 2008. -->''[[Times Higher Education|Times Higher Education Supplement]]'' Award for \"Outstanding contribution to the local community\".<ref name=\"upbeat.eu.com\">{{cite web|title=Upbeat \u2013 Community Unity in Bradford|url=http://www.upbeat.eu.com/casestudy/success1/|access-date=4 October 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090420083454/http://upbeat.eu.com/casestudy/success1/|archive-date=20 April 2009|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nThe charity set up by Ward focused mainly on anti-racist interventions and community cohesion events,<ref name=\"upbeat.eu.com\"/> and he continues to support organisations such as the Sports Campaign Against Racism (SCAR).<ref>Ward, D. (26 September 2012) [https://twitter.com/DavidWardMP/status/250922340597243905 \"Having a meeting now w/ anti-racist campaigners about their work in #Bradford & how I can support them\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150130180659/https://twitter.com/DavidWardMP/status/250922340597243905 |date=30 January 2015 }} ''Twitter.com''</ref>\n\nHe was the Liberal Democrat candidate at the [[1990 Bradford North by-election|Bradford North by-election in 1990]], and after his defeat he stood again in [[Bradford North (UK Parliament constituency)|Bradford North]] at the general elections in [[1992 United Kingdom general election|1992]], [[2001 United Kingdom general election|2001]] and [[2005 United Kingdom general election|2005]].<ref>{{cite news|title=UK Political Database \u2013 Bradford East|url=http://ukpolitics.telegraph.co.uk/Bradford+East|accessdate=3 October 2012|location=London|work=The Daily Telegraph|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100424223338/http://ukpolitics.telegraph.co.uk/Bradford+East|archive-date=24 April 2010|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nIn 2005, he came second, 3,500 votes behind the incumbent [[Labour Party (UK)|Labour Party]] MP [[Terry Rooney]]. Bradford North was abolished in [[Boundary Commissions (United Kingdom)|boundary changes]] for the [[2010 United Kingdom general election|general election in May 2010]]; Ward was elected for the new Bradford East seat, with a majority of 365 votes over Rooney.\n\n==Parliamentary career==\nHe was a member of the Business, Innovation and Skills Select Committee from June 2010 to June 2012, when he became a member of the Education Select Committee.<ref>{{cite web|title=www.parliament.uk \u2013 MP biographies|url=http://www.parliament.uk/biographies/commons/david-ward/37625|accessdate=3 October 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121018034141/http://www.parliament.uk/biographies/commons/david-ward/37625|archive-date=18 October 2012|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\n===Controversies===\n\n====Comments on the Holocaust====\nOn 25 January 2013, the Liberal Democrats reprimanded Ward for his \"use of language\" in a statement on his website about [[Israel]]'s treatment of [[Palestinians]], which he put on his blog the same day that he signed a memorial book in the [[House of Commons of the United Kingdom|House of Commons]] marking [[Holocaust Memorial Day (UK)|Holocaust Memorial Day]].<ref name=\"Byers\">{{cite news|last=Byers|first=David|url=https://www.thetimes.co.uk/article/liberal-democrat-mp-david-ward-in-row-over-holocaust-remarks-g9bhnkrwffw|title=Liberal Democrat MP David Ward in row over Holocaust remarks|work=The Times|date=26 January 2013|accessdate=26 April 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170427100545/https://www.thetimes.co.uk/article/liberal-democrat-mp-david-ward-in-row-over-holocaust-remarks-g9bhnkrwffw|archive-date=27 April 2017|url-status=live}}{{subscription required}}</ref> He wrote there that he honoured \"those who were persecuted and killed during the Holocaust\" but also commented: \"Having visited Auschwitz twice \u2013 once with my family and once with local schools \u2013 I am saddened that the Jews, who suffered unbelievable levels of persecution during the Holocaust, could within a few years of liberation from the death camps be inflicting atrocities on Palestinians in the new State of Israel and continue to do so on a daily basis in the West Bank and Gaza\".<ref name=\"Byers\"/><ref name=\"Condemn\">{{cite news | url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-21194991 | title=Lib Dems condemn MP's criticism of Israel ahead of Holocaust Memorial Day | work=[[BBC News]] | date=25 January 2013 | accessdate=25 January 2013 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130125204654/http://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-21194991 | archive-date=25 January 2013 | url-status=live }}</ref> \"It appears that the suffering by the Jews has not transformed their views on how others should be treated\", he said in a later statement.<ref name=\"Byers\"/>\n\nKaren Pollock, chief executive of the [[Holocaust Educational Trust]], said: \"Mr Ward has deliberately abused the memory of the Holocaust, causing deep pain and offence \u2013 these comments are sickening and unacceptable and have no place in British politics\". Jon Benjamin, chief executive of the [[Board of Deputies of British Jews]], said: \"We are outraged and shocked at these offensive comments about Jewish victims of the Holocaust and the suggestion that Jews should have learned a lesson from the experience.\"<ref name=\"Condemn\"/>\n\nIn an updated blog entry on 26 January he stated he had \"never for a moment intended to criticise or offend the Jewish people as a whole, either as a race or as a people of faith, and apologise sincerely for the unintended offence which my words caused\" and stated that while his \"criticisms of actions since 1948 in the Palestinian territories in the name of the State of Israel remain as strong as ever\" he was \"trying to make clear that everybody needs to learn the lessons of the Holocaust\".<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/politics/liberaldemocrats/9829180/Lib-Dem-MP-apologises-over-attack-on-the-Jews.html|title=Lib Dem MP apologises over attack on 'the Jews'|work=The Daily Telegraph|date=26 January 2013|accessdate=26 April 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170427101506/http://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/politics/liberaldemocrats/9829180/Lib-Dem-MP-apologises-over-attack-on-the-Jews.html|archive-date=27 April 2017|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Gray|first=Sadie|url=https://www.thetimes.co.uk/article/holocaust-row-mp-issues-public-apology-dkp7n52zh7v|title=Holocaust row MP issues public apology|work=The Times|date=26 January 2013|accessdate=26 April 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170427100026/https://www.thetimes.co.uk/article/holocaust-row-mp-issues-public-apology-dkp7n52zh7v|archive-date=27 April 2017|url-status=live}}{{subscription required}}</ref>\n\nIn a meeting with [[Alistair Carmichael]], the Liberal Democrats chief whip, Ward was told he would face disciplinary action if he repeated these words.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-leeds-21240036|title=Lib-Dem David Ward MP censured over Israel criticism|publisher=BBC News|date=28 January 2013|accessdate=26 April 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170507170907/http://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-leeds-21240036|archive-date=7 May 2017|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Lipman|first=Jennifer|url=https://www.thejc.com/news/uk-news/david-ward-responds-to-holocaust-comments-1.41180|title=David Ward responds to Holocaust comments|work=The Jewish Chronicle|date=31 January 2013|accessdate=26 April 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170427095811/https://www.thejc.com/news/uk-news/david-ward-responds-to-holocaust-comments-1.41180|archive-date=27 April 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> A meeting Ward was to attend with the [[Liberal Democrat Friends of Israel]] in February 2013 over his use of language did not occur because he had not removed contentious phrasing from his website.<ref>{{cite news|last=Dysch|first=Marcus|url=https://www.thejc.com/news/uk-news/liberal-democrats-in-turmoil-over-david-ward-1.46277|title=Liberal Democrats in turmoil over David Ward|work=The Jewish Chronicle|date=27 June 2013|accessdate=26 April 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170427003721/https://www.thejc.com/news/uk-news/liberal-democrats-in-turmoil-over-david-ward-1.46277|archive-date=27 April 2017|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nIn an interview with [[Aida Edemariam]] of ''[[The Guardian]]'' in February 2013, Ward said: \"There is a huge operation out there, a machine almost, which is designed to protect the state of Israel from criticism. And that comes into play very, very quickly\" with the result \"I end up looking at\" the vocabulary \"I should use\" which \"is winning, for them. Because what I want to talk about is the fundamental question of how can they do this, and how can they be allowed to do this\".<ref name=\"Edemariam\"/>\n\n====Comments on Israel====\nWard [[Twitter|tweeted]] on 13 July 2013: \"Am I wrong or are am I right? At long last the Zionists are losing the battle \u2013 how long can the apartheid State of Israel last?\" He refused to apologise for questioning Israel's right to exist, and was suspended from the Liberal Democrats parliamentary party for three months.<ref name=\"Whip\"/><ref>{{cite news|last=Morris|first=Nigel|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/politics/liberal-democrats-suspend-mp-david-ward-over-israel-comments-on-holocaust-day-8717552.html|title=Liberal Democrats suspend MP David Ward over Israel comments on Holocaust Day|work=The Independent|date=18 July 2013|accessdate=25 April 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170426063337/http://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/politics/liberal-democrats-suspend-mp-david-ward-over-israel-comments-on-holocaust-day-8717552.html|archive-date=26 April 2017|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nThe Liberal Democrats' chief whip Alistair Carmichael reminded him of his failure to keep a previous promise to use \"proportionate and precise\" language when commenting on Israel,<ref name=\"Rutter\">{{cite news|last=Rutter|first=Tamsin|url=https://www.theguardian.com/uk-news/the-northerner/2013/jul/22/david-ward-israel-comments-bradford|title=Bradford Muslim group to show support for MP David Ward|work=[[The Guardian]]|date=22 July 2013|accessdate=26 April 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170426063626/https://www.theguardian.com/uk-news/the-northerner/2013/jul/22/david-ward-israel-comments-bradford|archive-date=26 April 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> writing: \"These interventions cause considerable offence rather than addressing questions of political substance about the plight of the Palestinian people and the right of Israel's citizens to live a life free of violence\".<ref name=\"Mason180713\">{{cite news|last=Mason|first=Rowena|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/politics/liberaldemocrats/10188329/Lib-Dems-suspend-David-Ward-as-MP-over-Israel-tweet.html|title=Lib Dems suspend David Ward as MP over Israel tweet|work=The Daily Telegraph|date=18 July 2013|accessdate=26 April 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170427004720/http://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/politics/liberaldemocrats/10188329/Lib-Dems-suspend-David-Ward-as-MP-over-Israel-tweet.html|archive-date=27 April 2017|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Craig|first=Jon|url=http://news.sky.com/story/david-ward-in-row-after-zionist-tweet-10439857|title=David Ward In Row After '#Zionist' Tweet|publisher=Sky News|date=18 July 2013|accessdate=26 April 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170427100030/http://news.sky.com/story/david-ward-in-row-after-zionist-tweet-10439857|archive-date=27 April 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> Jonathan Arkush, vice-president of the Board of Deputies of British Jews, described the decision to take away Ward's party whip as \"too little, too late\" and \"an empty gesture\" because of the parliamentary recess.<ref>{{cite news|last=Dysch|first=Marcus|url=https://www.thejc.com/news/uk-news/liberal-democrats-suspend-whip-from-david-ward-1.47009|title=Liberal Democrats suspend whip from David Ward|work=The Jewish Chronicle|date=18 July 2013|accessdate=26 April 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170427095808/https://www.thejc.com/news/uk-news/liberal-democrats-suspend-whip-from-david-ward-1.47009|archive-date=27 April 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> Parliament was due to sit for only  two weeks in September 2013 before the end of his suspension.<ref name=\"Mason180713\"/> Ward objected to his suspension believing his views are widely shared. The [[Respect Party|Respect]] MP for [[Bradford West (UK Parliament constituency)|Bradford West]], [[George Galloway]], defended Ward against his suspension, as did several Muslim activists in his constituency.<ref name=\"Rutter\"/>\n\n====Comments on the Board of Deputies====\nIn November 2013, after Ward had said that it is \"a shame there isn\u2019t a powerful, well-funded Board of Deputies for [[Romani people|Roma]]\", an editorial in ''[[The Jewish Chronicle]]'' described his comments as \"a clear restatement of the most basic antisemitic theme of all \u2014 that wealthy Jews buy up power\" and said that the Liberal Democrats' had goven a \"contemptible response\" with their inaction.<ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.thejc.com/comment/leaders/libdem-s-inaction-over-david-ward-is-contemptible-1.51120| title=LibDem's inaction over David Ward is contemptible| work=[[The Jewish Chronicle]]| date=22 November 2013| accessdate=26 April 2017| archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170427095929/https://www.thejc.com/comment/leaders/libdem-s-inaction-over-david-ward-is-contemptible-1.51120| archive-date=27 April 2017| url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n====Comments on Hamas rockets====\nWard [[twitter|tweeted]] in July 2014 about the ongoing [[Operation Protective Edge|Israeli conflict in Gaza]] suggesting that if he lived in Gaza, he would fire rockets at Israel: \"The big question is \u2013 if I lived in #Gaza would I fire a rocket? \u2013 probably yes\". Interviewed on [[BBC Radio 5 Live]], he initially refused to apologise.<ref name=\"BBC220714\">{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-28424396|title=Lib Dem MP David Ward criticised over Gaza tweets|publisher=BBC News|date=22 July 2014|accessdate=26 April 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170616204155/http://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-28424396|archive-date=16 June 2017|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nWard was condemned by other politicians. [[Grant Shapps]], the [[Chairman of the Conservative Party]], called the tweet \"essentially [an] incitement to violence\" and \"completely irresponsible\". Shapps urged him to delete the comment.<ref name=\"BBC220714\"/><ref>{{cite news|last=Mason|first=Rowena|url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2014/jul/22/david-ward-gaza-rocket-tweet|title=Lib Dem MP David Ward facing disciplinary action for Gaza tweets|work=The Guardian|date=22 July 2014|accessdate=26 April 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170422040223/https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2014/jul/22/david-ward-gaza-rocket-tweet|archive-date=22 April 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> A Liberal Democrat spokesperson called the tweet \"vile and crass\"; the party leader Nick Clegg had called for peace in Israel and Gaza.<ref>{{cite news|last=Datoo|first=Siraj|url=https://www.buzzfeed.com/sirajdatoo/liberal-democrat-mp-set-to-be-disciplined-for-gaza-tweets|title=Liberal Democrat MP Criticised For Saying He Would Fire A Rocket If He Lived In Gaza|work=Buzzfeed|date=23 July 2014|accessdate=26 April 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170423062130/https://www.buzzfeed.com/sirajdatoo/liberal-democrat-mp-set-to-be-disciplined-for-gaza-tweets|archive-date=23 April 2017|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Coates|first=Sam|url=https://www.thetimes.co.uk/article/lib-dem-mps-vile-gaza-tweets-attacked-by-party-xfwww3kb95c|title=Lib Dem MP's 'vile' Gaza tweets attacked by party|work=The Times|date=23 July 2014|accessdate=26 April 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170427100217/https://www.thetimes.co.uk/article/lib-dem-mps-vile-gaza-tweets-attacked-by-party-xfwww3kb95c|archive-date=27 April 2017|url-status=live}}{{subscription required}}</ref> Gavin Stollar, chair of the Liberal Democrats Friends of Israel, said Ward was \"an ignorant political opportunist\" who \"is neither a Liberal nor a Democrat\".<ref>{{cite news|last=Rashty|first=Sandy|url=https://www.thejc.com/news/uk-news/lib-dems-will-discipline-david-ward-over-gaza-tweet-1.55832|title=Lib Dems will discipline David Ward over Gaza tweet|work=The Jewish Chronicle|date=23 July 2014|accessdate=26 April 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170427003829/https://www.thejc.com/news/uk-news/lib-dems-will-discipline-david-ward-over-gaza-tweet-1.55832|archive-date=27 April 2017|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nAn apology was issued under his name by his party in late July.<ref>{{cite news|last=Savage|first=Michael|url=https://www.thetimes.co.uk/article/lib-dem-mp-david-ward-backs-down-over-vile-gaza-tweets-nvtmp78m63x|title=Lib Dem MP David Ward backs down over 'vile' Gaza tweets|work=The Times|date=23 July 2014|accessdate=26 April 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170427100537/https://www.thetimes.co.uk/article/lib-dem-mp-david-ward-backs-down-over-vile-gaza-tweets-nvtmp78m63x|archive-date=27 April 2017|url-status=live}}{{subscription required}}</ref> \"I utterly condemn the violence on both sides in Israel and Gaza\" he said, and \"while I defend the right of Israel to exist and defend itself, I will continue to speak out for the rights of the Palestinian people\".<ref name=\"Savage240714\">{{cite news|last=Savage|first=Michael|url=https://www.thetimes.co.uk/article/lib-dem-mp-in-gaza-rockets-row-25vhbsjv8w3|title=Lib Dem MP in Gaza rockets row|work=The Times|date=24 July 2014|accessdate=26 April 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170427100403/https://www.thetimes.co.uk/article/lib-dem-mp-in-gaza-rockets-row-25vhbsjv8w3|archive-date=27 April 2017|url-status=live}}{{subscription required}}</ref> In a response, the Board of Deputies said: \"This morning's 'spin' in no way negates the fact that David Ward has deliberately placed himself outside the party\u2019s core beliefs and values. We have seen Ward apologise and receive rebuke before, to no avail\".<ref name=\"Savage240714\"/>\n\nThe following month, it emerged Ward would not face any disciplinary action. The party's chief whip, by now [[Don Foster, Baron Foster of Bath|Don Foster]], said the comment had not brought the party into disrepute, nor was it antisemitic. Ward had assured Foster \"he would do all he could to ensure comments he made would be in a form that would be difficult to misinterpret\".<ref>{{cite news|last=Dysch|first=Marcus|url=https://www.thejc.com/news/uk-news/lib-dems-won-t-discipline-david-ward-over-gaza-rocket-tweet-1.56133|title=Lib Dems won't discipline David Ward over Gaza rocket tweet|work=The Jewish Chronicle|date=13 August 2014|accessdate=26 April 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170427003826/https://www.thejc.com/news/uk-news/lib-dems-won-t-discipline-david-ward-over-gaza-rocket-tweet-1.56133|archive-date=27 April 2017|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n====Comments following ''Charlie Hebdo'' attack====\nDuring the [[republican marches]] in January 2015, following the [[Charlie Hebdo shooting|''Charlie Hebdo'' shooting]] and [[Porte de Vincennes hostage crisis]] during which four French Jews were murdered at a kosher supermarket, he tweeted \"Je suis #Palestinian\" (a play on the ''[[Je suis Charlie]]'' slogan) and that Israeli Prime Minister [[Benjamin Netanyahu]]'s presence in Paris \"makes [him] feel sick\". The tweet was criticised by the Israeli ambassador.<ref name=\"Perraudin140115\">{{cite news|last=Perraudin|first=Frances|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2015/jan/14/israel-protests-nick-clegg-netanyahu-tweet-david-ward|title=Israel protests to Nick Clegg over MP's Netanyahu tweet|work=The Guardian|date=14 January 2015|accessdate=10 September 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160924125002/https://www.theguardian.com/world/2015/jan/14/israel-protests-nick-clegg-netanyahu-tweet-david-ward|archive-date=24 September 2016|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\"BBC130115\">{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-30803254|title=David Ward France solidarity tweet 'in bad taste' say Liberal Democrats|publisher=BBC News|date=13 January 2015|accessdate=14 January 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150406151010/http://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-30803254|archive-date=6 April 2015|url-status=live}}</ref> A Liberal  Democrat spokesman said \"David Ward does not speak for the Liberal Democrats on this issue. He has well known and strongly held views on this issue but this tweet was clearly in bad taste\".<ref name=\"Perraudin140115\"/><ref name=\"BBC130115\"/> The comments were also condemned by party leader Nick Clegg.<ref>{{cite news|title=Nick Clegg calls Lib Dem MP Paris attack tweet 'stupid'|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-leeds-30826637|publisher=BBC News|date=15 January 2015|accessdate=15 January 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150115125100/http://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-leeds-30826637|archive-date=15 January 2015|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Perraudin|first=Frances|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2015/jan/14/israel-protests-nick-clegg-netanyahu-tweet-david-ward|title=Nick Clegg condemns Lib Dem MP's 'stupid' Netanyahu tweet|work=The Guardian|date=15 January 2015|accessdate=10 September 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160924125002/https://www.theguardian.com/world/2015/jan/14/israel-protests-nick-clegg-netanyahu-tweet-david-ward|archive-date=24 September 2016|url-status=live}}</ref> Not long afterwards at an event, [[Maajid Nawaz]], a former Islamist who is now a mainstream Liberal Democrat politician, said the Paris victims had been \"murdered for being Jewish and no other reason\" and asked his audience to acknowledge, if such a situation was reversed for Muslims in someone's tweet, \"how hurtful such a sentiment at such a time can be\".<ref>{{cite news|last=Judah|first=Ben|url=http://www.tabletmag.com/jewish-news-and-politics/189347/a-polite-hatred-2-bradford-galloway|title=Is Bradford's 'Israel-Free Zone' the New Face of Banlieue Britain?|work=The Tablet|date=6 March 2015|accessdate=26 April 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170427003918/http://www.tabletmag.com/jewish-news-and-politics/189347/a-polite-hatred-2-bradford-galloway|archive-date=27 April 2017|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n==Post-Parliament==\nWard lost his Bradford East seat at the [[2015 United Kingdom general election|2015 general election]] to [[Labour Party (UK)|Labour]]'s [[Imran Hussain (British politician)|Imran Hussain]] who gained the seat with a majority of 7,084.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/politics/constituencies/E14000587|title=Election 2015: Bradford East|publisher=BBC News|date=9 May 2015|accessdate=26 April 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190508081529/https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/politics/constituencies/E14000587|archive-date=8 May 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> Ward returned to local politics as a member of Bradford's Metropolitan District Council in the [[2016 City of Bradford Metropolitan District Council election|May 2016 elections]], and was reported to be studying at the time for a Middle East Politics and Security Studies MA at [[University of Bradford|Bradford University]].<ref name=\"Dysch0901516\">{{cite news|last=Dysch|first=Marcus|url=https://www.thejc.com/news/uk-news/lib-dems-speak-to-ex-mp-david-ward-after-he-backs-naz-shah-antisemitic-comments-1.56643|title=Lib Dems speak to ex-MP David Ward after he backs Naz Shah antisemitic comments|work=The Jewish Chronicle|date=9 May 2016|accessdate=25 April 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170426061127/https://www.thejc.com/news/uk-news/lib-dems-speak-to-ex-mp-david-ward-after-he-backs-naz-shah-antisemitic-comments-1.56643|archive-date=26 April 2017|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nThe Liberal Democrats reminded Ward of its opposition to antisemitism in May 2016 after he tweeted his support for [[Naz Shah]], the MP for [[Bradford West (UK Parliament constituency)|Bradford West]] whom [[Labour Party (UK)|Labour]] suspended after she was revealed to have written that Israel should be re-located to the United States.<ref name=\"Dysch0901516\"/>\n\n[[Tim Farron]], leader of the Liberal Democrats,  told a hearing of the Commons Home Affairs Committee's inquiry into antisemitism in October 2016 when asked about Ward's 2013 suspension that after \"a disciplinary process has been gone through\" and \"they have served their time, then it\u2019s appropriate\" for the individual to return to active involvement in a \"free organisation as they would do otherwise\". Farron said he didn't agree with Ward's comments \"some of which I would deem to be anti-semitic\".<ref>{{cite news|url=http://jewishnews.timesofisrael.com/tim-farron-backs-david-ward-return-hes-served-his-time/|title=Tim Farron backs David Ward return: 'He's served his time'|work=Jewish News|date=13 October 2016|accessdate=25 April 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170426064403/http://jewishnews.timesofisrael.com/tim-farron-backs-david-ward-return-hes-served-his-time/|archive-date=26 April 2017|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nWard was selected to contest his former seat of Bradford East at the [[2017 United Kingdom general election|2017 general election]] for the Liberal Democrats.<ref>{{cite news|last=Langston|first=Kate|url=http://www.yorkshirepost.co.uk/news/former-lib-dem-mp-accused-of-anti-semitism-to-contest-bradford-east-1-8511733|title=Former Lib Dem MP accused of anti-Semitism to contest Bradford East|work=The Yorkshire Post|date=25 April 2017|accessdate=25 April 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170425210344/http://www.yorkshirepost.co.uk/news/former-lib-dem-mp-accused-of-anti-semitism-to-contest-bradford-east-1-8511733|archive-date=25 April 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> Polling suggested he might defeat the Labour incumbent.<ref name=\"Elgot2017\">{{cite news|last=Elgot|first=Jessica|url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2017/apr/26/lib-dems-criticised-over-reselection-of-ex-mp-censured-for-antisemitism|title=Tim Farron sacks Lib Dem candidate for 'deeply offensive and antisemitic' comments|work=The Guardian|date=26 April 2017|accessdate=26 April 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170426130137/https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2017/apr/26/lib-dems-criticised-over-reselection-of-ex-mp-censured-for-antisemitism|archive-date=26 April 2017|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Dysch|first=Marcus|url=https://www.thejc.com/comment/analysis/ward-sacked-but-why-did-it-take-the-liberal-democrats-so-long-1.436945|title=Ward sacked \u2013 but why did it take the Liberal Democrats so long?|work=The Jewish Chronicle|date=26 April 2017|accessdate=26 April 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170427192229/https://www.thejc.com/comment/analysis/ward-sacked-but-why-did-it-take-the-liberal-democrats-so-long-1.436945|archive-date=27 April 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> Shortly afterwards, [[Theresa May]] mentioned his \"questionable record on antisemitism\" on 26 April in the last [[Prime Minister's Questions|prime minister's questions]] before the election. Ward was removed as the party's candidate and suspended from party membership before an intended independent investigation.<ref name=\"Elgot2017\"/> Tim Farron said \"Ward is unfit to represent the party\" and the Liberal Democrats have \"zero tolerance\" for \"anti-Semitic remarks\".<ref name=\"BBC2601417\">{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-39723144|title=Ex-MP David Ward sacked as candidate|publisher=BBC News|date=26 April 2017|accessdate=26 April 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170426141600/http://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-39723144|archive-date=26 April 2017|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Zeffman|first=Henry|url=https://www.thetimes.co.uk/edition/news/farron-sacks-lib-dem-candidate-over-antisemitic-remarks-rqbfq97qq|title=Farron sacks Lib Dem candidate over antisemitic remarks|work=The Times|date=26 April 2017|accessdate=26 April 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170426212741/https://www.thetimes.co.uk/edition/news/farron-sacks-lib-dem-candidate-over-antisemitic-remarks-rqbfq97qq|archive-date=26 April 2017|url-status=live}}{{subscription required}}</ref> Ward told [[BBC News]]: \"I would defy anybody to find one single derogatory comment I've made against a Jew which was not related to something being done in Israel\".<ref name=\"BBC2601417\"/> Ward stood as an independent,<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-leeds-39875790|title=David Ward to stand as independent for Bradford East|publisher=BBC News|date=10 May 2017|accessdate=10 May 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170510220301/http://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-leeds-39875790|archive-date=10 May 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> but Hussain was returned as the constituency MP with a larger majority; Ward came a distant third, but ahead of the Liberal Democrat candidate.<ref>{{cite news|last=Casci|first=Mark|url=http://www.yorkshirepost.co.uk/news/hussain-nets-massive-victory-in-bradford-east-1-8586345|title=Hussain Nets Massive Victoryin Bradford East|work=The Yorkshire Post|date=9 June 2017|accessdate=11 June 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170609100446/http://www.yorkshirepost.co.uk/news/hussain-nets-massive-victory-in-bradford-east-1-8586345|archive-date=9 June 2017|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nIn [[2016 City of Bradford Metropolitan District Council election|May 2016]] Ward successfully stood in the electoral ward of [[Bolton and Undercliffe]] to become a Liberal Democrat [[Councillor#United Kingdom|councillor]] for [[City of Bradford Metropolitan District Council|Bradford Council]].<ref>{{cite news | last = Young | first = Christ | title = Former Bradford East MP returns to local politics after winning seat on Bradford Council | url = http://www.thetelegraphandargus.co.uk/news/14477148.Former_Bradford_East_MP_returns_to_local_politics_after_winning_seat_on_Bradford_Council/ | work = Telegraph and Argus | date = 6 May 2016 | access-date = 22 September 2017 | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20180804051000/http://www.thetelegraphandargus.co.uk/news/14477148.Former_Bradford_East_MP_returns_to_local_politics_after_winning_seat_on_Bradford_Council/ | archive-date = 4 August 2018 | url-status = live }}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n== External links ==\n*{{UK MP links | parliament = david-ward/3923 | hansardcurr = <!-- 5541 --> | guardian = 6571/david-ward | publicwhip = David_Ward | theywork = david_ward | record = David-Ward/Bradford-East/1366 | bbc = 37625.stm | journalisted = david-ward-2 }}\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20150520125406/http://www.grassrootdiplomat.org/whoswho/ David Ward MP, Grassroot Diplomat]\n* {{C-SPAN|davidward04}}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-par|uk}}\n{{s-new | constituency }}\n{{s-ttl\n | title = [[Member of Parliament (United Kingdom)|Member of Parliament]] for [[Bradford East (UK Parliament constituency)|Bradford East]]\n | years = [[2010 United Kingdom general election|2010]]\u2013[[2015 United Kingdom general election|2015]]\n}}\n{{s-aft | after = [[Imran Hussain (British politician)|Imran Hussain]] }} \n{{s-end}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Ward, David}}\n[[Category:1953 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Alumni of the University of Bradford]]\n[[Category:Alumni of the University of Leicester]]\n[[Category:Anti-Zionism in the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:Councillors in Bradford]]\n[[Category:Liberal Democrats (UK) councillors]]\n[[Category:Liberal Democrats (UK) MPs for English constituencies]]\n[[Category:People educated at Boston Grammar School]]\n[[Category:People from Boston, Lincolnshire]]\n[[Category:Politics of Bradford]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 2010\u20132015]]\n", "text_old": "{{For|the General Secretary of the Communication Workers\u2019 Union|Dave Ward (trade unionist)}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=January 2015}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n| image = Mr David Ward MP.jpg\n| honorific-prefix =\n| name = David Ward\n| honorific-suffix =  \n| office = [[Member of Parliament (United Kingdom)|Member of Parliament]] <br /> for [[Bradford East (UK Parliament constituency)|Bradford East]]\n| parliament = \n| majority =\n| predecessor =  Constituency created\n| successor = [[Imran Hussain (British politician)|Imran Hussain]]\n| term_start = 6 May 2010\n| term_end =  30 March 2015\n|office3          = Member of the [[City of Bradford Metropolitan District Council]] for <br />[[Bolton and Undercliffe]] Ward\n|term_start3      = 5 May 2016\n|term_end3        = \n|predecessor3     = Tracey Leeming (LibDem)\n|successor3       = \n|majority3         = 874 (21.9%)\n\n| birth_date = {{Birth date and age|1953|06|24|df=yes}}\n| birth_place = [[Lincoln, England|Lincoln]], [[Lincolnshire]], England\n| death_date =\n| death_place =\n| nationality = [[United Kingdom|British]]\n| spouse = Jackie\n| party = [[Independent politician|Independent]] \n| relations =\n| children = 2 sons\n| residence = \n| alma_mater = \n| occupation = Politician\n| profession =\n| religion = \n| signature =\n| website = \n| footnotes =\n}}\n'''David Ward''' (born 24 June 1953) is a [[United Kingdom|British]] politician who was elected as the [[Liberal Democrats (UK)|Liberal Democrat]] [[Member of Parliament (United Kingdom)|Member of Parliament]] (MP) for [[Bradford East (UK Parliament constituency)|Bradford East]] at the [[2010 United Kingdom general election|2010 general election]].<ref name=\"BBC-eln2010\">{{cite news |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/shared/election2010/results/constituency/a58.stm |title=Election 2010: Bradford East |work=[[BBC News]] |accessdate=7 May 2010 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170904232258/http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/shared/election2010/results/constituency/a58.stm |archive-date=4 September 2017 |url-status=live }}</ref> He lost his seat in [[2015 United Kingdom general election|2015]] when  the [[Labour Party (UK)|Labour Party]] candidate [[Imran Hussain (British politician)|Imran Hussain]] defeated him by 7,000 votes.<ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/politics/constituencies/E14000587 | title=Bradford East Parliamentary constituency | work=[[BBC News]] | accessdate=7 May 2015 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190508081529/https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/politics/constituencies/E14000587 | archive-date=8 May 2019 | url-status=live }}</ref> Before his election to parliament, he was a councillor in Bradford for 26 years, and returned to local politics in 2016.<ref name=\"Young\">{{cite news|last=Young|first=Chris|url=http://www.thetelegraphandargus.co.uk/news/14477148.Former_Bradford_East_MP_returns_to_local_politics_after_winning_seat_on_Bradford_Council/|title=Former Bradford East MP David Ward returns to local politics after winning seat on Bradford Council|work=[[Telegraph & Argus]]|location=Bradford|date=6 May 2016|accessdate=25 April 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180804051000/http://www.thetelegraphandargus.co.uk/news/14477148.Former_Bradford_East_MP_returns_to_local_politics_after_winning_seat_on_Bradford_Council/|archive-date=4 August 2018|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nIn July 2013, he was suspended from the [[List of United Kingdom Liberal Democrat MPs (2010\u2013)|Liberal Democrats Parliamentary party]] until September 2013, after questioning the continuing existence of the state of [[Israel]] and refusing to apologise for his remarks.<ref name=\"Parliament\">{{cite news | url=http://findyourmp.parliament.uk/constituencies/bradford-east | title=Find your MP \u2013 David Ward | work=Parliament UK | accessdate=6 November 2013 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141029230323/http://findyourmp.parliament.uk/constituencies/bradford-east | archive-date=29 October 2014 | url-status=live }}</ref><ref name=\"Whip\">{{cite news|last=Syal|first=Rajeev|url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2013/jul/18/david-ward-whip-israel-apartheid-state|title=Lib Dems withdraw party whip from MP David Ward over Israel comment|work=[[The Guardian]]|date=18 July 2013|accessdate=22 July 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130730123836/http://www.theguardian.com/politics/2013/jul/18/david-ward-whip-israel-apartheid-state|archive-date=30 July 2013|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\"Suspension\">{{cite news | last=O'Donoghue | first=Gary | url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-23361380 | title=MP David Ward has Lib Dem whip withdrawn over Israel comment | work=[[BBC News]] | date=18 July 2013 | accessdate=22 July 2013 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130721214319/http://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-23361380 | archive-date=21 July 2013 | url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n==Early life and career==\n===Early life: lecturer and Bradford City F.C.===\nDavid Ward was born in [[Lincoln, England|Lincoln]]; his father was a plumber, and his mother worked on farms, in a canning factory and then in a care home.<ref name=\"Edemariam\">{{cite news|last=Edemariam|first=Aida|url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2013/feb/06/david-ward-not-racist|title=David Ward: 'The solid ground I stand on is that I am not a racist'|work=The Guardian|date=6 February 2013|accessdate=25 April 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170426063750/https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2013/feb/06/david-ward-not-racist|archive-date=26 April 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> He attended [[Boston Grammar School]] in [[Boston, Lincolnshire]], and then qualified as a member of the [[Chartered Institute of Public Finance and Accountancy]] (CIPFA) in 1976.<ref name=\"bradfordbusinessconference.co.uk\">{{cite web|title=Business Innovation in Bradford \u2013 Panel Q&A with Key Bradford Business Leaders|url=http://bradfordbusinessconference.co.uk/seminar-shining-lights.php|accessdate=3 October 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120902145354/http://www.bradfordbusinessconference.co.uk/seminar-shining-lights.php|archive-date=2 September 2012|url-status=dead}}</ref> He attended the [[University of Bradford]] Management Centre to complete an [[Master of Business Administration|MBA]] and an [[Master of Philosophy|MPhil]] by research.<ref name=\"bradfordbusinessconference.co.uk\"/><ref>{{cite news|title=University of Bradford Guide|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/education/universityeducation/universities-and-colleges/8473460/University-of-Bradford-guide.html|location=London|work=The Daily Telegraph|first=Charlotte|last=Lytton|date=17 April 2013|access-date=3 April 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120531224621/http://www.telegraph.co.uk/education/universityeducation/universities-and-colleges/8473460/University-of-Bradford-guide.html|archive-date=31 May 2012|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nHe began working at Leeds Polytechnic (later [[Leeds Metropolitan University]]) in 1985, remaining there for the next 18 years as a Principal Lecturer in finance and strategic management, and as a Business Development Manager in charge of External Income Generation.<ref name=\"pumr.pascalobservatory.org\">{{cite web|title=Pascal Universities for a Modern Renaissance|url=http://pumr.pascalobservatory.org/pascalnow/pascal-projects/pumr/david-ward|access-date=3 October 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160304042201/http://pumr.pascalobservatory.org/pascalnow/pascal-projects/pumr/david-ward|archive-date=4 March 2016|url-status=live}}</ref> In 1996, he obtained an [[Master of Science|MSc]] from the [[University of Leicester]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Lib Dems \u2013 Who We Are|url=http://www.libdems.org.uk/parliamentary_candidates_detail.aspx?name=David_Ward_MP&pPK=17eeef9e-e7a3-42d5-bd13-5bbb2151ec57|archive-url=https://archive.today/20121225023520/http://www.libdems.org.uk/parliamentary_candidates_detail.aspx?name=David_Ward_MP&pPK=17eeef9e-e7a3-42d5-bd13-5bbb2151ec57|url-status=dead|archive-date=2012-12-25}}</ref>\n\nIn July 2004, he was seconded from Leeds Metropolitan University to work at [[Bradford City Football Club]] on a full-time basis<ref name=\"pumr.pascalobservatory.org\"/> to help the club to build links with the local community  and to engage with the predominantly Pakistani-Bangladeshi community that surrounds the club in Manningham.<ref>{{cite web|title=The Times Higher Awards 2006 \u2013 The Shortlisted Candidates (Page 5)|url=http://www.bris.ac.uk/pwe/thes2006award|access-date=4 October 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20081204084436/http://www.bris.ac.uk/pwe/thes2006award|archive-date=4 December 2008|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Universities' Third Mission|url=http://pascalobservatory.org/pascalnow/term/pascal-themes/universities-third-mission?page=7|access-date=4 October 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160602085139/http://pascalobservatory.org/pascalnow/term/pascal-themes/universities-third-mission?page=7|archive-date=2 June 2016|url-status=live}}</ref> It is now host to a positive lifestyle centre, which has run programmes for more than 11,000 school children in the past seven years. There is also the football club in the community scheme, which works with 130 of Bradford\u2019s schools.<ref>{{cite web|title=David Ward MP's Maiden Speech|url=http://www.libdemvoice.org/david-ward-mps-maiden-speech-19822.html|access-date=20 October 2011|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120405160108/http://www.libdemvoice.org/david-ward-mps-maiden-speech-19822.html|archive-date=5 April 2012|url-status=live}}</ref> On 5 May 2012, the football museum{{which|date=May 2016}} was closed down.<ref>{{cite web|title=bantamspast \u2013 a kind of ending|url=http://www.bantamspast.co.uk/index.php?id=1876810492935767147|access-date=3 October 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160308203314/http://bantamspast.co.uk/index.php?id=1876810492935767147|archive-date=8 March 2016|url-status=dead}}</ref> Work began to turn the museum into a free school to be run by the One in a Million charity,<ref>{{cite web|title=Working under Way On Free School|url=http://www.oneinamillion.org.uk/work-under-way-on-free-school/|access-date=3 October 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121117105522/http://www.oneinamillion.org.uk/work-under-way-on-free-school/|archive-date=17 November 2012|url-status=live}}</ref> but a week before the start of the school term in September the funding was pulled for the school.<ref>{{cite web|title=Free School Funding Pulled|url=http://www.oneinamillion.org.uk/free-school-funding-pulled/|access-date=3 October 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121004105059/http://www.oneinamillion.org.uk/free-school-funding-pulled/|archive-date=4 October 2012|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Bradford free school loses funding one week before opening|url=https://www.theguardian.com/education/2012/aug/28/bradford-free-school-government-funding|location=London|work=The Guardian|first=Helen|last=Nugent|date=28 August 2012|access-date=11 December 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160916150454/https://www.theguardian.com/education/2012/aug/28/bradford-free-school-government-funding|archive-date=16 September 2016|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Parents rage as Michael Gove pulls free school funding days before opening|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/education/education-news/parents-rage-as-michael-gove-pulls-free-school-funding-days-before-opening-8082614.html|location=London|work=The Independent|first=Rob|last=Hastings|date=28 August 2012|access-date=26 August 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160603030013/http://www.independent.co.uk/news/education/education-news/parents-rage-as-michael-gove-pulls-free-school-funding-days-before-opening-8082614.html|archive-date=3 June 2016|url-status=live}}</ref> Ward called the move to pull the funding for the school as being \"callous, cruel and quite stupid...and incredibly unfair on the parents and children and One in a Million.\"<ref>{{cite news|title=Bradford free school One In A Million has funding cut|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-leeds-19396745|work=BBC News|date=28 August 2012|access-date=20 June 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141021170544/http://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-leeds-19396745|archive-date=21 October 2014|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=David Ward MP speaks about cruel decision to pull funding for free school in Bradford|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=2F1GQwUvsCk|access-date=25 November 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160409162902/https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=2F1GQwUvsCk|archive-date=9 April 2016|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n===Bradford public career===\nWard was first elected to [[City of Bradford Metropolitan District Council|Bradford Metropolitan District Councillor]] in 1984, and served for 26 years until he was elected to Parliament in 2010.<ref name=\"Young\"/><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.thetelegraphandargus.co.uk/news/8074215.display/|title=Former civic leader dies|work=[[Telegraph & Argus]]|location=Bradford|date=20 August 1998|accessdate=25 April 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170426064812/http://www.thetelegraphandargus.co.uk/news/8074215.display/|archive-date=26 April 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> His specialist area was education;<ref name=\"Edemariam\"/> he was a governor for 30 years at several special, primary and secondary schools<ref>{{cite web|title=Schools' joy over \u00a3500,000 reprieve|url=http://www.thetelegraphandargus.co.uk/news/local/localbrad/4090511.Schools____joy_over___500_000_reprieve/|accessdate=4 October 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130708142800/http://www.thetelegraphandargus.co.uk/news/local/localbrad/4090511.Schools____joy_over___500_000_reprieve/|archive-date=8 July 2013|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Schools to pay back \u00a3466,000|url=http://www.thetelegraphandargus.co.uk/news/local/localbrad/3760856.Schools_to_pay_back___466_000/|accessdate=4 October 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130708143843/http://www.thetelegraphandargus.co.uk/news/local/localbrad/3760856.Schools_to_pay_back___466_000/|archive-date=8 July 2013|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=College drops plans to become academy|url=http://www.thetelegraphandargus.co.uk/archive/2006/09/29/bradford_education+(bradford_education)/946201.College_drops_plans_to_become_academy/|access-date=4 October 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130708144826/http://www.thetelegraphandargus.co.uk/archive/2006/09/29/bradford_education+(bradford_education)/946201.College_drops_plans_to_become_academy/|archive-date=8 July 2013|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Clawback amnesty declared on school cash|url=http://davidward.org.uk/en/article/2009/150973/clawback-amnesty-declared-on-school-cash|accessdate=4 October 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130103083612/http://davidward.org.uk/en/article/2009/150973/clawback-amnesty-declared-on-school-cash|archive-date=3 January 2013|url-status=dead}}</ref> and held the Education Portfolio on the council for four years.<ref>{{cite web|title=Lost exam papers blow to college|url=http://www.thetelegraphandargus.co.uk/news/local/localbrad/1226713.Lost_exam_papers_blow_to_college/|accessdate=4 October 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130708145717/http://www.thetelegraphandargus.co.uk/news/local/localbrad/1226713.Lost_exam_papers_blow_to_college/|archive-date=8 July 2013|url-status=live}}</ref> Whilst holding this post he visited [[Kashmir]] with a Primary school and Secondary school headteacher to try to forge links with local schools.<ref>{{cite web|title=David Ward MP speech on Maqbool Butt Shaheed Day 2012|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=eLHmCWXjPmM&t=4m9s|access-date=25 November 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170817095922/https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=eLHmCWXjPmM&t=4m9s|archive-date=17 August 2017|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nIn 2006, he worked with others to organise the first-ever community day for the Manningham area, and his work at the club was acknowledged later that year when Leeds Metropolitan University won the <!-- Name change dates from 2008. -->''[[Times Higher Education|Times Higher Education Supplement]]'' Award for \"Outstanding contribution to the local community\".<ref name=\"upbeat.eu.com\">{{cite web|title=Upbeat \u2013 Community Unity in Bradford|url=http://www.upbeat.eu.com/casestudy/success1/|access-date=4 October 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090420083454/http://upbeat.eu.com/casestudy/success1/|archive-date=20 April 2009|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nThe charity set up by Ward focused mainly on anti-racist interventions and community cohesion events,<ref name=\"upbeat.eu.com\"/> and he continues to support organisations such as the Sports Campaign Against Racism (SCAR).<ref>Ward, D. (26 September 2012) [https://twitter.com/DavidWardMP/status/250922340597243905 \"Having a meeting now w/ anti-racist campaigners about their work in #Bradford & how I can support them\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150130180659/https://twitter.com/DavidWardMP/status/250922340597243905 |date=30 January 2015 }} ''Twitter.com''</ref>\n\nHe was the Liberal Democrat candidate at the [[1990 Bradford North by-election|Bradford North by-election in 1990]], and after his defeat he stood again in [[Bradford North (UK Parliament constituency)|Bradford North]] at the general elections in [[1992 United Kingdom general election|1992]], [[2001 United Kingdom general election|2001]] and [[2005 United Kingdom general election|2005]].<ref>{{cite news|title=UK Political Database \u2013 Bradford East|url=http://ukpolitics.telegraph.co.uk/Bradford+East|accessdate=3 October 2012|location=London|work=The Daily Telegraph|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100424223338/http://ukpolitics.telegraph.co.uk/Bradford+East|archive-date=24 April 2010|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nIn 2005, he came second, 3,500 votes behind the incumbent [[Labour Party (UK)|Labour Party]] MP [[Terry Rooney]]. Bradford North was abolished in [[Boundary Commissions (United Kingdom)|boundary changes]] for the [[2010 United Kingdom general election|general election in May 2010]]; Ward was elected for the new Bradford East seat, with a majority of 365 votes over Rooney.\n\n==Parliamentary career==\nHe was a member of the Business, Innovation and Skills Select Committee from June 2010 to June 2012, when he became a member of the Education Select Committee.<ref>{{cite web|title=www.parliament.uk \u2013 MP biographies|url=http://www.parliament.uk/biographies/commons/david-ward/37625|accessdate=3 October 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121018034141/http://www.parliament.uk/biographies/commons/david-ward/37625|archive-date=18 October 2012|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\n===Controversies===\n\n====Comments on the Holocaust====\nOn 25 January 2013, the Liberal Democrats reprimanded Ward for his \"use of language\" in a statement on his website about [[Israel]]'s treatment of [[Palestinians]], which he put on his blog the same day that he signed a memorial book in the [[House of Commons of the United Kingdom|House of Commons]] marking [[Holocaust Memorial Day (UK)|Holocaust Memorial Day]].<ref name=\"Byers\">{{cite news|last=Byers|first=David|url=https://www.thetimes.co.uk/article/liberal-democrat-mp-david-ward-in-row-over-holocaust-remarks-g9bhnkrwffw|title=Liberal Democrat MP David Ward in row over Holocaust remarks|work=The Times|date=26 January 2013|accessdate=26 April 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170427100545/https://www.thetimes.co.uk/article/liberal-democrat-mp-david-ward-in-row-over-holocaust-remarks-g9bhnkrwffw|archive-date=27 April 2017|url-status=live}}{{subscription required}}</ref> He wrote there that he honoured \"those who were persecuted and killed during the Holocaust\" but also commented: \"Having visited Auschwitz twice \u2013 once with my family and once with local schools \u2013 I am saddened that the Jews, who suffered unbelievable levels of persecution during the Holocaust, could within a few years of liberation from the death camps be inflicting atrocities on Palestinians in the new State of Israel and continue to do so on a daily basis in the West Bank and Gaza\".<ref name=\"Byers\"/><ref name=\"Condemn\">{{cite news | url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-21194991 | title=Lib Dems condemn MP's criticism of Israel ahead of Holocaust Memorial Day | work=[[BBC News]] | date=25 January 2013 | accessdate=25 January 2013 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130125204654/http://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-21194991 | archive-date=25 January 2013 | url-status=live }}</ref> \"It appears that the suffering by the Jews has not transformed their views on how others should be treated\", he said in a later statement.<ref name=\"Byers\"/>\n\nKaren Pollock, chief executive of the [[Holocaust Educational Trust]], said: \"Mr Ward has deliberately abused the memory of the Holocaust, causing deep pain and offence \u2013 these comments are sickening and unacceptable and have no place in British politics\". Jon Benjamin, chief executive of the [[Board of Deputies of British Jews]], said: \"We are outraged and shocked at these offensive comments about Jewish victims of the Holocaust and the suggestion that Jews should have learned a lesson from the experience.\"<ref name=\"Condemn\"/>\n\nIn an updated blog entry on 26 January he stated he had \"never for a moment intended to criticise or offend the Jewish people as a whole, either as a race or as a people of faith, and apologise sincerely for the unintended offence which my words caused\" and stated that while his \"criticisms of actions since 1948 in the Palestinian territories in the name of the State of Israel remain as strong as ever\" he was \"trying to make clear that everybody needs to learn the lessons of the Holocaust\".<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/politics/liberaldemocrats/9829180/Lib-Dem-MP-apologises-over-attack-on-the-Jews.html|title=Lib Dem MP apologises over attack on 'the Jews'|work=The Daily Telegraph|date=26 January 2013|accessdate=26 April 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170427101506/http://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/politics/liberaldemocrats/9829180/Lib-Dem-MP-apologises-over-attack-on-the-Jews.html|archive-date=27 April 2017|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Gray|first=Sadie|url=https://www.thetimes.co.uk/article/holocaust-row-mp-issues-public-apology-dkp7n52zh7v|title=Holocaust row MP issues public apology|work=The Times|date=26 January 2013|accessdate=26 April 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170427100026/https://www.thetimes.co.uk/article/holocaust-row-mp-issues-public-apology-dkp7n52zh7v|archive-date=27 April 2017|url-status=live}}{{subscription required}}</ref>\n\nIn a meeting with [[Alistair Carmichael]], the Liberal Democrats chief whip, Ward was told he would face disciplinary action if he repeated these words.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-leeds-21240036|title=Lib-Dem David Ward MP censured over Israel criticism|publisher=BBC News|date=28 January 2013|accessdate=26 April 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170507170907/http://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-leeds-21240036|archive-date=7 May 2017|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Lipman|first=Jennifer|url=https://www.thejc.com/news/uk-news/david-ward-responds-to-holocaust-comments-1.41180|title=David Ward responds to Holocaust comments|work=The Jewish Chronicle|date=31 January 2013|accessdate=26 April 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170427095811/https://www.thejc.com/news/uk-news/david-ward-responds-to-holocaust-comments-1.41180|archive-date=27 April 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> A meeting Ward was to attend with the [[Liberal Democrat Friends of Israel]] in February 2013 over his use of language did not occur because he had not removed contentious phrasing from his website.<ref>{{cite news|last=Dysch|first=Marcus|url=https://www.thejc.com/news/uk-news/liberal-democrats-in-turmoil-over-david-ward-1.46277|title=Liberal Democrats in turmoil over David Ward|work=The Jewish Chronicle|date=27 June 2013|accessdate=26 April 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170427003721/https://www.thejc.com/news/uk-news/liberal-democrats-in-turmoil-over-david-ward-1.46277|archive-date=27 April 2017|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nIn an interview with [[Aida Edemariam]] of ''[[The Guardian]]'' in February 2013, Ward said: \"There is a huge operation out there, a machine almost, which is designed to protect the state of Israel from criticism. And that comes into play very, very quickly\" with the result \"I end up looking at\" the vocabulary \"I should use\" which \"is winning, for them. Because what I want to talk about is the fundamental question of how can they do this, and how can they be allowed to do this\".<ref name=\"Edemariam\"/>\n\n====Comments on Israel====\nWard [[Twitter|tweeted]] on 13 July 2013: \"Am I wrong or are am I right? At long last the Zionists are losing the battle \u2013 how long can the apartheid State of Israel last?\" He refused to apologise for questioning Israel's right to exist, and was suspended from the Liberal Democrats parliamentary party for three months.<ref name=\"Whip\"/><ref>{{cite news|last=Morris|first=Nigel|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/politics/liberal-democrats-suspend-mp-david-ward-over-israel-comments-on-holocaust-day-8717552.html|title=Liberal Democrats suspend MP David Ward over Israel comments on Holocaust Day|work=The Independent|date=18 July 2013|accessdate=25 April 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170426063337/http://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/politics/liberal-democrats-suspend-mp-david-ward-over-israel-comments-on-holocaust-day-8717552.html|archive-date=26 April 2017|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nThe Liberal Democrats' chief whip Alistair Carmichael reminded him of his failure to keep a previous promise to use \"proportionate and precise\" language when commenting on Israel,<ref name=\"Rutter\">{{cite news|last=Rutter|first=Tamsin|url=https://www.theguardian.com/uk-news/the-northerner/2013/jul/22/david-ward-israel-comments-bradford|title=Bradford Muslim group to show support for MP David Ward|work=[[The Guardian]]|date=22 July 2013|accessdate=26 April 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170426063626/https://www.theguardian.com/uk-news/the-northerner/2013/jul/22/david-ward-israel-comments-bradford|archive-date=26 April 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> writing: \"These interventions cause considerable offence rather than addressing questions of political substance about the plight of the Palestinian people and the right of Israel's citizens to live a life free of violence\".<ref name=\"Mason180713\">{{cite news|last=Mason|first=Rowena|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/politics/liberaldemocrats/10188329/Lib-Dems-suspend-David-Ward-as-MP-over-Israel-tweet.html|title=Lib Dems suspend David Ward as MP over Israel tweet|work=The Daily Telegraph|date=18 July 2013|accessdate=26 April 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170427004720/http://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/politics/liberaldemocrats/10188329/Lib-Dems-suspend-David-Ward-as-MP-over-Israel-tweet.html|archive-date=27 April 2017|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Craig|first=Jon|url=http://news.sky.com/story/david-ward-in-row-after-zionist-tweet-10439857|title=David Ward In Row After '#Zionist' Tweet|publisher=Sky News|date=18 July 2013|accessdate=26 April 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170427100030/http://news.sky.com/story/david-ward-in-row-after-zionist-tweet-10439857|archive-date=27 April 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> Jonathan Arkush, vice-president of the Board of Deputies of British Jews, described the decision to take away Ward's party whip as \"too little, too late\" and \"an empty gesture\" because of the parliamentary recess.<ref>{{cite news|last=Dysch|first=Marcus|url=https://www.thejc.com/news/uk-news/liberal-democrats-suspend-whip-from-david-ward-1.47009|title=Liberal Democrats suspend whip from David Ward|work=The Jewish Chronicle|date=18 July 2013|accessdate=26 April 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170427095808/https://www.thejc.com/news/uk-news/liberal-democrats-suspend-whip-from-david-ward-1.47009|archive-date=27 April 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> Parliament was due to sit for only  two weeks in September 2013 before the end of his suspension.<ref name=\"Mason180713\"/> Ward objected to his suspension believing his views are widely shared. The [[Respect Party|Respect]] MP for [[Bradford West (UK Parliament constituency)|Bradford West]], [[George Galloway]], defended Ward against his suspension, as did several Muslim activists in his constituency.<ref name=\"Rutter\"/>\n\n====Comments on the Board of Deputies====\nIn November 2013, after Ward had said that it is \"a shame there isn\u2019t a powerful, well-funded Board of Deputies for [[Romani people|Roma]]\", an editorial in ''[[The Jewish Chronicle]]'' described his comments as \"a clear restatement of the most basic antisemitic theme of all \u2014 that wealthy Jews buy up power\" and said that the Liberal Democrats' had goven a \"contemptible response\" with their inaction.<ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.thejc.com/comment/leaders/libdem-s-inaction-over-david-ward-is-contemptible-1.51120| title=LibDem's inaction over David Ward is contemptible| work=[[The Jewish Chronicle]]| date=22 November 2013| accessdate=26 April 2017| archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170427095929/https://www.thejc.com/comment/leaders/libdem-s-inaction-over-david-ward-is-contemptible-1.51120| archive-date=27 April 2017| url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n====Comments on Hamas rockets====\nWard [[twitter|tweeted]] in July 2014 about the ongoing [[Operation Protective Edge|Israeli conflict in Gaza]] suggesting that if he lived in Gaza, he would fire rockets at Israel: \"The big question is \u2013 if I lived in #Gaza would I fire a rocket? \u2013 probably yes\". Interviewed on [[BBC Radio 5 Live]], he initially refused to apologise.<ref name=\"BBC220714\">{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-28424396|title=Lib Dem MP David Ward criticised over Gaza tweets|publisher=BBC News|date=22 July 2014|accessdate=26 April 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170616204155/http://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-28424396|archive-date=16 June 2017|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nWard was condemned by other politicians. [[Grant Shapps]], the [[Chairman of the Conservative Party]], called the tweet \"essentially [an] incitement to violence\" and \"completely irresponsible\". Shapps urged him to delete the comment.<ref name=\"BBC220714\"/><ref>{{cite news|last=Mason|first=Rowena|url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2014/jul/22/david-ward-gaza-rocket-tweet|title=Lib Dem MP David Ward facing disciplinary action for Gaza tweets|work=The Guardian|date=22 July 2014|accessdate=26 April 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170422040223/https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2014/jul/22/david-ward-gaza-rocket-tweet|archive-date=22 April 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> A Liberal Democrat spokesperson called the tweet \"vile and crass\"; the party leader Nick Clegg had called for peace in Israel and Gaza.<ref>{{cite news|last=Datoo|first=Siraj|url=https://www.buzzfeed.com/sirajdatoo/liberal-democrat-mp-set-to-be-disciplined-for-gaza-tweets|title=Liberal Democrat MP Criticised For Saying He Would Fire A Rocket If He Lived In Gaza|work=Buzzfeed|date=23 July 2014|accessdate=26 April 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170423062130/https://www.buzzfeed.com/sirajdatoo/liberal-democrat-mp-set-to-be-disciplined-for-gaza-tweets|archive-date=23 April 2017|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Coates|first=Sam|url=https://www.thetimes.co.uk/article/lib-dem-mps-vile-gaza-tweets-attacked-by-party-xfwww3kb95c|title=Lib Dem MP's 'vile' Gaza tweets attacked by party|work=The Times|date=23 July 2014|accessdate=26 April 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170427100217/https://www.thetimes.co.uk/article/lib-dem-mps-vile-gaza-tweets-attacked-by-party-xfwww3kb95c|archive-date=27 April 2017|url-status=live}}{{subscription required}}</ref> Gavin Stollar, chair of the Liberal Democrats Friends of Israel, said Ward was \"an ignorant political opportunist\" who \"is neither a Liberal nor a Democrat\".<ref>{{cite news|last=Rashty|first=Sandy|url=https://www.thejc.com/news/uk-news/lib-dems-will-discipline-david-ward-over-gaza-tweet-1.55832|title=Lib Dems will discipline David Ward over Gaza tweet|work=The Jewish Chronicle|date=23 July 2014|accessdate=26 April 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170427003829/https://www.thejc.com/news/uk-news/lib-dems-will-discipline-david-ward-over-gaza-tweet-1.55832|archive-date=27 April 2017|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nAn apology was issued under his name by his party in late July.<ref>{{cite news|last=Savage|first=Michael|url=https://www.thetimes.co.uk/article/lib-dem-mp-david-ward-backs-down-over-vile-gaza-tweets-nvtmp78m63x|title=Lib Dem MP David Ward backs down over 'vile' Gaza tweets|work=The Times|date=23 July 2014|accessdate=26 April 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170427100537/https://www.thetimes.co.uk/article/lib-dem-mp-david-ward-backs-down-over-vile-gaza-tweets-nvtmp78m63x|archive-date=27 April 2017|url-status=live}}{{subscription required}}</ref> \"I utterly condemn the violence on both sides in Israel and Gaza\" he said, and \"while I defend the right of Israel to exist and defend itself, I will continue to speak out for the rights of the Palestinian people\".<ref name=\"Savage240714\">{{cite news|last=Savage|first=Michael|url=https://www.thetimes.co.uk/article/lib-dem-mp-in-gaza-rockets-row-25vhbsjv8w3|title=Lib Dem MP in Gaza rockets row|work=The Times|date=24 July 2014|accessdate=26 April 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170427100403/https://www.thetimes.co.uk/article/lib-dem-mp-in-gaza-rockets-row-25vhbsjv8w3|archive-date=27 April 2017|url-status=live}}{{subscription required}}</ref> In a response, the Board of Deputies said: \"This morning's 'spin' in no way negates the fact that David Ward has deliberately placed himself outside the party\u2019s core beliefs and values. We have seen Ward apologise and receive rebuke before, to no avail\".<ref name=\"Savage240714\"/>\n\nThe following month, it emerged Ward would not face any disciplinary action. The party's chief whip, by now [[Don Foster, Baron Foster of Bath|Don Foster]], said the comment had not brought the party into disrepute, nor was it antisemitic. Ward had assured Foster \"he would do all he could to ensure comments he made would be in a form that would be difficult to misinterpret\".<ref>{{cite news|last=Dysch|first=Marcus|url=https://www.thejc.com/news/uk-news/lib-dems-won-t-discipline-david-ward-over-gaza-rocket-tweet-1.56133|title=Lib Dems won't discipline David Ward over Gaza rocket tweet|work=The Jewish Chronicle|date=13 August 2014|accessdate=26 April 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170427003826/https://www.thejc.com/news/uk-news/lib-dems-won-t-discipline-david-ward-over-gaza-rocket-tweet-1.56133|archive-date=27 April 2017|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n====Comments following ''Charlie Hebdo'' attack====\nDuring the [[republican marches]] in January 2015, following the [[Charlie Hebdo shooting|''Charlie Hebdo'' shooting]] and [[Porte de Vincennes hostage crisis]] during which four French Jews were murdered at a kosher supermarket, he tweeted \"Je suis #Palestinian\" (a play on the ''[[Je suis Charlie]]'' slogan) and that Israeli Prime Minister [[Benjamin Netanyahu]]'s presence in Paris \"makes [him] feel sick\". The tweet was criticised by the Israeli ambassador.<ref name=\"Perraudin140115\">{{cite news|last=Perraudin|first=Frances|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2015/jan/14/israel-protests-nick-clegg-netanyahu-tweet-david-ward|title=Israel protests to Nick Clegg over MP's Netanyahu tweet|work=The Guardian|date=14 January 2015|accessdate=10 September 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160924125002/https://www.theguardian.com/world/2015/jan/14/israel-protests-nick-clegg-netanyahu-tweet-david-ward|archive-date=24 September 2016|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\"BBC130115\">{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-30803254|title=David Ward France solidarity tweet 'in bad taste' say Liberal Democrats|publisher=BBC News|date=13 January 2015|accessdate=14 January 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150406151010/http://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-30803254|archive-date=6 April 2015|url-status=live}}</ref> A Liberal  Democrat spokesman said \"David Ward does not speak for the Liberal Democrats on this issue. He has well known and strongly held views on this issue but this tweet was clearly in bad taste\".<ref name=\"Perraudin140115\"/><ref name=\"BBC130115\"/> The comments were also condemned by party leader Nick Clegg.<ref>{{cite news|title=Nick Clegg calls Lib Dem MP Paris attack tweet 'stupid'|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-leeds-30826637|publisher=BBC News|date=15 January 2015|accessdate=15 January 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150115125100/http://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-leeds-30826637|archive-date=15 January 2015|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Perraudin|first=Frances|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2015/jan/14/israel-protests-nick-clegg-netanyahu-tweet-david-ward|title=Nick Clegg condemns Lib Dem MP's 'stupid' Netanyahu tweet|work=The Guardian|date=15 January 2015|accessdate=10 September 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160924125002/https://www.theguardian.com/world/2015/jan/14/israel-protests-nick-clegg-netanyahu-tweet-david-ward|archive-date=24 September 2016|url-status=live}}</ref> Not long afterwards at an event, [[Maajid Nawaz]], a former Islamist who is now a mainstream Liberal Democrat politician, said the Paris victims had been \"murdered for being Jewish and no other reason\" and asked his audience to acknowledge, if such a situation was reversed for Muslims in someone's tweet, \"how hurtful such a sentiment at such a time can be\".<ref>{{cite news|last=Judah|first=Ben|url=http://www.tabletmag.com/jewish-news-and-politics/189347/a-polite-hatred-2-bradford-galloway|title=Is Bradford's 'Israel-Free Zone' the New Face of Banlieue Britain?|work=The Tablet|date=6 March 2015|accessdate=26 April 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170427003918/http://www.tabletmag.com/jewish-news-and-politics/189347/a-polite-hatred-2-bradford-galloway|archive-date=27 April 2017|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n==Post-Parliament==\nWard lost his Bradford East seat at the [[2015 United Kingdom general election|2015 general election]] to [[Labour Party (UK)|Labour]]'s [[Imran Hussain (British politician)|Imran Hussain]] who gained the seat with a majority of 7,084.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/politics/constituencies/E14000587|title=Election 2015: Bradford East|publisher=BBC News|date=9 May 2015|accessdate=26 April 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190508081529/https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/politics/constituencies/E14000587|archive-date=8 May 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> Ward returned to local politics as a member of Bradford\u2019s Metropolitan District Council in the [[2016 City of Bradford Metropolitan District Council election|May 2016 elections]], and was reported to be studying at the time for a Middle East Politics and Security Studies MA at [[University of Bradford|Bradford University]].<ref name=\"Dysch0901516\">{{cite news|last=Dysch|first=Marcus|url=https://www.thejc.com/news/uk-news/lib-dems-speak-to-ex-mp-david-ward-after-he-backs-naz-shah-antisemitic-comments-1.56643|title=Lib Dems speak to ex-MP David Ward after he backs Naz Shah antisemitic comments|work=The Jewish Chronicle|date=9 May 2016|accessdate=25 April 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170426061127/https://www.thejc.com/news/uk-news/lib-dems-speak-to-ex-mp-david-ward-after-he-backs-naz-shah-antisemitic-comments-1.56643|archive-date=26 April 2017|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nThe Liberal Democrats reminded Ward of its opposition to antisemitism in May 2016 after he tweeted his support for [[Naz Shah]], the MP for [[Bradford West (UK Parliament constituency)|Bradford West]] whom [[Labour Party (UK)|Labour]] suspended after she was revealed to have written that Israel should be re-located to the United States.<ref name=\"Dysch0901516\"/>\n\n[[Tim Farron]], leader of the Liberal Democrats,  told a hearing of the Commons Home Affairs Committee\u2019s inquiry into antisemitism in October 2016 when asked about Ward's 2013 suspension that after \"a disciplinary process has been gone through\" and \"they have served their time, then it\u2019s appropriate\" for the individual to return to active involvement in a \"free organisation as they would do otherwise\". Farron said he didn't agree with Ward's comments \"some of which I would deem to be anti-semitic\".<ref>{{cite news|url=http://jewishnews.timesofisrael.com/tim-farron-backs-david-ward-return-hes-served-his-time/|title=Tim Farron backs David Ward return: 'He's served his time'|work=Jewish News|date=13 October 2016|accessdate=25 April 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170426064403/http://jewishnews.timesofisrael.com/tim-farron-backs-david-ward-return-hes-served-his-time/|archive-date=26 April 2017|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nWard was selected to contest his former seat of Bradford East at the [[2017 United Kingdom general election|2017 general election]] for the Liberal Democrats.<ref>{{cite news|last=Langston|first=Kate|url=http://www.yorkshirepost.co.uk/news/former-lib-dem-mp-accused-of-anti-semitism-to-contest-bradford-east-1-8511733|title=Former Lib Dem MP accused of anti-Semitism to contest Bradford East|work=The Yorkshire Post|date=25 April 2017|accessdate=25 April 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170425210344/http://www.yorkshirepost.co.uk/news/former-lib-dem-mp-accused-of-anti-semitism-to-contest-bradford-east-1-8511733|archive-date=25 April 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> Polling suggested he might defeat the Labour incumbent.<ref name=\"Elgot2017\">{{cite news|last=Elgot|first=Jessica|url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2017/apr/26/lib-dems-criticised-over-reselection-of-ex-mp-censured-for-antisemitism|title=Tim Farron sacks Lib Dem candidate for 'deeply offensive and antisemitic' comments|work=The Guardian|date=26 April 2017|accessdate=26 April 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170426130137/https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2017/apr/26/lib-dems-criticised-over-reselection-of-ex-mp-censured-for-antisemitism|archive-date=26 April 2017|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Dysch|first=Marcus|url=https://www.thejc.com/comment/analysis/ward-sacked-but-why-did-it-take-the-liberal-democrats-so-long-1.436945|title=Ward sacked \u2013 but why did it take the Liberal Democrats so long?|work=The Jewish Chronicle|date=26 April 2017|accessdate=26 April 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170427192229/https://www.thejc.com/comment/analysis/ward-sacked-but-why-did-it-take-the-liberal-democrats-so-long-1.436945|archive-date=27 April 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> Shortly afterwards, [[Theresa May]] mentioned his \"questionable record on antisemitism\" on 26 April in the last [[Prime Minister's Questions|prime minister's questions]] before the election. Ward was removed as the party's candidate and suspended from party membership before an intended independent investigation.<ref name=\"Elgot2017\"/> Tim Farron said \"Ward is unfit to represent the party\" and the Liberal Democrats have \"zero tolerance\" for \"anti-Semitic remarks\".<ref name=\"BBC2601417\">{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-39723144|title=Ex-MP David Ward sacked as candidate|publisher=BBC News|date=26 April 2017|accessdate=26 April 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170426141600/http://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-39723144|archive-date=26 April 2017|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Zeffman|first=Henry|url=https://www.thetimes.co.uk/edition/news/farron-sacks-lib-dem-candidate-over-antisemitic-remarks-rqbfq97qq|title=Farron sacks Lib Dem candidate over antisemitic remarks|work=The Times|date=26 April 2017|accessdate=26 April 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170426212741/https://www.thetimes.co.uk/edition/news/farron-sacks-lib-dem-candidate-over-antisemitic-remarks-rqbfq97qq|archive-date=26 April 2017|url-status=live}}{{subscription required}}</ref> Ward told [[BBC News]]: \"I would defy anybody to find one single derogatory comment I've made against a Jew which was not related to something being done in Israel\".<ref name=\"BBC2601417\"/> Ward stood as an independent,<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-leeds-39875790|title=David Ward to stand as independent for Bradford East|publisher=BBC News|date=10 May 2017|accessdate=10 May 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170510220301/http://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-leeds-39875790|archive-date=10 May 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> but Hussain was returned as the constituency MP with a larger majority; Ward came a distant third, but ahead of the Liberal Democrat candidate.<ref>{{cite news|last=Casci|first=Mark|url=http://www.yorkshirepost.co.uk/news/hussain-nets-massive-victory-in-bradford-east-1-8586345|title=Hussain Nets Massive Victoryin Bradford East|work=The Yorkshire Post|date=9 June 2017|accessdate=11 June 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170609100446/http://www.yorkshirepost.co.uk/news/hussain-nets-massive-victory-in-bradford-east-1-8586345|archive-date=9 June 2017|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nIn [[2016 City of Bradford Metropolitan District Council election|May 2016]] Ward successfully stood in the electoral ward of [[Bolton and Undercliffe]] to become a Liberal Democrat [[Councillor#United Kingdom|councillor]] for [[City of Bradford Metropolitan District Council|Bradford Council]].<ref>{{cite news | last = Young | first = Christ | title = Former Bradford East MP returns to local politics after winning seat on Bradford Council | url = http://www.thetelegraphandargus.co.uk/news/14477148.Former_Bradford_East_MP_returns_to_local_politics_after_winning_seat_on_Bradford_Council/ | work = Telegraph and Argus | date = 6 May 2016 | access-date = 22 September 2017 | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20180804051000/http://www.thetelegraphandargus.co.uk/news/14477148.Former_Bradford_East_MP_returns_to_local_politics_after_winning_seat_on_Bradford_Council/ | archive-date = 4 August 2018 | url-status = live }}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n== External links ==\n*{{UK MP links | parliament = david-ward/3923 | hansardcurr = <!-- 5541 --> | guardian = 6571/david-ward | publicwhip = David_Ward | theywork = david_ward | record = David-Ward/Bradford-East/1366 | bbc = 37625.stm | journalisted = david-ward-2 }}\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20150520125406/http://www.grassrootdiplomat.org/whoswho/ David Ward MP, Grassroot Diplomat]\n* {{C-SPAN|davidward04}}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-par|uk}}\n{{s-new | constituency }}\n{{s-ttl\n | title = [[Member of Parliament (United Kingdom)|Member of Parliament]] for [[Bradford East (UK Parliament constituency)|Bradford East]]\n | years = [[2010 United Kingdom general election|2010]]\u2013[[2015 United Kingdom general election|2015]]\n}}\n{{s-aft | after = [[Imran Hussain (British politician)|Imran Hussain]] }} \n{{s-end}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Ward, David}}\n[[Category:1953 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Alumni of the University of Bradford]]\n[[Category:Alumni of the University of Leicester]]\n[[Category:Anti-Zionism in the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:Councillors in Bradford]]\n[[Category:Liberal Democrats (UK) councillors]]\n[[Category:Liberal Democrats (UK) MPs for English constituencies]]\n[[Category:People educated at Boston Grammar School]]\n[[Category:People from Boston, Lincolnshire]]\n[[Category:Politics of Bradford]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 2010\u20132015]]\n", "name_user": "Iridescent", "label": "safe", "comment": "Cleanup andtypo fixing,typo(s) fixed: \u2019s \u2192 's (3)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/David_Ward_(British_politician)"}
{"title_page": "WSVN", "text_new": "{{short description|Fox affiliate in Miami}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=March 2019}}\n<!-- Do NOT post content from NewsBlues.com, as it is NOT a reliable source. -->\n{{Refimprove|date=January 2017}}\n{{Infobox broadcast\n| call_letters             = WSVN\n| station_logo             = WSVN 7 Miami logo.png\n| logo_size                = 175px\n| location                 = [[Miami]]\u2013[[Fort Lauderdale, Florida]]\n| country                  = United States\n| city                     = Miami, Florida\n| station_branding         = '''general:''' WSVN 7<br>'''newscasts:''' ''7 News''\n| station_slogan           = ''The News Station''\n| digital                  = 9 ([[very high frequency|VHF]])\n| virtual                  = 7 ([[Program and System Information Protocol|PSIP]])\n| affiliations             = {{ubl|'''7.1:''' [[Fox Broadcasting Company|Fox]]|'''7.2:''' [[Light TV]]}}\n| owner                    = [[Sunbeam Television|Sunbeam Television Corporation]]\n| licensee                 = \n| airdate                  = {{start date and age|1956|7|29|p=y}}<br>''(current license dates from December 19, 1962)''\n| callsign_meaning         = Channel '''S'''e'''V'''e'''N'''\n| sister_stations          = \n| former_callsigns         = WCKT (1956\u20131983)\n| former_channel_numbers   = {{ubl|'''Analog:'''|7 (VHF, 1956\u20132009)|'''Digital:'''|8 (VHF, 2000\u20132009)|7 (VHF, 2009\u20132019)}}\n| former_affiliations      = {{ubl|'''Primary:'''|[[NBC]] (1956\u20131988)|'''Secondary:'''|[[American Broadcasting Company|ABC]] (1956\u20131957)|'''DT2:'''|[[Estrella TV]] (2009\u20132017)}}\n| effective_radiated_power = 158 [[kilowatt|kW]]\n| HAAT                     = {{convert|307.1|m|ft|0|abbr=on}}\n| facility_id              = 63840\n| coordinates              = {{nowrap|{{coord|25|58|1|N|80|12|42|W|type:landmark_scale:2000|display=inline, title}}}}\n| licensing_authority      = [[Federal Communications Commission|FCC]]\n| homepage                 = {{URL|https://wsvn.com/}}\n}}\n\n'''WSVN''', [[virtual channel]] 7 ([[Very high frequency|VHF]] [[digital terrestrial television|digital]] channel 9), is a [[Fox Broadcasting Company|Fox]]-[[network affiliate|affiliated]] [[television station]] [[city of license|licensed]] to [[Miami|Miami, Florida]], United States and also serving [[Fort Lauderdale, Florida|Fort Lauderdale]]. It is the [[flagship (broadcasting)|flagship station]] of locally based [[Sunbeam Television]]. WSVN's studios are located on 79th Street Causeway ([[Florida State Road 934|SR 934]]) in [[North Bay Village, Florida|North Bay Village]] (though with a Miami [[United States Postal Service|postal]] address), and its transmitter is located in north [[Miami\u2013Dade County, Florida|Miami\u2013Dade County]].\n\n==History==\n\n===WCKT===\nThe station first signed on the air on July 29, 1956 as '''WCKT'''. Originally operating as an [[NBC]] affiliate, it was founded by the Biscayne Television Corporation, a partnership between the [[Cox Enterprises|Cox]] and [[Knight Ridder|Knight]] publishing families (from which the original call letters were derived ['''C'''ox '''K'''night '''T'''elevision]), who respectively owned Miami's two major newspapers: the now-defunct ''[[The Miami News|Miami News]]'' and the still-operating ''[[The Miami Herald|Miami Herald]]''. The same Cox/Knight partnership also owned WCKR radio (610 AM, now [[WIOD]], and 97.3 FM, now [[WFLC]]). Niles Trammell, a former NBC president, held a 15 percent ownership interest in WCKT.\n\nBefore WCKT signed on, NBC programming had been carried on [[Fort Lauderdale, Florida|Fort Lauderdale]]'s WFTL-TV (channel 23, later known as WGBS-TV after it had been acquired by [[Storer Broadcasting]]), which also held a secondary affiliation with the [[DuMont Television Network]]. However, WFTL struggled because television sets were not required to have UHF tuning capability (the [[Federal Communications Commission]] (FCC) would later [[All-Channel Receiver Act|require such tuners to be included]] in sets manufactured from 1964 onward). It didn't help matters that much of the area particularly Fort Lauderdale got a fairly strong signal from WJNO-TV (channel 5, now [[WPTV-TV|WPTV]]) in [[West Palm Beach, Florida|West Palm Beach]]. When the Cox/Knight partnership won a [[construction permit]] and [[broadcast license]] to operate a station on VHF channel 7, NBC quickly agreed to move its affiliation to WCKT, since WCKR radio had been the longtime Miami affiliate of the [[Blue Network|NBC Blue Network]] (the forerunner to today's [[American Broadcasting Company]] (ABC)). Until WPST-TV (channel 10, now [[WPLG]]) signed on in August 1957, WCKT also shared ABC programming with [[WTVJ]] (channel 4), as part of an arrangement with the network to provide its programming throughout the [[media market|market]] as television sets were not required to have UHF tuning capability at the time, preventing many in the area from receiving the market's original ABC affiliate, WITV (channel 17). Channel 23 became an [[Independent station (North America)|independent station]] and eventually went dark, and later came back to the air in 1967 as WAJA-TV (it is now [[Univision]] flagship [[WLTV-DT]]).\n\nIn 1962, the Cox/Knight/Trammell partnership was stripped of its broadcast licenses due to violations of the FCC's licensing rules and ethics violations. In hearings that began in June 1960, it was found that some of the principals of Biscayne Television, as well as some of James Cox's personal friends, had made improper contact with FCC commissioner Richard Mack in order to influence the awarding of the construction permit and licenses. Biscayne had competed for the license with two other applicants, East Coast Television and South Florida TV. Mack had also been found guilty of taking payoffs and was forced to resign by [[President of the United States|President]] [[Dwight D. Eisenhower]], as well as the rest of the FCC commissioners.\n\nBiscayne Television originally planned to appeal its license revocation, but was advised that the appeal would be turned down due to the gravity of the situation. Mack had also been found guilty of taking payoffs in the licensing process WPST, to the broadcasting subsidiary of [[National Airlines (NA)|National Airlines]]. WPST had its license revoked and Biscayne then opted to put WCKT up for sale. The owners of WPST were forced to sell the station only after they had to cease broadcasting.\n\n===Sunbeam Television ownership===\nShortly afterward, a new company called [[Sunbeam Television|Sunbeam Television Corporation]] bought the station for $3.4 million and assumed ownership of channel 7 on December 19, 1962. Upon the change in ownership, Sunbeam retained the WCKT call letters and claimed the Cox/Knight station's history as its own. Sunbeam was a partnership between [[Miami Beach, Florida|Miami Beach]]-based real estate developer Sydney Ansin, and his son [[Edmund Ansin]]. The younger Ansin succeeded his father as president of Sunbeam Television in 1971. The station began using its own version of the [[circle 7 logo]] (which is moderately similar to the version originally created for ABC's owned-and-operated stations, but with the \"7\" not connected to the circle and being somewhat shaped differently) in the mid-1970s. On June 7, 1983, the station's callsign was changed to the current '''WSVN''', after those call letters were acquired from a [[PBS]] satellite [[Blue Ridge PBS|member station]] in [[Norton, Virginia]] (which subsequently became WSBN-TV; it has since [[Dark (broadcasting)|gone off the air]]).\n\nAs an NBC affiliate, WCKT/WSVN aired a local newscast in place of programs that NBC had aired at noon on weekdays. It also occasionally preempted network shows that aired during the 10:00 a.m. or 11:00 a.m. timeslot (but ran at least one of these hours) and preempted an occasional prime time program. While NBC was traditionally far less tolerant of program preemptions than the other major broadcast networks, it did not mind this at first provided that the network was able to get Miami area independent stations to air whatever programs that WSVN chose not to air. In addition, NBC programs that were not broadcast by WSVN were cleared by WPTV, whose signal provides city-grade coverage of Fort Lauderdale and was available on nearly every [[cable television|cable]] provider in the area. However, in the early 1980s, WPTV was removed from some Miami area cable systems to make room for new channels due to limited [[cable television headend|headend]] channel capacity. Largely due to those preemptions, WCKT/WSVN was one of NBC's weaker affiliates. Though NBC continued to arrange for independent stations to air network programs that were not shown on WSVN, the network grew increasingly annoyed at having to resort to such an arrangement in what had grown into a major market. NBC eventually decided that it needed to [[owned-and-operated station|acquire its own station]] in the growing [[South Florida metropolitan area|South Florida]] market.\n\n====Network affiliation switch====\nNBC got its chance at owning a station in the late 1980s, when [[Kohlberg Kravis Roberts]] put [[CBS]] affiliate WTVJ (then on channel 4, now on channel 6) on the market. NBC's then-corporate parent [[General Electric]] purchased that station in 1987, but WTVJ's affiliation contract with CBS was not set to expire until December 1988. CBS was willing to let WTVJ out of its contract one year early. However, Ed Ansin was not interested in letting NBC out of its affiliation agreement with WSVN, which also expired at the same time; Ansin even made an unsuccessful petition to the FCC to stop NBC's purchase of WTVJ.<ref>{{cite web|author= |url=http://articles.sun-sentinel.com/1987-03-11/business/8701150881_1_station-owner-ed-ansin-channel |title=Channel 7 Fights Sale Of Rival Tv Station`s Owner Wants Channel 4 Deal Stopped  |website=Sun-Sentinel |date=March 11, 1987 |accessdate=January 21, 2016}}</ref><ref>[http://www.americanradiohistory.com/Archive-BC-IDX/87-OCR/BC-1987-03-16-Page-0041.pdf] {{dead link|date=January 2016}}</ref><ref>[http://www.americanradiohistory.com/Archive-BC-IDX/87-OCR/BC-1987-03-16-Page-0042.pdf] {{dead link|date=January 2016}}</ref> He wanted channel 7 to air NBC's strong fall 1988 lineup, which included the network's coverage of [[Major League Baseball]]'s [[1988 World Series|World Series]] and the [[1988 Summer Olympics|Summer Olympics]].\n\nAs a result, NBC was forced to run WTVJ as a CBS affiliate for more than a year, with all of the NBC shows that were preempted by WSVN airing on WTVJ instead. This  situation did not sit well with either network. Ansin made an offer to take the CBS affiliation, but CBS turned the offer down.<ref>[http://articles.sun-sentinel.com/1988-06-19/business/8802050663_1_affiliates-convention-nbc-affiliation-affiliate-stations CBS Snubs WTVJ, Network Affiliation Flap Is Setting Precedents], ''Fort Lauderdale Sun-Sentinel'', June 19, 1988.</ref> Instead, CBS bought Miami's longtime independent station and original [[Fox Broadcasting Company|Fox]] affiliate, WCIX channel 6, even though that station had an inadequate signal in [[Broward County, Florida|Broward County]] (WCIX's transmitter was located in [[Homestead, Florida|Homestead]], farther southwest than those of other Miami area stations, to avoid signal interference with WCPX-TV (now [[WKMG-TV]]) in [[Orlando, Florida|Orlando]] and WPTV). In May 1988, Ed Ansin filed an antitrust lawsuit against General Electric/NBC and CBS, one week after he had claimed that CBS backed out of contract negotiations to affiliate with WSVN.<ref>[http://articles.sun-sentinel.com/1988-05-07/business/8801280416_1_two-networks-wsvn-nbc WSVN Owner Files Suit Against Networks, Firm], ''Fort Lauderdale Sun-Sentinel'', May 7, 1988.</ref> With WCIX planning to switch to CBS at the start of 1989, Fox began negotiations with other area stations to carry its programming. It ultimately reached an agreement with Sunbeam Television to affiliate with channel 7.\n\n====Fox affiliation====\nOn [[New Year's Day|January 1]], 1989, South Florida's first network affiliation switch occurred, with NBC moving to WTVJ full-time and WSVN taking the Fox affiliation. Channel 7 had far fewer network shows to preempt as a result, as Fox only ran prime time programming on weekends at the time and would not air an entire week's worth of programming until 1993. As a result, WSVN was for essential intents and purposes programmed as a ''de facto'' independent station (even referring to itself as such in promotions regarding the switch, despite still being affiliated with a network). Until Fox began airing programming every weeknight, WSVN aired a movie in prime time at 8:00 p.m. on nights where network programming was not scheduled to air. WSVN's affiliation with Fox could be seen as a major coup for the fledgling network, as WSVN had been a longtime NBC affiliate and Fox was pleased to affiliate with a station that had been with a \"[[Big Three television networks|Big Three]]\" network for years. At the time, WSVN was one of the largest heritage \"Big Three\" stations to join Fox. The combination of WSVN not following a similar pattern to other Fox affiliates at the time (which focused more on syndicated programming and movies, than news), and WCIX becoming a \"Big Three\" affiliate had also led then-struggling independent WDZL (channel 39, now [[The CW|CW]] affiliate [[WSFL-TV]]) to rise to a higher profile, as WDZL had picked up many shows that were formerly seen on WCIX (now [[WFOR-TV]] on channel 4). WSVN, meanwhile, picked up some of WCIX's movie packages, as well as a couple of cartoons that it aired on Saturday and Sunday mornings.\n\n[[Image:Svntape.JPG|205px|thumb|right|WSVN archive [[betacam]] newstape at the Florida Moving Image Archive.]]\nInstead of acquiring a large amount of off-network sitcoms and cartoons, WSVN opted to pour most of its resources into its news department and took on a news-intensive format\u2014expanding its newscasts to seven hours on weekdays\u2014a move that was pilloried at the time since its newscasts had consistently finished well behind WTVJ and WPLG in the ratings.<ref>[http://articles.sun-sentinel.com/1988-09-13/features/8802220537_1_ed-ansin-wsvn-station Emphasis On News A Bold Move For Ch. 7], ''Fort Lauderdale Sun-Sentinel'', September 13, 1988.</ref> Because of this, the station had a higher local newscast output than the rest of Fox's stations did at the time of the switch; when WSVN became a Fox affiliate, only a small number of Fox stations ran local newscasts, which were largely limited to late prime time slots (as of 2014, about \u00be of Fox's stations have morning newscasts, but only about one-third of its owned-and-operated stations and affiliates carry newscasts in either the midday or late afternoon/early evening time periods). In addition to newscasts, WSVN began to air a lot of first-run [[Broadcast syndication|syndicated]] [[talk show]]s, [[court show]]s, and off-network [[drama (film and television)|drama]] series. As Fox lacked a national evening newscast (a situation which continues to this day), the station also ran a half-hour late afternoon simulcast of [[HLN (TV channel)|CNN Headline News]] during the early and mid-1990s.\n\nThe station ran some cartoons on weekend mornings as well, it originally aired [[Fox Kids]] when Fox launched the block on September 8, 1990, however, it would become the first Fox station in the country to stop carrying the block in 1993, Fox Kids subsequently moved to WDZL, before moving again to [[WAMI-DT|WAMI]] (channel 69) in 1998, [[WBFS-TV]] (channel 33) aired the successor [[4Kids TV]] block until it ended on December 27, 2008. By coincidence, when [[New World Pictures#New World Communications (1992\u20131997)|New World Communications]] switched most of its \"Big Three\"-affiliated stations to Fox between 1994 and 1996, the programming on those stations was very similar in format to WSVN, except that their news formats may have been aimed at an older audience than WSVN's, many stations owned by New World also passed on Fox Kids just as WSVN did. In the early 1990s, the station added a few off-network sitcoms to its schedule such as ''[[Designing Women]]'', ''[[The Golden Girls]]'', and ''[[Empty Nest]]'' (the latter two being set in Miami).\n\n<!-- Deleted image removed: [[File:WSVNlogo.jpg|205px|thumb|left|WSVN's 2001-2009 news open.{{ffdc|1=WSVNlogo.jpg|log=2016 January 15}}]] -->\nAs a Fox affiliate, the station brands itself as \"WSVN 7\", rather than \"Fox 7\" under Fox's branding guidelines for its owned-and-operated stations and affiliates ([[Boston]] sister station [[WHDH (TV)|WHDH]] formerly used its affiliated network's name in its branding as \"7 NBC\" until it became an independent station in January 2017, although NBC is not as strict with station branding as Fox is), and is one of a handful of Fox affiliates that omit network references entirely from their branding. However, [[Fox News|Fox News Channel]] refers to the station as \"Fox 7\" when carrying WSVN's coverage of breaking news stories from South Florida; until its website was remodeled in late 2009, the Fox logo also occasionally appeared in a rolling marquee alongside the station's \"circle 7\" logo on the top left hand corner of the site. At the time of the 1989 switch, the network's owned-and-operated stations and certain affiliates were the only Fox stations to use full network references, while other stations\u2014like original Miami affiliate WCIX used limited to no references to Fox in their branding. Miami\u2013Fort Lauderdale is one of two U.S. television markets in which the Fox affiliation had moved from one VHF station to another (the other being [[Honolulu]], [[Hawaii]], if stations not operating as [[Broadcast relay station#Satellite stations|satellites]] are counted, as Fox charter affiliate [[KHNL]] and NBC affiliate [[KHON-TV]] swapped affiliations on January 1, 1996) and the only known instance of a longtime \"Big Three\" affiliate switching to Fox prior to its [[1994 United States broadcast TV realignment|1994 affiliation agreement]] with New World Communications and the affiliation transactions that resulted from the deal.\n\nWSVN ended programming on its analog signal, on [[Very high frequency|VHF]] channel 7, on June 12, 2009, the official date in which full-power television stations in the United States [[Digital television transition in the United States|transitioned from analog to digital broadcasts]]. The station's digital signal relocated from its pre-transition VHF channel 8 to channel 7.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://hraunfoss.fcc.gov/edocs_public/attachmatch/DA-06-1082A2.pdf |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130829004251/http://hraunfoss.fcc.gov/edocs_public/attachmatch/DA-06-1082A2.pdf |url-status=dead |archive-date=August 29, 2013 |title=DTV Tentative Channel Designations for the First and the Second Rounds |format=PDF |accessdate=March 24, 2012}}</ref> The station was one of four that operated digital signals on the VHF band to be granted a power increase later that month after stations experienced signal problems on VHF that did not occur with the [[Ultra high frequency|UHF]] band following the transition.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.broadcastingcable.com/article/307121-Boise_Station_Gets_Power_Boost.php?rssid=20068&q=digital+tv |title=Boise Station Gets Power Boost |last=Eggerton |first=John |date=June 29, 2009 |work=[[Broadcasting & Cable]] |accessdate=July 1, 2009}}</ref>\n\nOn January 14, 2012, WSVN and Boston sister stations WHDH and [[WLVI]] were pulled from [[DirecTV]] after negotiations with Sunbeam Television on a new carriage contract broke down due to a proposal to increase retransmission fees paid to the company by a reported 300%.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thestreet.com/story/11376257/1/sunbeam-television-shuts-out-directv-nfl-fans-in-miami-in-attempt-to-extract-300-percent-pay-increase.html |title=Sunbeam Television Shuts Out DIRECTV NFL Fans In Miami In Attempt To Extract 300 Percent Pay Increase |website=Thestreet.com |date=January 14, 2012 |accessdate=January 21, 2016}}</ref> In response, a [[Facebook]] page called \"Boycott WSVN\" was started to pressure businesses to pull their advertising from the station.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.facebook.com/pages/Boycott-WSVN/324011944297374?ref=ts |title=Facebook |publisher=Facebook |date= |accessdate=January 21, 2016}}</ref> However, WSVN did allow DirecTV customers to view the [[NFC Championship Game#NFC Championship Game: New York Giants 20, San Francisco 49ers 17 (OT)|NFC championship game]] and an episode of ''[[American Idol]]'' that aired immediately after the game while negotiations were still ongoing. Sunbeam and DirecTV reached a new carriage deal on January 26, 2012, ending the blackout.<ref>[http://www.wsvn.com/news/articles/local/21006531578486/sunbeam-television-and-direct-tv-reach-deal/] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120129092448/http://www.wsvn.com/news/articles/local/21006531578486/sunbeam-television-and-direct-tv-reach-deal/ |date=January 29, 2012 }}</ref>\n\nSince Fox acquired [[National Hot Rod Association]] (NHRA) broadcast rights in 2016, WSVN has constantly been the target of viewer and NHRA complaints, the station preempts ''[[NHRA Mello Yello Drag Racing Series|Fox NHRA]]'' in favor of [[infomercial]]s, resulting in the NHRA sending a formal complaint on their website.<ref>[http://www.nhra.com/news/2016/nhra-miami-fans-get-your-fox-live]</ref> This usually amounts to four NHRA events a season, including the [[NHRA U.S. Nationals|U.S. Nationals]]. The station often preempts live coverage of the NHRA and [[Germany|German]] [[Bundesliga]] [[association football|soccer]] matches to after the late news in order to retain paid programming revenue for those afternoon timeslots that Fox uses to carry prestigious sporting events.\n\nOn September 27, 2017, three workers were killed after a crane collapsed off the side of WSVN's television tower. The tower, shared with WPLG, was having to install a new transmitter for WSVN as part of the mandated FCC spectrum repack.<ref>https://www.local10.com/news/3-dead-after-scaffolding-collapses-at-miami-television-tower</ref><ref>http://www.miamiherald.com/news/local/community/miami-dade/article175737951.html</ref>\n\n===Averted loss of Fox affiliation===\nOn February 22, 2018, it was reported that [[Sinclair Broadcast Group]] would sell CW affiliate WSFL-TV to [[Fox Television Stations]] as part of its [[Proposed acquisition of Tribune Media by Sinclair Broadcast Group|larger deal]] to acquire WSFL parent [[Tribune Media]];<ref name=\"foxsinclairdeal\">{{cite web|title=21st Century Fox Finalizing Deal With Sinclair to Acquire Six TV Stations (EXCLUSIVE)|url=https://variety.com/2018/tv/news/sinclair-tribune-fox-station-deal-seattle-1202707565/|last=Littleton|first=Cynthia|periodical=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|publisher=[[Prometheus Global Media]]|date=February 22, 2018|accessdate=February 22, 2018}}</ref> the deal was officially announced on May 9, 2018.<ref name=\"foxsinclairdeal2\">{{cite web|title=21st Century Fox Buys Seven Local TV Stations From Sinclair For $910 Million|url=https://deadline.com/2018/05/21st-century-fox-buys-seven-local-tv-stations-from-sinclair-for-910-million-1202386066/|last=Hayes|first=Dade|work=[[Deadline Hollywood]]|publisher=[[Penske Media Corporation]]|date=May 9, 2018|accessdate=May 9, 2018}}</ref> A purchase of WSFL by FTS would likely result in WSFL becoming a Fox [[Owned-and-operated station|O&O]] and WSVN losing its affiliation, similar to sister station WHDH in Boston losing its NBC affiliation to WBTS-LD (now [[Telemundo]] O&O [[WYCN-LD]] in [[Providence, Rhode Island]]) after NBC purchased that station, executives at Fox parent company [[21st Century Fox]] declined to immediately announce any plans regarding WSFL in an earnings call,<ref name=\"tvs-wsflmaybefox\">{{cite news|last1=Ariens|first1=Chris|title=Fox Bosses Mum on What Will Become of WSFL|url=https://www.adweek.com/tvspy/fox-bosses-mum-on-what-will-become-of-wsfl/204024|accessdate=May 10, 2018|work=[[TVSpy]]|date=May 10, 2018}}</ref> with CEO [[Lachlan Murdoch]] stating that \"We're not making any announcements of any affiliate changes today.\"<ref name=\"b&c-wsvnnofox?\">{{cite news|last1=Lafayette|first1=Jon|title=Ansin: WSVN-TV Will Thrive Despite Fox Buying Fla. Station|url=https://www.broadcastingcable.com/news/ansin-wsvn-will-thrive-despite-fox-buying-fla-station|accessdate=May 11, 2018|work=[[Broadcasting & Cable]]|language=en-us}}</ref> On May 11, 2018, Ed Ansin stated that WSVN would remain a Fox affiliate through at least June 30, 2019 (when its affiliation contract was scheduled to expire), and that WSVN would be run as a news-intensive independent station modeled on WHDH if the Fox affiliation was lost,<ref name=\"b&c-wsvnnofox?\"/> in an interview with the ''[[Sun-Sentinel]]'', Ansin said that Fox had not informed him of its intentions, and that the station would replace Fox's prime time programming with syndicated programming and an additional newscast.<ref name=\"ss-wsvnnofox?\">{{cite news|last1=Diaz|first1=Johnny|title=Could Fox network shows find a new home on Miami-Fort Lauderdale TV?|url=http://www.sun-sentinel.com/features/fl-reg-wsvn-channel-7-may-lose-fox-affiliation-20180511-story.html|accessdate=May 11, 2018|work=[[Sun-Sentinel]]|date=May 11, 2018}}</ref>\n\nThree weeks after the FCC's July 18, 2018 vote to have the deal reviewed by an [[administrative law judge]] amid \"serious concerns\" about Sinclair's forthrightness in its applications to sell certain conflict properties, on August 9, 2018, Tribune announced it would terminate the Sinclair deal, intending to seek other [[Mergers and acquisitions|M&A]] opportunities. The termination of the said merger also made the Fox purchase of WSFL unsuccessful.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2018-07-16/fcc-rejects-sinclair-plan-for-tv-station-sales-in-tribune-deal-jjof6bcs|title=Sinclair and Tribune Fall as FCC Slams TV Station Sale Plan|author=Todd Shields|date=July 16, 2018|accessdate=July 19, 2018|agency=[[Bloomberg L.P.|Bloomberg News]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://thehill.com/policy/technology/397194-fcc-chairman-rejects-sinclair-tribune-merger|title=FCC chair rejects Sinclair-Tribune merger|author=Harper Neidig|date=July 16, 2018|newspaper=[[The Hill (newspaper)|The Hill]]|accessdate=August 9, 2018|publisher=Capitol Hill Publishing Corp.}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.robertfeder.com/2018/07/16/fcc-throws-sinclairtribune-deal-doubt/|title=FCC throws Sinclair/Tribune deal in doubt|author=[[Robert Feder]]|date=July 16, 2018|website=RobertFeder.com|accessdate=August 9, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://nymag.com/daily/intelligencer/2018/07/fcc-throws-wrench-into-sinclair-tribune-deal.html|title=FCC Throws Wrench Into Sinclair Media Megadeal|author=Benjamin Hart|date=July 16, 2018|periodical=[[New York (magazine)|New York]]|accessdate=August 9, 2018|publisher=New York Media, LLC}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2018/07/18/business/media/sinclair-tribune-fcc.html|title=Sinclair Tries to Appease F.C.C., but Its Tribune Bid Is Challenged|author=Edmund Lee|date=July 18, 2018|newspaper=The New York Times|accessdate=August 9, 2018|publisher=The New York Times Company}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.baltimoresun.com/business/bs-bz-sinclair-tribune-revised-divestitures-20180718-story.html|title=FCC orders hearing even as Sinclair changes plans to sell TV stations to address concerns about Tribune deal|author=Lorraine Mirabella|date=July 18, 2018|publisher=Tronc|accessdate=August 9, 2018|newspaper=[[Baltimore Sun]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/tribune-media-terminates-merger-agreement-with-sinclair-broadcast-group-1533810907|title=Tribune Terminates $3.9 Billion Sinclair Merger, Sues Broadcast Rival|date=August 9, 2018|newspaper=[[The Wall Street Journal]]|publisher=[[News Corp (2013\u2013present)|News Corp.]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://tvnewscheck.com/article/top-news/220320/tribune-kills-sinclair-merger/|title=Tribune Kills Sinclair Merger, Files Suit|author=Mark K. Miller|date=August 9, 2018|website=TVNewsCheck|publisher=NewsCheck Media}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.baltimoresun.com/business/bs-bz-tribune-sinclair-merger-ended-20180809-story.html#|title=Tribune Media pulls out of Sinclair Broadcast merger|author=Christopher Dinsmore|date=August 9, 2018|newspaper=[[Baltimore Sun]]|publisher=[[Tronc]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2018/08/09/business/dealbook/sinclair-tribune-media.html|title=Tribune Ends Deal With Sinclair, Dashing Plan for Conservative TV Behemoth|author=Edmund Lee|date=August 9, 2018|newspaper=The New York Times|publisher=The New York Times Company|author2=Amie Tsang}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.broadcastingcable.com/news/tribune-ends-deal-with-sinclair-files-breach-of-contract-suit|title=Tribune Ends Deal with Sinclair, Files Breach of Contract Suit|author=Jon Lafayette|date=August 9, 2018|publisher=NewBay Media|periodical=Broadcasting & Cable}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/technology/2018/08/09/tribune-withdraws-sinclair-merger-saying-it-will-sue-breach-contract/|title=Tribune withdraws from Sinclair merger, saying it will sue for \u2018breach of contract\u2019|author=Brian Fung|date=August 9, 2018|newspaper=The Washington Post|publisher=Nash Holdings LLC|author2=Tony Romm}}</ref> On December 3, 2018, [[Irving, Texas]]-based [[Nexstar Media Group]] announced it would acquire the assets of Tribune Media for $6.4 billion in cash and debt,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nexstar.tv/wp-content/uploads/2018/12/Nexstar-Tribune-Investor-Presentation-FINAL-12-3-18.pdf|title=Acquisition of Tribune Media Company|date=December 3, 2018|website=[[Nexstar Media Group]]|format=[[PDF]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://tvnewscheck.com/article/top-news/226264/nexstar-buying-tribune-media-6-4-billion/|title=Nexstar Buying Tribune Media For $6.4 Billion|author=Mark K. Miller|date=December 3, 2018|website=TVNewsCheck|publisher=NewsCheck Media}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2018/12/nexstar-tribune-media-acquisition-1202512653/|title=Nexstar Confirms $4.1B Tribune Media Acquisition To Become Leading Local TV Station Owner|author=Peter White|author2=Dade Hayes|date=December 3, 2018|website=Deadline Hollywood|publisher=Penske Media Corporation}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.chicagotribune.com/business/ct-nexstar-tribune-media-20181202-story.html|title=Nexstar to buy WGN owner Tribune Media for $4.1 billion|author=Gerry Smith|author2=Nabila Ahmed|date=December 3, 2018|publisher=[[Tribune Publishing]]|author3=Eric Newcomer|agency=[[Bloomberg L.P.|Bloomberg News]]|newspaper=[[Chicago Tribune]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-tribune-media-m-a-nexstar-media/nexstar-to-buy-tribune-media-for-4-1-billion-idUSKBN1O217Z|title=Nexstar to buy Tribune Media for $4.1 billion|author=Arjun Panchadar|author2=Sonam Rai|date=December 3, 2018|agency=[[Reuters]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.broadcastingcable.com/news/nexstar-announces-deal-to-buy-tribune-for-6-4b|title=Nexstar Announces Deal to Buy Tribune for $6.4B|author=Jon Lafayette|date=December 3, 2018|publisher=NewBay Media|periodical=Broadcasting & Cable}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.rbr.com/reuters-nexstar-gets-tribune-in-4-1b-deal/|title=It\u2019s Official: Nexstar Takes Tribune In Billion-Dollar Stock Deal|author=Adam Jacobson|date=December 3, 2018|website=Radio-Television Business Report|publisher=Streamline-RBR, Inc.}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://tvnewscheck.com/article/top-news/226264/nexstar-buying-tribune-media-6-4-billion/|title=Nexstar To Spin Off $1B In Stations|author=Harry A. Jessell|author2=Mark K. Miller|date=December 3, 2018|website=TVNewsCheck|publisher=NewsCheck Media}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://variety.com/2018/tv/news/tribune-media-acquired-nexstar-media-group-1203073621/|title=Tribune Media to Be Acquired by Nexstar Media Group|author=Cynthia Littleton|date=December 3, 2018|publisher=Penske Media Corporation|accessdate=December 4, 2018|periodical=Variety}}</ref> on March 20, 2019, WSFL was agreed to be divested to [[Cincinnati]]-based [[E. W. Scripps Company|The E. W. Scripps Company]] upon the consummation of the Nexstar-Tribune merger, as part of the company's sale of nineteen Nexstar- and Tribune-operated stations to Scripps and [[Tegna Inc.]] in separate deals worth $1.32 billion.<ref name=\"tvnc=nexstarspinoffs\">{{cite web|url=https://tvnewscheck.com/article/top-news/232391/nexstar-selling-19-tvs-in-15-markets-for-1-32b/|title=Nexstar Selling 19 TVs In 15 Markets For $1.32B|author=Mark K. Miller|date=March 20, 2019|website=TVNewsCheck|publisher=NewsCheck Media}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2019-03-20/nexstar-to-sell-19-stations-to-tegna-scripps-for-1-32-billion|title=Nexstar to Sell Stations to Tegna, Scripps for $1.32 Billion|author=Nabila Ahmed|date=March 20, 2019|publisher=[[Bloomberg, L.P.]]|author2=Anousha Sakoui|website=Bloomberg News}}</ref> On September 26, 2019, WSVN announced that it had renewed its Fox affiliation.<ref name=\"b&c-wsvnfoxrenewal\">{{cite news |last1=Lafayette |first1=Jon |title=WSVN-TV in Miami Renews Affiliation Deal with Fox |url=https://www.broadcastingcable.com/news/wsvn-tv-in-miami-renews-affiliation-deal-with-fox |accessdate=September 27, 2019 |work=[[Broadcasting & Cable]] |date=September 26, 2019 |language=en-us}}</ref>\n\n==Digital television==\n\n===Digital channels===\nThe station's digital signal is [[multiplex (TV)|multiplexed]]:\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! [[Digital subchannel#United States|Channel]]\n! [[Display resolution|Video]]\n! [[Aspect ratio (image)|Aspect]]\n! [[Program and System Information Protocol#What PSIP does|PSIP Short Name]]\n! Programming<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rabbitears.info/market.php?request=station_search&callsign=WSVN#station |title=RabbitEars.Info |website=RabbitEars.info |accessdate=January 21, 2016}}</ref>\n|-\n| 7.1 || [[720p]] || [[16:9]] || WSVN-D1 || Main WSVN programming / [[Fox Broadcasting Company|Fox]]\n|-\n| 7.2 || [[480i]] || [[4:3]] || WSVN-D2 || [[Light TV]] \n|}\n\nWSVN's second digital subchannel carried [[Estrella TV]] from its 2009 launch<ref name=\"tvnc-wsvnestrella7.2\">{{cite news|title=Estrella TV Taps WSVN as Miami Affiliate|url=http://www.tvnewscheck.com/article/31028/estrella-tv-taps-wsvn-as-miami-affiliate|accessdate=January 7, 2018|work=TVNewsCheck|date=April 7, 2009|language=en}}</ref> until July 14, 2017, when it began carrying Light TV.<ref name=\"tvbr-azawgentowpmf\">{{cite news|last1=Jacobson|first1=Adam|title=Exclusive: 'Estrella TV' Ready For A Big Miami Return|url=https://www.rbr.com/estrella-tv-miami-return/|accessdate=January 7, 2018|work=Radio & Television Business Report|date=January 5, 2018|quote=On July 14, 2017, Sunbeam Television-owned WSVN-7 dropped Estrella TV from its DT2 multicast channel, replacing it with LIGHT TV\u2026}}</ref>\n\n==Programming==\nWhen WSVN became a Fox affiliate in January 1989, its programming format was quite unusual for the network's affiliates as it did not include [[sitcom]]s as part of its schedule, it ran [[animated cartoon|cartoons]] only on weekend mornings, and aired a heavy amount of talk and court shows, some [[feature film|movies]], and some drama series. As time went on, though, most Fox stations began relying more on talk and court shows, as well as local newscasts. Channel 7 runs only a slightly heavier amount of local news programming than other Fox stations (which have gradually increased their news outputs over the last 15 years). WSVN continues not to feature any sitcoms as part of its syndication inventory, somewhat atypical for a news-intensive Fox station.\n\n===Sports programming===\nIn 1966, with the establishment of the [[Miami Dolphins]] of the [[American Football League]], the station, via [[NFL on NBC|NBC]], which held the league's broadcast rights, became the station of record for the new team. WVSN provided coverage of the Dolphins' victory in [[Super Bowl VII]] after their [[1972 Miami Dolphins season|perfect season in 1972]]. This alliance continued until the end of the [[1988 Miami Dolphins season|1988 season]], when most games moved over to WTVJ (today, most games are aired by WFOR). Since 1994, the station airs at least two Dolphins games a season via the [[Fox NFL|NFL on Fox]], usually when the team plays host to an [[National Football Conference|NFC]] team at [[Hard Rock Stadium]], however, starting in [[2014 Miami Dolphins season|2014]], with the institution of the NFL's new broadcast 'cross-flex' rules, more games can be seen on Channel 7 when they are moved from WFOR, and since 2018, via Fox's exclusive contract, [[Thursday Night Football]] games. In addition, any [[Miami Marlins]] games featured as part of Fox's MLB broadcast contract are aired on channel 7, this included their victory in the [[2003 World Series]], when the team was still the Florida Marlins. The station was also the local broadcaster of [[Super Bowl LIV]] which was held at Hard Rock Stadium, as Fox [[NFL on Fox|had the national television rights]] to the game; it also previously served as the home broadcaster of [[Super Bowl XXXIII]] which was also on Fox.\n\n==News operation==\nWSVN presently broadcasts 63\u00bd hours of locally produced newscasts each week (with 10\u00bd hours each weekday, six hours on Saturdays and five hours on Sundays), in regards to the number of hours devoted to news programming, it is the highest local newscast output of any local television station in Miami. Unlike other news-intensive Fox stations, WSVN carries newscasts at 5:00 p.m., 6:00 p.m., and 6:30 p.m. on both Saturdays and Sundays (others either air early evening newscasts on weekends at different times on Saturdays and Sundays [i.e., Saturdays at 6:00 p.m. and Sundays at 5:00 p.m.], air them either at only 5:00 p.m. or 6:00 p.m. on both nights or do not carry newscasts in that particular weekend time period at all), however, WSVN's weekend 5:00 p.m. and 6:00 p.m. newscasts are subject to preemption and/or delay due to network sports telecasts running into the timeslot. In addition, the station produces the entertainment news/lifestyle program ''[[Deco Drive]]'' (which airs at 7:30 p.m. weeknights). The station is affiliated with [[CNN]] for news.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Allen|first1=Keith|last2=Preuss|first2=Andreas|title=Millions of dollars found stashed in buckets at Miami home, police say|url=http://www.cnn.com/2016/06/30/us/florida-cash-drugs-gun-found-in-home/|accessdate=June 30, 2016|work=CNN|date=June 30, 2016|quote=...told CNN affiliate WSVN.}}</ref>\n\nWhen the station gained the Fox affiliation on January 1, 1989, it retained a news schedule similar to the one it had as an NBC affiliate, in its early years with Fox, local news programming on the station ran on weekdays from 6:00 a.m. to 9:00 a.m., Noon to 1:00 p.m., 5:00 p.m. to 7:00 p.m., weekends from 6:00 p.m. to 6:30 p.m. and nightly from 10:00 p.m. to 11:00 p.m. The station became the second Fox affiliate to have a weekday morning newscast as a result and was the first one with weeknight 5:00 p.m. and 6:00 p.m. newscasts. On the date of the network switch, WSVN debuted a locally produced early evening [[newsmagazine|news magazine]] program, ''Inside Story'', the program eventually evolved into its present entertainment-based format as ''7:30'' (in reference to its timeslot) in 1994, and later changed its title to the current ''Deco Drive'' in 1996.\n\nUnder [[news director]] [[Joel Cheatwood]], WSVN became well known in South Florida, and throughout the nation, for its emphasis on crime stories and sensationalistic reporting\u2014summarized in the phrase, \"if it bleeds, it leads.\"<ref>{{cite news|last=Jicha|first=Tom|title=News Show To Get WSVN's Familiar Tabloid Touch|url=http://articles.sun-sentinel.com/1991-03-29/features/9101160152_1_newscast-joel-cheatwood-wsvn|accessdate=July 9, 2012|newspaper=[[Sun-Sentinel|Fort Lauderdale Sun-Sentinel]]|date=March 29, 1991}}</ref> Although this embrace of [[tabloid television]] was criticized, it rejuvenated a station that had languished in third place for most of its tenure with NBC. Within a few years, with anchor Rick Sanchez at the helm, WSVN became the market's highest-rated English-language station from sign-on to sign-off,<ref>http://www.flnewscenter.com/archives/696.html</ref> a rank it would hold for the better part of two decades until it was overtaken for the title by WFOR, though WSVN has been a solid runner-up and has tied for second with WPLG.\n\n[[Image:WSVN HD.JPG|225px|thumb|left|WSVN's Pre-2015 HD Newsplex studio.]]\nWSVN's success also influenced how newscasts on other Fox affiliates would look in later years; the station's decision to take on a news-intensive schedule would eventually serve as the template for the programming formats of the former \"Big Three\" stations that switched to Fox as a result of its 1994 affiliation agreement with New World Communications and certain transactions related to the deal, and was gradually adopted by many heritage Fox stations and certain news-producing stations that are not affiliated with the network, NBC, CBS or ABC. It was also the first station to take a cue from CNN, integrating its newsroom and studio into one large area, which the station has termed the \"newsplex\". It evolved out of their initial two sets around the time of the network switch in the late 1980s: one used for its morning and 5:00 p.m. newscasts, which was a small, enclosed area in the newsroom, and its main set, which was positioned in the station's control room. Other stations and networks, both in the U.S. and internationally, have taken cues from WSVN's set. The overall format was successful enough in Miami that in 1993, Ed Ansin assigned Cheatwood to overhaul Sunbeam's newly acquired Boston station WHDH, incorporating a considerably watered-down version of the WSVN format for its newscasts; as in Miami, the tabloid style helped WHDH rise from a perennial third place into a contender for first in the news ratings (against the more traditional [[WCVB-TV]]). WHDH uses many visual cues taken from WSVN including the use of flashy graphics, distinct music packages composed by Chris Crane (who has composed the various custom news themes used by WSVN since 1991) and a similarly designed \"newsplex\" set; WSVN's \"circle 7\" logo was also adopted by WHDH after Sunbeam assumed ownership. A similar format was adopted by [[KJRH-TV]] in [[Tulsa, Oklahoma]] between 1994 and 1997, that station has since reverted to airing traditional newscasts.\n\nThe station's 11:00 p.m. newscast evolved into an hour-long 10:00 p.m. program after it joined Fox, but was revived in 1995 as a 15-minute wrap-up of the proceedings in the [[O.J. Simpson murder case]], and expanded to a half-hour the following year, the 11:00 p.m. newscast expanded to weekend evenings on September 26, 2009.<ref name=\"wsvn-weekend11pmadd\">{{cite news|url=http://www.wsvn.com/news/articles/local/MI132150/|title=WSVN-TV Announces More News at the News Station|date=September 23, 2009|work=WSVN.com|accessdate=September 23, 2009|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090926031340/http://www1.wsvn.com/news/articles/local/MI132150|archive-date=September 26, 2009|url-status=dead}}</ref> The station debuted a half-hour 4:00 p.m. newscast on September 11, 2006,<ref>{{cite news| url=http://southflorida.bizjournals.com/southflorida/stories/2006/09/04/story4.html | first=Brian | last=Bandell | title=More news is good news for WSVN Channel 7 | date=September 4, 2006}}</ref> which later expanded to one hour in 2007. On January 11, 2009, starting with its 5:00 p.m. newscast, WSVN became the second station in the Miami market (behind WTVJ) to begin broadcasting its local newscasts in [[High-definition television|high definition]]. With the switch to HD, came an updated newsplex set that premiered two weeks earlier on December 29, 2008 and new HD graphics. On July 11, 2010, WSVN expanded its Saturday and Sunday 6:00 p.m. newscasts to one hour with the addition of half-hour newscasts at 6:30 p.m.<ref>[http://www.tvnewscheck.com/articles/2010/06/21/daily.9/ WSVN Adding More Weekend News]{{Dead link|date=September 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}, TVNewsCheck.com, June 21, 2010. Accessed October 19, 2010.</ref> On August 22, 2011, WSVN added a fifth hour (from 9:00 p.m. to 10:00 a.m.) to the weekday edition of ''Today in Florida'', by way of the move of ''[[Live! with Kelly and Michael|Live! with Regis and Kelly]]'' to WPLG.<ref>[http://www.tvnewscheck.com/article/2011/08/09/53130/wsvn-miami-expands-morning-news-block WSVN Miami Expands Morning News Block], ''TVNewsCheck'', August 9, 2011.</ref> On Sunday, September 13, 2015, the station expanded its ''Today in Florida'' newscast to Sunday mornings airing from 8:00 a.m. to 11:00 a.m. The latest addition now brings the total newscast output to 64 1/2 hours per week.\n\n===On-air staff===\n\n====Notable former on-air staff====\n{{div col|colwidth=25em}}\n* [[Jim Berry (news anchor)|Jim Berry]] &ndash; sports anchor (now morning news anchor at [[WFOR-TV]], also in Miami) \n* [[Ann Bishop (journalist)|Ann Bishop]] &ndash; script writer (moved to [[WPLG]]/[[Miami]] and became a legendary anchor, died November 14, 1997)\n* [[Penny Daniels]] &ndash; anchor/reporter (retired)\n* [[Donna Hanover]] &ndash; (ex-wife of former New York City mayor [[Rudy Giuliani]])\n* [[Robb Hanrahan]] &ndash; evening anchor (later at [[WABC-TV]]/[[New York City]], now at [[WHP-TV]]/[[Harrisburg, Pennsylvania]])\n* [[Jackie Johnson]] &ndash; meteorologist (now at [[KCBS-TV]]/[[Los Angeles]])\n* [[Alycia Lane]] &ndash; (later at [[KYW-TV]]/[[Philadelphia]], last at [[KNBC]]/Los Angeles)\n* [[Rick Leventhal]] &ndash; (now at [[Fox News Channel]])\n* [[Elita Loresca]] &ndash; meteorologist (now at [[KTRK-TV]] in Houston)\n* [[Joan Lovett]] &ndash; anchor/reporter (later at [[WBBM-TV]]/[[Chicago]])\n* [[Robin Meade]] &ndash; anchor/reporter (now at [[HLN (TV channel)|HLN]])\n* [[Marilyn Mitzel]] &ndash; anchor/reporter (1988\u20132005)\n* [[Charles Perez]] &ndash; anchor/reporter (later at [[WABC-TV]]/[[New York City]], then at WPLG/Miami; retired)\n* [[Jillian Reynolds|Jillian Warry (Reynolds)]] &ndash; meteorologist (later at [[KTTV]]/Los Angeles)\n* [[Shaun Robinson]] &ndash; (later weekend anchor/correspondent for syndicated entertainment newsmagazine ''[[Access Hollywood]]'')\n* [[Rick Sanchez (journalist)|Rick Sanchez]] &ndash; (later at [[MSNBC]] and then [[CNN]]; [[WIOD]] and [[WJAN-CD]] in Miami/Fort Lauderdale; now at [[RT America]])\n* [[Shepard Smith]] &ndash; (now at [[Fox News Channel]])\n* [[Stephanie Stahl (reporter)|Stephanie Stahl]] &ndash; anchor (later and now at KYW-TV in Philadelphia for health and science reporter)\n* [[Linda Stouffer]] &ndash; (now at HLN; went by Cinnamon Stouffer during her stint at WSVN)\n* [[Michelle Tuzee]] &ndash; (now anchor at [[KABC-TV]]/Los Angeles)\n{{div col end}}\n\n==Other notes==\n* WSVN's newscasts were featured in at least two movies, ''[[The Mean Season]]'' (1985) and ''[[Flight of the Navigator]]'' (1986). WSVN can also be seen in several episodes of ''[[Miami Vice]]'' before the NBC affiliation for the Miami market moved to WTVJ towards the end of the show's run.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{official website|https://wsvn.com/}}\n*{{TVQ|WSVN}}\n\n{{Miami TV}}\n{{Fox Florida}}\n{{Sunbeam Television}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Wsvn}}\n[[Category:Television stations in Miami|SVN]]\n[[Category:Fox network affiliates]]\n[[Category:Light TV affiliates]]\n[[Category:Television channels and stations established in 1956]]\n[[Category:Television channels and stations established in 1962]]\n[[Category:1956 establishments in Florida]]\n[[Category:National Football League primary television stations]]\n[[Category:Miami Dolphins broadcasters]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Fox affiliate in Miami}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=March 2019}}\n<!-- Do NOT post content from NewsBlues.com, as it is NOT a reliable source. -->\n{{Refimprove|date=January 2017}}\n{{Infobox broadcast\n| call_letters             = WSVN\n| station_logo             = WSVN 7 Miami logo.png\n| logo_size                = 175px\n| location                 = [[Miami]]\u2013[[Fort Lauderdale, Florida]]\n| country                  = United States\n| city                     = Miami, Florida\n| station_branding         = '''general:''' WSVN 7<br>'''newscasts:''' ''7 News''\n| station_slogan           = ''The News Station''\n| digital                  = 9 ([[very high frequency|VHF]])\n| virtual                  = 7 ([[Program and System Information Protocol|PSIP]])\n| affiliations             = {{ubl|'''7.1:''' [[Fox Broadcasting Company|Fox]]|'''7.2:''' [[Light TV]]}}\n| owner                    = [[Sunbeam Television|Sunbeam Television Corporation]]\n| licensee                 = \n| airdate                  = {{start date and age|1956|7|29|p=y}}<br>''(current license dates from December 19, 1962)''\n| callsign_meaning         = Channel '''S'''e'''V'''e'''N'''\n| sister_stations          = \n| former_callsigns         = WCKT (1956\u20131983)\n| former_channel_numbers   = {{ubl|'''Analog:'''|7 (VHF, 1956\u20132009)|'''Digital:'''|8 (VHF, 2000\u20132009)|7 (VHF, 2009\u20132019)}}\n| former_affiliations      = {{ubl|'''Primary:'''|[[NBC]] (1956\u20131988)|'''Secondary:'''|[[American Broadcasting Company|ABC]] (1956\u20131957)|'''DT2:'''|[[Estrella TV]] (2009\u20132017)}}\n| effective_radiated_power = 158 [[kilowatt|kW]]\n| HAAT                     = {{convert|307.1|m|ft|0|abbr=on}}\n| facility_id              = 63840\n| coordinates              = {{nowrap|{{coord|25|58|1|N|80|12|42|W|type:landmark_scale:2000|display=inline, title}}}}\n| licensing_authority      = [[Federal Communications Commission|FCC]]\n| homepage                 = {{URL|https://wsvn.com/}}\n}}\n\n'''WSVN''', [[virtual channel]] 7 ([[Very high frequency|VHF]] [[digital terrestrial television|digital]] channel 9), is a [[Fox Broadcasting Company|Fox]]-[[network affiliate|affiliated]] [[television station]] [[city of license|licensed]] to [[Miami|Miami, Florida]], United States and also serving [[Fort Lauderdale, Florida|Fort Lauderdale]]. It is the [[flagship (broadcasting)|flagship station]] of locally based [[Sunbeam Television]]. WSVN's studios are located on 79th Street Causeway ([[Florida State Road 934|SR 934]]) in [[North Bay Village, Florida|North Bay Village]] (though with a Miami [[United States Postal Service|postal]] address), and its transmitter is located in north [[Miami\u2013Dade County, Florida|Miami\u2013Dade County]].\n\n==History==\n\n===WCKT===\nThe station first signed on the air on July 29, 1956 as '''WCKT'''. Originally operating as an [[NBC]] affiliate, it was founded by the Biscayne Television Corporation, a partnership between the [[Cox Enterprises|Cox]] and [[Knight Ridder|Knight]] publishing families (from which the original call letters were derived ['''C'''ox '''K'''night '''T'''elevision]), who respectively owned Miami's two major newspapers: the now-defunct ''[[The Miami News|Miami News]]'' and the still-operating ''[[The Miami Herald|Miami Herald]]''. The same Cox/Knight partnership also owned WCKR radio (610 AM, now [[WIOD]], and 97.3 FM, now [[WFLC]]). Niles Trammell, a former NBC president, held a 15 percent ownership interest in WCKT.\n\nBefore WCKT signed on, NBC programming had been carried on [[Fort Lauderdale, Florida|Fort Lauderdale]]'s WFTL-TV (channel 23, later known as WGBS-TV after it had been acquired by [[Storer Broadcasting]]), which also held a secondary affiliation with the [[DuMont Television Network]]. However, WFTL struggled because television sets were not required to have UHF tuning capability (the [[Federal Communications Commission]] (FCC) would later [[All-Channel Receiver Act|require such tuners to be included]] in sets manufactured from 1964 onward). It didn't help matters that much of the area particularly Fort Lauderdale got a fairly strong signal from WJNO-TV (channel 5, now [[WPTV-TV|WPTV]]) in [[West Palm Beach, Florida|West Palm Beach]]. When the Cox/Knight partnership won a [[construction permit]] and [[broadcast license]] to operate a station on VHF channel 7, NBC quickly agreed to move its affiliation to WCKT, since WCKR radio had been the longtime Miami affiliate of the [[Blue Network|NBC Blue Network]] (the forerunner to today's [[American Broadcasting Company]] (ABC)). Until WPST-TV (channel 10, now [[WPLG]]) signed on in August 1957, WCKT also shared ABC programming with [[WTVJ]] (channel 4), as part of an arrangement with the network to provide its programming throughout the [[media market|market]] as television sets were not required to have UHF tuning capability at the time, preventing many in the area from receiving the market's original ABC affiliate, WITV (channel 17). Channel 23 became an [[Independent station (North America)|independent station]] and eventually went dark, and later came back to the air in 1967 as WAJA-TV (it is now [[Univision]] flagship [[WLTV-DT]]).\n\nIn 1962, the Cox/Knight/Trammell partnership was stripped of its broadcast licenses due to violations of the FCC's licensing rules and ethics violations. In hearings that began in June 1960, it was found that some of the principals of Biscayne Television, as well as some of James Cox's personal friends, had made improper contact with FCC commissioner Richard Mack in order to influence the awarding of the construction permit and licenses. Biscayne had competed for the license with two other applicants, East Coast Television and South Florida TV. Mack had also been found guilty of taking payoffs and was forced to resign by [[President of the United States|President]] [[Dwight D. Eisenhower]], as well as the rest of the FCC commissioners.\n\nBiscayne Television originally planned to appeal its license revocation, but was advised that the appeal would be turned down due to the gravity of the situation. Mack had also been found guilty of taking payoffs in the licensing process WPST, to the broadcasting subsidiary of [[National Airlines (NA)|National Airlines]]. WPST had its license revoked and Biscayne then opted to put WCKT up for sale. The owners of WPST were forced to sell the station only after they had to cease broadcasting.\n\n===Sunbeam Television ownership===\nShortly afterward, a new company called [[Sunbeam Television|Sunbeam Television Corporation]] bought the station for $3.4 million and assumed ownership of channel 7 on December 19, 1962. Upon the change in ownership, Sunbeam retained the WCKT call letters and claimed the Cox/Knight station's history as its own. Sunbeam was a partnership between [[Miami Beach, Florida|Miami Beach]]-based real estate developer Sydney Ansin, and his son [[Edmund Ansin]]. The younger Ansin succeeded his father as president of Sunbeam Television in 1971. The station began using its own version of the [[circle 7 logo]] (which is moderately similar to the version originally created for ABC's owned-and-operated stations, but with the \"7\" not connected to the circle and being somewhat shaped differently) in the mid-1970s. On June 7, 1983, the station's callsign was changed to the current '''WSVN''', after those call letters were acquired from a [[PBS]] satellite [[Blue Ridge PBS|member station]] in [[Norton, Virginia]] (which subsequently became WSBN-TV; it has since [[Dark (broadcasting)|gone off the air]]).\n\nAs an NBC affiliate, WCKT/WSVN aired a local newscast in place of programs that NBC had aired at noon on weekdays. It also occasionally preempted network shows that aired during the 10:00 a.m. or 11:00 a.m. timeslot (but ran at least one of these hours) and preempted an occasional prime time program. While NBC was traditionally far less tolerant of program preemptions than the other major broadcast networks, it did not mind this at first provided that the network was able to get Miami area independent stations to air whatever programs that WSVN chose not to air. In addition, NBC programs that were not broadcast by WSVN were cleared by WPTV, whose signal provides city-grade coverage of Fort Lauderdale and was available on nearly every [[cable television|cable]] provider in the area. However, in the early 1980s, WPTV was removed from some Miami area cable systems to make room for new channels due to limited [[cable television headend|headend]] channel capacity. Largely due to those preemptions, WCKT/WSVN was one of NBC's weaker affiliates. Though NBC continued to arrange for independent stations to air network programs that were not shown on WSVN, the network grew increasingly annoyed at having to resort to such an arrangement in what had grown into a major market. NBC eventually decided that it needed to [[owned-and-operated station|acquire its own station]] in the growing [[South Florida metropolitan area|South Florida]] market.\n\n====Network affiliation switch====\nNBC got its chance at owning a station in the late 1980s, when [[Kohlberg Kravis Roberts]] put [[CBS]] affiliate WTVJ (then on channel 4, now on channel 6) on the market. NBC's then-corporate parent [[General Electric]] purchased that station in 1987, but WTVJ's affiliation contract with CBS was not set to expire until December 1988. CBS was willing to let WTVJ out of its contract one year early. However, Ed Ansin was not interested in letting NBC out of its affiliation agreement with WSVN, which also expired at the same time; Ansin even made an unsuccessful petition to the FCC to stop NBC's purchase of WTVJ.<ref>{{cite web|author= |url=http://articles.sun-sentinel.com/1987-03-11/business/8701150881_1_station-owner-ed-ansin-channel |title=Channel 7 Fights Sale Of Rival Tv Station`s Owner Wants Channel 4 Deal Stopped  |website=Sun-Sentinel |date=March 11, 1987 |accessdate=January 21, 2016}}</ref><ref>[http://www.americanradiohistory.com/Archive-BC-IDX/87-OCR/BC-1987-03-16-Page-0041.pdf] {{dead link|date=January 2016}}</ref><ref>[http://www.americanradiohistory.com/Archive-BC-IDX/87-OCR/BC-1987-03-16-Page-0042.pdf] {{dead link|date=January 2016}}</ref> He wanted channel 7 to air NBC's strong fall 1988 lineup, which included the network's coverage of [[Major League Baseball]]'s [[1988 World Series|World Series]] and the [[1988 Summer Olympics|Summer Olympics]].\n\nAs a result, NBC was forced to run WTVJ as a CBS affiliate for more than a year, with all of the NBC shows that were preempted by WSVN airing on WTVJ instead. This  situation did not sit well with either network. Ansin made an offer to take the CBS affiliation, but CBS turned the offer down.<ref>[http://articles.sun-sentinel.com/1988-06-19/business/8802050663_1_affiliates-convention-nbc-affiliation-affiliate-stations CBS Snubs WTVJ, Network Affiliation Flap Is Setting Precedents], ''Fort Lauderdale Sun-Sentinel'', June 19, 1988.</ref> Instead, CBS bought Miami's longtime independent station and original [[Fox Broadcasting Company|Fox]] affiliate, WCIX channel 6, even though that station had an inadequate signal in [[Broward County, Florida|Broward County]] (WCIX's transmitter was located in [[Homestead, Florida|Homestead]], farther southwest than those of other Miami area stations, to avoid signal interference with WCPX-TV (now [[WKMG-TV]]) in [[Orlando, Florida|Orlando]] and WPTV). In May 1988, Ed Ansin filed an antitrust lawsuit against General Electric/NBC and CBS, one week after he had claimed that CBS backed out of contract negotiations to affiliate with WSVN.<ref>[http://articles.sun-sentinel.com/1988-05-07/business/8801280416_1_two-networks-wsvn-nbc WSVN Owner Files Suit Against Networks, Firm], ''Fort Lauderdale Sun-Sentinel'', May 7, 1988.</ref> With WCIX planning to switch to CBS at the start of 1989, Fox began negotiations with other area stations to carry its programming. It ultimately reached an agreement with Sunbeam Television to affiliate with channel 7.\n\n====Fox affiliation====\nOn [[New Year's Day|January 1]], 1989, South Florida's first network affiliation switch occurred, with NBC moving to WTVJ full-time and WSVN taking the Fox affiliation. Channel 7 had far fewer network shows to preempt as a result, as Fox only ran prime time programming on weekends at the time and would not air an entire week's worth of programming until 1993. As a result, WSVN was for essential intents and purposes programmed as a ''de facto'' independent station (even referring to itself as such in promotions regarding the switch, despite still being affiliated with a network). Until Fox began airing programming every weeknight, WSVN aired a movie in prime time at 8:00 p.m. on nights where network programming was not scheduled to air. WSVN's affiliation with Fox could be seen as a major coup for the fledgling network, as WSVN had been a longtime NBC affiliate and Fox was pleased to affiliate with a station that had been with a \"[[Big Three television networks|Big Three]]\" network for years. At the time, WSVN was one of the largest heritage \"Big Three\" stations to join Fox. The combination of WSVN not following a similar pattern to other Fox affiliates at the time (which focused more on syndicated programming and movies, than news), and WCIX becoming a \"Big Three\" affiliate had also led then-struggling independent WDZL (channel 39, now [[The CW|CW]] affiliate [[WSFL-TV]]) to rise to a higher profile, as WDZL had picked up many shows that were formerly seen on WCIX (now [[WFOR-TV]] on channel 4). WSVN, meanwhile, picked up some of WCIX's movie packages, as well as a couple of cartoons that it aired on Saturday and Sunday mornings.\n\n[[Image:Svntape.JPG|205px|thumb|right|WSVN archive [[betacam]] newstape at the Florida Moving Image Archive.]]\nInstead of acquiring a large amount of off-network sitcoms and cartoons, WSVN opted to pour most of its resources into its news department and took on a news-intensive format\u2014expanding its newscasts to seven hours on weekdays\u2014a move that was pilloried at the time since its newscasts had consistently finished well behind WTVJ and WPLG in the ratings.<ref>[http://articles.sun-sentinel.com/1988-09-13/features/8802220537_1_ed-ansin-wsvn-station Emphasis On News A Bold Move For Ch. 7], ''Fort Lauderdale Sun-Sentinel'', September 13, 1988.</ref> Because of this, the station had a higher local newscast output than the rest of Fox's stations did at the time of the switch; when WSVN became a Fox affiliate, only a small number of Fox stations ran local newscasts, which were largely limited to late prime time slots (as of 2014, about \u00be of Fox's stations have morning newscasts, but only about one-third of its owned-and-operated stations and affiliates carry newscasts in either the midday or late afternoon/early evening time periods). In addition to newscasts, WSVN began to air a lot of first-run [[Broadcast syndication|syndicated]] [[talk show]]s, [[court show]]s, and off-network [[drama (film and television)|drama]] series. As Fox lacked a national evening newscast (a situation which continues to this day), the station also ran a half-hour late afternoon simulcast of [[HLN (TV channel)|CNN Headline News]] during the early and mid-1990s.\n\nThe station ran some cartoons on weekend mornings as well, it originally aired [[Fox Kids]] when Fox launched the block on September 8, 1990, however, it would become the first Fox station in the country to stop carrying the block in 1993, Fox Kids subsequently moved to WDZL, before moving again to [[WAMI-DT|WAMI]] (channel 69) in 1998, [[WBFS-TV]] (channel 33) aired the successor [[4Kids TV]] block until it ended on December 27, 2008. By coincidence, when [[New World Pictures#New World Communications (1992\u20131997)|New World Communications]] switched most of its \"Big Three\"-affiliated stations to Fox between 1994 and 1996, the programming on those stations was very similar in format to WSVN, except that their news formats may have been aimed at an older audience than WSVN's, many stations owned by New World also passed on Fox Kids just as WSVN did. In the early 1990s, the station added a few off-network sitcoms to its schedule such as ''[[Designing Women]]'', ''[[The Golden Girls]]'', and ''[[Empty Nest]]'' (the latter two being set in Miami).\n\n<!-- Deleted image removed: [[File:WSVNlogo.jpg|205px|thumb|left|WSVN's 2001-2009 news open.{{ffdc|1=WSVNlogo.jpg|log=2016 January 15}}]] -->\nAs a Fox affiliate, the station brands itself as \"WSVN 7\", rather than \"Fox 7\" under Fox's branding guidelines for its owned-and-operated stations and affiliates ([[Boston]] sister station [[WHDH (TV)|WHDH]] formerly used its affiliated network's name in its branding as \"7 NBC\" until it became an independent station in January 2017, although NBC is not as strict with station branding as Fox is), and is one of a handful of Fox affiliates that omit network references entirely from their branding. However, [[Fox News|Fox News Channel]] refers to the station as \"Fox 7\" when carrying WSVN's coverage of breaking news stories from South Florida; until its website was remodeled in late 2009, the Fox logo also occasionally appeared in a rolling marquee alongside the station's \"circle 7\" logo on the top left hand corner of the site. At the time of the 1989 switch, the network's owned-and-operated stations and certain affiliates were the only Fox stations to use full network references, while other stations\u2014like original Miami affiliate WCIX used limited to no references to Fox in their branding. Miami\u2013Fort Lauderdale is one of two U.S. television markets in which the Fox affiliation had moved from one VHF station to another (the other being [[Honolulu]], [[Hawaii]], if stations not operating as [[Broadcast relay station#Satellite stations|satellites]] are counted, as Fox charter affiliate [[KHNL]] and NBC affiliate [[KHON-TV]] swapped affiliations on January 1, 1996) and the only known instance of a longtime \"Big Three\" affiliate switching to Fox prior to its [[1994 United States broadcast TV realignment|1994 affiliation agreement]] with New World Communications and the affiliation transactions that resulted from the deal.\n\nWSVN ended programming on its analog signal, on [[Very high frequency|VHF]] channel 7, on June 12, 2009, the official date in which full-power television stations in the United States [[Digital television transition in the United States|transitioned from analog to digital broadcasts]]. The station's digital signal relocated from its pre-transition VHF channel 8 to channel 7.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://hraunfoss.fcc.gov/edocs_public/attachmatch/DA-06-1082A2.pdf |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130829004251/http://hraunfoss.fcc.gov/edocs_public/attachmatch/DA-06-1082A2.pdf |url-status=dead |archive-date=August 29, 2013 |title=DTV Tentative Channel Designations for the First and the Second Rounds |format=PDF |accessdate=March 24, 2012}}</ref> The station was one of four that operated digital signals on the VHF band to be granted a power increase later that month after stations experienced signal problems on VHF that did not occur with the [[Ultra high frequency|UHF]] band following the transition.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.broadcastingcable.com/article/307121-Boise_Station_Gets_Power_Boost.php?rssid=20068&q=digital+tv |title=Boise Station Gets Power Boost |last=Eggerton |first=John |date=June 29, 2009 |work=[[Broadcasting & Cable]] |accessdate=July 1, 2009}}</ref>\n\nOn January 14, 2012, WSVN and Boston sister stations WHDH and [[WLVI]] were pulled from [[DirecTV]] after negotiations with Sunbeam Television on a new carriage contract broke down due to a proposal to increase retransmission fees paid to the company by a reported 300%.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thestreet.com/story/11376257/1/sunbeam-television-shuts-out-directv-nfl-fans-in-miami-in-attempt-to-extract-300-percent-pay-increase.html |title=Sunbeam Television Shuts Out DIRECTV NFL Fans In Miami In Attempt To Extract 300 Percent Pay Increase |website=Thestreet.com |date=January 14, 2012 |accessdate=January 21, 2016}}</ref> In response, a [[Facebook]] page called \"Boycott WSVN\" was started to pressure businesses to pull their advertising from the station.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.facebook.com/pages/Boycott-WSVN/324011944297374?ref=ts |title=Facebook |publisher=Facebook |date= |accessdate=January 21, 2016}}</ref> However, WSVN did allow DirecTV customers to view the [[NFC Championship Game#NFC Championship Game: New York Giants 20, San Francisco 49ers 17 (OT)|NFC championship game]] and an episode of ''[[American Idol]]'' that aired immediately after the game while negotiations were still ongoing. Sunbeam and DirecTV reached a new carriage deal on January 26, 2012, ending the blackout.<ref>[http://www.wsvn.com/news/articles/local/21006531578486/sunbeam-television-and-direct-tv-reach-deal/] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120129092448/http://www.wsvn.com/news/articles/local/21006531578486/sunbeam-television-and-direct-tv-reach-deal/ |date=January 29, 2012 }}</ref>\n\nSince Fox acquired [[National Hot Rod Association]] (NHRA) broadcast rights in 2016, WSVN has constantly been the target of viewer and NHRA complaints, the station preempts ''[[NHRA Mello Yello Drag Racing Series|Fox NHRA]]'' in favor of [[infomercial]]s, resulting in the NHRA sending a formal complaint on their website.<ref>[http://www.nhra.com/news/2016/nhra-miami-fans-get-your-fox-live]</ref> This usually amounts to four NHRA events a season, including the [[NHRA U.S. Nationals|U.S. Nationals]]. The station often preempts live coverage of the NHRA and [[Germany|German]] [[Bundesliga]] [[association football|soccer]] matches to after the late news in order to retain paid programming revenue for those afternoon timeslots that Fox uses to carry prestigious sporting events.\n\nOn September 27, 2017, three workers were killed after a crane collapsed off the side of WSVN's television tower. The tower, shared with WPLG, was having to install a new transmitter for WSVN as part of the mandated FCC spectrum repack.<ref>https://www.local10.com/news/3-dead-after-scaffolding-collapses-at-miami-television-tower</ref><ref>http://www.miamiherald.com/news/local/community/miami-dade/article175737951.html</ref>\n\n===Averted loss of Fox affiliation===\nOn February 22, 2018, it was reported that [[Sinclair Broadcast Group]] would sell CW affiliate WSFL-TV to [[Fox Television Stations]] as part of its [[Proposed acquisition of Tribune Media by Sinclair Broadcast Group|larger deal]] to acquire WSFL parent [[Tribune Media]];<ref name=\"foxsinclairdeal\">{{cite web|title=21st Century Fox Finalizing Deal With Sinclair to Acquire Six TV Stations (EXCLUSIVE)|url=https://variety.com/2018/tv/news/sinclair-tribune-fox-station-deal-seattle-1202707565/|last=Littleton|first=Cynthia|periodical=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|publisher=[[Prometheus Global Media]]|date=February 22, 2018|accessdate=February 22, 2018}}</ref> the deal was officially announced on May 9, 2018.<ref name=\"foxsinclairdeal2\">{{cite web|title=21st Century Fox Buys Seven Local TV Stations From Sinclair For $910 Million|url=https://deadline.com/2018/05/21st-century-fox-buys-seven-local-tv-stations-from-sinclair-for-910-million-1202386066/|last=Hayes|first=Dade|work=[[Deadline Hollywood]]|publisher=[[Penske Media Corporation]]|date=May 9, 2018|accessdate=May 9, 2018}}</ref> A purchase of WSFL by FTS would likely result in WSFL becoming a Fox [[Owned-and-operated station|O&O]] and WSVN losing its affiliation, similar to sister station WHDH in Boston losing its NBC affiliation to WBTS-LD (now [[Telemundo]] O&O [[WYCN-LD]] in [[Providence, Rhode Island]]) after NBC purchased that station, executives at Fox parent company [[21st Century Fox]] declined to immediately announce any plans regarding WSFL in an earnings call,<ref name=\"tvs-wsflmaybefox\">{{cite news|last1=Ariens|first1=Chris|title=Fox Bosses Mum on What Will Become of WSFL|url=https://www.adweek.com/tvspy/fox-bosses-mum-on-what-will-become-of-wsfl/204024|accessdate=May 10, 2018|work=[[TVSpy]]|date=May 10, 2018}}</ref> with CEO [[Lachlan Murdoch]] stating that \"We're not making any announcements of any affiliate changes today.\"<ref name=\"b&c-wsvnnofox?\">{{cite news|last1=Lafayette|first1=Jon|title=Ansin: WSVN-TV Will Thrive Despite Fox Buying Fla. Station|url=https://www.broadcastingcable.com/news/ansin-wsvn-will-thrive-despite-fox-buying-fla-station|accessdate=May 11, 2018|work=[[Broadcasting & Cable]]|language=en-us}}</ref> On May 11, 2018, Ed Ansin stated that WSVN would remain a Fox affiliate through at least June 30, 2019 (when its affiliation contract was scheduled to expire), and that WSVN would be run as a news-intensive independent station modeled on WHDH if the Fox affiliation was lost,<ref name=\"b&c-wsvnnofox?\"/> in an interview with the ''[[Sun-Sentinel]]'', Ansin said that Fox had not informed him of its intentions, and that the station would replace Fox's prime time programming with syndicated programming and an additional newscast.<ref name=\"ss-wsvnnofox?\">{{cite news|last1=Diaz|first1=Johnny|title=Could Fox network shows find a new home on Miami-Fort Lauderdale TV?|url=http://www.sun-sentinel.com/features/fl-reg-wsvn-channel-7-may-lose-fox-affiliation-20180511-story.html|accessdate=May 11, 2018|work=[[Sun-Sentinel]]|date=May 11, 2018}}</ref>\n\nThree weeks after the FCC's July 18, 2018 vote to have the deal reviewed by an [[administrative law judge]] amid \"serious concerns\" about Sinclair's forthrightness in its applications to sell certain conflict properties, on August 9, 2018, Tribune announced it would terminate the Sinclair deal, intending to seek other [[Mergers and acquisitions|M&A]] opportunities. The termination of the said merger also made the Fox purchase of WSFL unsuccessful.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2018-07-16/fcc-rejects-sinclair-plan-for-tv-station-sales-in-tribune-deal-jjof6bcs|title=Sinclair and Tribune Fall as FCC Slams TV Station Sale Plan|author=Todd Shields|date=July 16, 2018|accessdate=July 19, 2018|agency=[[Bloomberg L.P.|Bloomberg News]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://thehill.com/policy/technology/397194-fcc-chairman-rejects-sinclair-tribune-merger|title=FCC chair rejects Sinclair-Tribune merger|author=Harper Neidig|date=July 16, 2018|newspaper=[[The Hill (newspaper)|The Hill]]|accessdate=August 9, 2018|publisher=Capitol Hill Publishing Corp.}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.robertfeder.com/2018/07/16/fcc-throws-sinclairtribune-deal-doubt/|title=FCC throws Sinclair/Tribune deal in doubt|author=[[Robert Feder]]|date=July 16, 2018|website=RobertFeder.com|accessdate=August 9, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://nymag.com/daily/intelligencer/2018/07/fcc-throws-wrench-into-sinclair-tribune-deal.html|title=FCC Throws Wrench Into Sinclair Media Megadeal|author=Benjamin Hart|date=July 16, 2018|periodical=[[New York (magazine)|New York]]|accessdate=August 9, 2018|publisher=New York Media, LLC}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2018/07/18/business/media/sinclair-tribune-fcc.html|title=Sinclair Tries to Appease F.C.C., but Its Tribune Bid Is Challenged|author=Edmund Lee|date=July 18, 2018|newspaper=The New York Times|accessdate=August 9, 2018|publisher=The New York Times Company}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.baltimoresun.com/business/bs-bz-sinclair-tribune-revised-divestitures-20180718-story.html|title=FCC orders hearing even as Sinclair changes plans to sell TV stations to address concerns about Tribune deal|author=Lorraine Mirabella|date=July 18, 2018|publisher=Tronc|accessdate=August 9, 2018|newspaper=[[Baltimore Sun]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/tribune-media-terminates-merger-agreement-with-sinclair-broadcast-group-1533810907|title=Tribune Terminates $3.9 Billion Sinclair Merger, Sues Broadcast Rival|date=August 9, 2018|newspaper=[[The Wall Street Journal]]|publisher=[[News Corp (2013\u2013present)|News Corp.]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://tvnewscheck.com/article/top-news/220320/tribune-kills-sinclair-merger/|title=Tribune Kills Sinclair Merger, Files Suit|author=Mark K. Miller|date=August 9, 2018|website=TVNewsCheck|publisher=NewsCheck Media}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.baltimoresun.com/business/bs-bz-tribune-sinclair-merger-ended-20180809-story.html#|title=Tribune Media pulls out of Sinclair Broadcast merger|author=Christopher Dinsmore|date=August 9, 2018|newspaper=[[Baltimore Sun]]|publisher=[[Tronc]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2018/08/09/business/dealbook/sinclair-tribune-media.html|title=Tribune Ends Deal With Sinclair, Dashing Plan for Conservative TV Behemoth|author=Edmund Lee|date=August 9, 2018|newspaper=The New York Times|publisher=The New York Times Company|author2=Amie Tsang}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.broadcastingcable.com/news/tribune-ends-deal-with-sinclair-files-breach-of-contract-suit|title=Tribune Ends Deal with Sinclair, Files Breach of Contract Suit|author=Jon Lafayette|date=August 9, 2018|publisher=NewBay Media|periodical=Broadcasting & Cable}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/technology/2018/08/09/tribune-withdraws-sinclair-merger-saying-it-will-sue-breach-contract/|title=Tribune withdraws from Sinclair merger, saying it will sue for \u2018breach of contract\u2019|author=Brian Fung|date=August 9, 2018|newspaper=The Washington Post|publisher=Nash Holdings LLC|author2=Tony Romm}}</ref> On December 3, 2018, [[Irving, Texas]]-based [[Nexstar Media Group]] announced it would acquire the assets of Tribune Media for $6.4 billion in cash and debt,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nexstar.tv/wp-content/uploads/2018/12/Nexstar-Tribune-Investor-Presentation-FINAL-12-3-18.pdf|title=Acquisition of Tribune Media Company|date=December 3, 2018|website=[[Nexstar Media Group]]|format=[[PDF]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://tvnewscheck.com/article/top-news/226264/nexstar-buying-tribune-media-6-4-billion/|title=Nexstar Buying Tribune Media For $6.4 Billion|author=Mark K. Miller|date=December 3, 2018|website=TVNewsCheck|publisher=NewsCheck Media}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2018/12/nexstar-tribune-media-acquisition-1202512653/|title=Nexstar Confirms $4.1B Tribune Media Acquisition To Become Leading Local TV Station Owner|author=Peter White|author2=Dade Hayes|date=December 3, 2018|website=Deadline Hollywood|publisher=Penske Media Corporation}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.chicagotribune.com/business/ct-nexstar-tribune-media-20181202-story.html|title=Nexstar to buy WGN owner Tribune Media for $4.1 billion|author=Gerry Smith|author2=Nabila Ahmed|date=December 3, 2018|publisher=[[Tribune Publishing]]|author3=Eric Newcomer|agency=[[Bloomberg L.P.|Bloomberg News]]|newspaper=[[Chicago Tribune]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-tribune-media-m-a-nexstar-media/nexstar-to-buy-tribune-media-for-4-1-billion-idUSKBN1O217Z|title=Nexstar to buy Tribune Media for $4.1 billion|author=Arjun Panchadar|author2=Sonam Rai|date=December 3, 2018|agency=[[Reuters]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.broadcastingcable.com/news/nexstar-announces-deal-to-buy-tribune-for-6-4b|title=Nexstar Announces Deal to Buy Tribune for $6.4B|author=Jon Lafayette|date=December 3, 2018|publisher=NewBay Media|periodical=Broadcasting & Cable}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.rbr.com/reuters-nexstar-gets-tribune-in-4-1b-deal/|title=It\u2019s Official: Nexstar Takes Tribune In Billion-Dollar Stock Deal|author=Adam Jacobson|date=December 3, 2018|website=Radio-Television Business Report|publisher=Streamline-RBR, Inc.}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://tvnewscheck.com/article/top-news/226264/nexstar-buying-tribune-media-6-4-billion/|title=Nexstar To Spin Off $1B In Stations|author=Harry A. Jessell|author2=Mark K. Miller|date=December 3, 2018|website=TVNewsCheck|publisher=NewsCheck Media}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://variety.com/2018/tv/news/tribune-media-acquired-nexstar-media-group-1203073621/|title=Tribune Media to Be Acquired by Nexstar Media Group|author=Cynthia Littleton|date=December 3, 2018|publisher=Penske Media Corporation|accessdate=December 4, 2018|periodical=Variety}}</ref> on March 20, 2019, WSFL was agreed to be divested to [[Cincinnati]]-based [[E. W. Scripps Company|The E. W. Scripps Company]] upon the consummation of the Nexstar-Tribune merger, as part of the company's sale of nineteen Nexstar- and Tribune-operated stations to Scripps and [[Tegna Inc.]] in separate deals worth $1.32 billion.<ref name=\"tvnc=nexstarspinoffs\">{{cite web|url=https://tvnewscheck.com/article/top-news/232391/nexstar-selling-19-tvs-in-15-markets-for-1-32b/|title=Nexstar Selling 19 TVs In 15 Markets For $1.32B|author=Mark K. Miller|date=March 20, 2019|website=TVNewsCheck|publisher=NewsCheck Media}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2019-03-20/nexstar-to-sell-19-stations-to-tegna-scripps-for-1-32-billion|title=Nexstar to Sell Stations to Tegna, Scripps for $1.32 Billion|author=Nabila Ahmed|date=March 20, 2019|publisher=[[Bloomberg, L.P.]]|author2=Anousha Sakoui|website=Bloomberg News}}</ref> On September 26, 2019, WSVN announced that it had renewed its Fox affiliation.<ref name=\"b&c-wsvnfoxrenewal\">{{cite news |last1=Lafayette |first1=Jon |title=WSVN-TV in Miami Renews Affiliation Deal with Fox |url=https://www.broadcastingcable.com/news/wsvn-tv-in-miami-renews-affiliation-deal-with-fox |accessdate=September 27, 2019 |work=[[Broadcasting & Cable]] |date=September 26, 2019 |language=en-us}}</ref>\n\n==Digital television==\n\n===Digital channels===\nThe station's digital signal is [[multiplex (TV)|multiplexed]]:\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! [[Digital subchannel#United States|Channel]]\n! [[Display resolution|Video]]\n! [[Aspect ratio (image)|Aspect]]\n! [[Program and System Information Protocol#What PSIP does|PSIP Short Name]]\n! Programming<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rabbitears.info/market.php?request=station_search&callsign=WSVN#station |title=RabbitEars.Info |website=RabbitEars.info |accessdate=January 21, 2016}}</ref>\n|-\n| 7.1 || [[720p]] || [[16:9]] || WSVN-D1 || Main WSVN programming / [[Fox Broadcasting Company|Fox]]\n|-\n| 7.2 || [[480i]] || [[4:3]] || WSVN-D2 || [[Light TV]] \n|}\n\nWSVN's second digital subchannel carried [[Estrella TV]] from its 2009 launch<ref name=\"tvnc-wsvnestrella7.2\">{{cite news|title=Estrella TV Taps WSVN as Miami Affiliate|url=http://www.tvnewscheck.com/article/31028/estrella-tv-taps-wsvn-as-miami-affiliate|accessdate=January 7, 2018|work=TVNewsCheck|date=April 7, 2009|language=en}}</ref> until July 14, 2017, when it began carrying Light TV.<ref name=\"tvbr-azawgentowpmf\">{{cite news|last1=Jacobson|first1=Adam|title=Exclusive: 'Estrella TV' Ready For A Big Miami Return|url=https://www.rbr.com/estrella-tv-miami-return/|accessdate=January 7, 2018|work=Radio & Television Business Report|date=January 5, 2018|quote=On July 14, 2017, Sunbeam Television-owned WSVN-7 dropped Estrella TV from its DT2 multicast channel, replacing it with LIGHT TV\u2026}}</ref>\n\n==Programming==\nWhen WSVN became a Fox affiliate in January 1989, its programming format was quite unusual for the network's affiliates as it did not include [[sitcom]]s as part of its schedule, it ran [[animated cartoon|cartoons]] only on weekend mornings, and aired a heavy amount of talk and court shows, some [[feature film|movies]], and some drama series. As time went on, though, most Fox stations began relying more on talk and court shows, as well as local newscasts. Channel 7 runs only a slightly heavier amount of local news programming than other Fox stations (which have gradually increased their news outputs over the last 15 years). WSVN continues not to feature any sitcoms as part of its syndication inventory, somewhat atypical for a news-intensive Fox station.\n\n===Sports programming===\nIn 1966, with the establishment of the [[Miami Dolphins]] of the [[American Football League]], the station, via [[NFL on NBC|NBC]], which held the league's broadcast rights, became the station of record for the new team. This alliance continued until the end of the [[1988 Miami Dolphins season|1988 season]], when most games moved over to WTVJ (today, most games are aired by WFOR). Since 1994, the station airs at least two Dolphins games a season via the [[Fox NFL|NFL on Fox]], usually when the team plays host to an [[National Football Conference|NFC]] team at [[Hard Rock Stadium]], however, starting in [[2014 Miami Dolphins season|2014]], with the institution of the NFL's new broadcast 'cross-flex' rules, more games can be seen on Channel 7 when they are moved from WFOR, and since 2018, via Fox's exclusive contract, [[Thursday Night Football]] games. In addition, any [[Miami Marlins]] games featured as part of Fox's MLB broadcast contract are aired on channel 7, this included their victory in the [[2003 World Series]], when the team was still the Florida Marlins. The station was also the local broadcaster of [[Super Bowl LIV]] which was held at Hard Rock Stadium, as Fox [[NFL on Fox|had the national television rights]] to the game; it also previously served as the home broadcaster of [[Super Bowl XXXIII]] which was also on Fox.\n\n==News operation==\nWSVN presently broadcasts 63\u00bd hours of locally produced newscasts each week (with 10\u00bd hours each weekday, six hours on Saturdays and five hours on Sundays), in regards to the number of hours devoted to news programming, it is the highest local newscast output of any local television station in Miami. Unlike other news-intensive Fox stations, WSVN carries newscasts at 5:00 p.m., 6:00 p.m., and 6:30 p.m. on both Saturdays and Sundays (others either air early evening newscasts on weekends at different times on Saturdays and Sundays [i.e., Saturdays at 6:00 p.m. and Sundays at 5:00 p.m.], air them either at only 5:00 p.m. or 6:00 p.m. on both nights or do not carry newscasts in that particular weekend time period at all), however, WSVN's weekend 5:00 p.m. and 6:00 p.m. newscasts are subject to preemption and/or delay due to network sports telecasts running into the timeslot. In addition, the station produces the entertainment news/lifestyle program ''[[Deco Drive]]'' (which airs at 7:30 p.m. weeknights). The station is affiliated with [[CNN]] for news.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Allen|first1=Keith|last2=Preuss|first2=Andreas|title=Millions of dollars found stashed in buckets at Miami home, police say|url=http://www.cnn.com/2016/06/30/us/florida-cash-drugs-gun-found-in-home/|accessdate=June 30, 2016|work=CNN|date=June 30, 2016|quote=...told CNN affiliate WSVN.}}</ref>\n\nWhen the station gained the Fox affiliation on January 1, 1989, it retained a news schedule similar to the one it had as an NBC affiliate, in its early years with Fox, local news programming on the station ran on weekdays from 6:00 a.m. to 9:00 a.m., Noon to 1:00 p.m., 5:00 p.m. to 7:00 p.m., weekends from 6:00 p.m. to 6:30 p.m. and nightly from 10:00 p.m. to 11:00 p.m. The station became the second Fox affiliate to have a weekday morning newscast as a result and was the first one with weeknight 5:00 p.m. and 6:00 p.m. newscasts. On the date of the network switch, WSVN debuted a locally produced early evening [[newsmagazine|news magazine]] program, ''Inside Story'', the program eventually evolved into its present entertainment-based format as ''7:30'' (in reference to its timeslot) in 1994, and later changed its title to the current ''Deco Drive'' in 1996.\n\nUnder [[news director]] [[Joel Cheatwood]], WSVN became well known in South Florida, and throughout the nation, for its emphasis on crime stories and sensationalistic reporting\u2014summarized in the phrase, \"if it bleeds, it leads.\"<ref>{{cite news|last=Jicha|first=Tom|title=News Show To Get WSVN's Familiar Tabloid Touch|url=http://articles.sun-sentinel.com/1991-03-29/features/9101160152_1_newscast-joel-cheatwood-wsvn|accessdate=July 9, 2012|newspaper=[[Sun-Sentinel|Fort Lauderdale Sun-Sentinel]]|date=March 29, 1991}}</ref> Although this embrace of [[tabloid television]] was criticized, it rejuvenated a station that had languished in third place for most of its tenure with NBC. Within a few years, with anchor Rick Sanchez at the helm, WSVN became the market's highest-rated English-language station from sign-on to sign-off,<ref>http://www.flnewscenter.com/archives/696.html</ref> a rank it would hold for the better part of two decades until it was overtaken for the title by WFOR, though WSVN has been a solid runner-up and has tied for second with WPLG.\n\n[[Image:WSVN HD.JPG|225px|thumb|left|WSVN's Pre-2015 HD Newsplex studio.]]\nWSVN's success also influenced how newscasts on other Fox affiliates would look in later years; the station's decision to take on a news-intensive schedule would eventually serve as the template for the programming formats of the former \"Big Three\" stations that switched to Fox as a result of its 1994 affiliation agreement with New World Communications and certain transactions related to the deal, and was gradually adopted by many heritage Fox stations and certain news-producing stations that are not affiliated with the network, NBC, CBS or ABC. It was also the first station to take a cue from CNN, integrating its newsroom and studio into one large area, which the station has termed the \"newsplex\". It evolved out of their initial two sets around the time of the network switch in the late 1980s: one used for its morning and 5:00 p.m. newscasts, which was a small, enclosed area in the newsroom, and its main set, which was positioned in the station's control room. Other stations and networks, both in the U.S. and internationally, have taken cues from WSVN's set. The overall format was successful enough in Miami that in 1993, Ed Ansin assigned Cheatwood to overhaul Sunbeam's newly acquired Boston station WHDH, incorporating a considerably watered-down version of the WSVN format for its newscasts; as in Miami, the tabloid style helped WHDH rise from a perennial third place into a contender for first in the news ratings (against the more traditional [[WCVB-TV]]). WHDH uses many visual cues taken from WSVN including the use of flashy graphics, distinct music packages composed by Chris Crane (who has composed the various custom news themes used by WSVN since 1991) and a similarly designed \"newsplex\" set; WSVN's \"circle 7\" logo was also adopted by WHDH after Sunbeam assumed ownership. A similar format was adopted by [[KJRH-TV]] in [[Tulsa, Oklahoma]] between 1994 and 1997, that station has since reverted to airing traditional newscasts.\n\nThe station's 11:00 p.m. newscast evolved into an hour-long 10:00 p.m. program after it joined Fox, but was revived in 1995 as a 15-minute wrap-up of the proceedings in the [[O.J. Simpson murder case]], and expanded to a half-hour the following year, the 11:00 p.m. newscast expanded to weekend evenings on September 26, 2009.<ref name=\"wsvn-weekend11pmadd\">{{cite news|url=http://www.wsvn.com/news/articles/local/MI132150/|title=WSVN-TV Announces More News at the News Station|date=September 23, 2009|work=WSVN.com|accessdate=September 23, 2009|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090926031340/http://www1.wsvn.com/news/articles/local/MI132150|archive-date=September 26, 2009|url-status=dead}}</ref> The station debuted a half-hour 4:00 p.m. newscast on September 11, 2006,<ref>{{cite news| url=http://southflorida.bizjournals.com/southflorida/stories/2006/09/04/story4.html | first=Brian | last=Bandell | title=More news is good news for WSVN Channel 7 | date=September 4, 2006}}</ref> which later expanded to one hour in 2007. On January 11, 2009, starting with its 5:00 p.m. newscast, WSVN became the second station in the Miami market (behind WTVJ) to begin broadcasting its local newscasts in [[High-definition television|high definition]]. With the switch to HD, came an updated newsplex set that premiered two weeks earlier on December 29, 2008 and new HD graphics. On July 11, 2010, WSVN expanded its Saturday and Sunday 6:00 p.m. newscasts to one hour with the addition of half-hour newscasts at 6:30 p.m.<ref>[http://www.tvnewscheck.com/articles/2010/06/21/daily.9/ WSVN Adding More Weekend News]{{Dead link|date=September 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}, TVNewsCheck.com, June 21, 2010. Accessed October 19, 2010.</ref> On August 22, 2011, WSVN added a fifth hour (from 9:00 p.m. to 10:00 a.m.) to the weekday edition of ''Today in Florida'', by way of the move of ''[[Live! with Kelly and Michael|Live! with Regis and Kelly]]'' to WPLG.<ref>[http://www.tvnewscheck.com/article/2011/08/09/53130/wsvn-miami-expands-morning-news-block WSVN Miami Expands Morning News Block], ''TVNewsCheck'', August 9, 2011.</ref> On Sunday, September 13, 2015, the station expanded its ''Today in Florida'' newscast to Sunday mornings airing from 8:00 a.m. to 11:00 a.m. The latest addition now brings the total newscast output to 64 1/2 hours per week.\n\n===On-air staff===\n\n====Notable former on-air staff====\n{{div col|colwidth=25em}}\n* [[Jim Berry (news anchor)|Jim Berry]] &ndash; sports anchor (now morning news anchor at [[WFOR-TV]], also in Miami) \n* [[Ann Bishop (journalist)|Ann Bishop]] &ndash; script writer (moved to [[WPLG]]/[[Miami]] and became a legendary anchor, died November 14, 1997)\n* [[Penny Daniels]] &ndash; anchor/reporter (retired)\n* [[Donna Hanover]] &ndash; (ex-wife of former New York City mayor [[Rudy Giuliani]])\n* [[Robb Hanrahan]] &ndash; evening anchor (later at [[WABC-TV]]/[[New York City]], now at [[WHP-TV]]/[[Harrisburg, Pennsylvania]])\n* [[Jackie Johnson]] &ndash; meteorologist (now at [[KCBS-TV]]/[[Los Angeles]])\n* [[Alycia Lane]] &ndash; (later at [[KYW-TV]]/[[Philadelphia]], last at [[KNBC]]/Los Angeles)\n* [[Rick Leventhal]] &ndash; (now at [[Fox News Channel]])\n* [[Elita Loresca]] &ndash; meteorologist (now at [[KTRK-TV]] in Houston)\n* [[Joan Lovett]] &ndash; anchor/reporter (later at [[WBBM-TV]]/[[Chicago]])\n* [[Robin Meade]] &ndash; anchor/reporter (now at [[HLN (TV channel)|HLN]])\n* [[Marilyn Mitzel]] &ndash; anchor/reporter (1988\u20132005)\n* [[Charles Perez]] &ndash; anchor/reporter (later at [[WABC-TV]]/[[New York City]], then at WPLG/Miami; retired)\n* [[Jillian Reynolds|Jillian Warry (Reynolds)]] &ndash; meteorologist (later at [[KTTV]]/Los Angeles)\n* [[Shaun Robinson]] &ndash; (later weekend anchor/correspondent for syndicated entertainment newsmagazine ''[[Access Hollywood]]'')\n* [[Rick Sanchez (journalist)|Rick Sanchez]] &ndash; (later at [[MSNBC]] and then [[CNN]]; [[WIOD]] and [[WJAN-CD]] in Miami/Fort Lauderdale; now at [[RT America]])\n* [[Shepard Smith]] &ndash; (now at [[Fox News Channel]])\n* [[Stephanie Stahl (reporter)|Stephanie Stahl]] &ndash; anchor (later and now at KYW-TV in Philadelphia for health and science reporter)\n* [[Linda Stouffer]] &ndash; (now at HLN; went by Cinnamon Stouffer during her stint at WSVN)\n* [[Michelle Tuzee]] &ndash; (now anchor at [[KABC-TV]]/Los Angeles)\n{{div col end}}\n\n==Other notes==\n* WSVN's newscasts were featured in at least two movies, ''[[The Mean Season]]'' (1985) and ''[[Flight of the Navigator]]'' (1986). WSVN can also be seen in several episodes of ''[[Miami Vice]]'' before the NBC affiliation for the Miami market moved to WTVJ towards the end of the show's run.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{official website|https://wsvn.com/}}\n*{{TVQ|WSVN}}\n\n{{Miami TV}}\n{{Fox Florida}}\n{{Sunbeam Television}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Wsvn}}\n[[Category:Television stations in Miami|SVN]]\n[[Category:Fox network affiliates]]\n[[Category:Light TV affiliates]]\n[[Category:Television channels and stations established in 1956]]\n[[Category:Television channels and stations established in 1962]]\n[[Category:1956 establishments in Florida]]\n[[Category:National Football League primary television stations]]\n[[Category:Miami Dolphins broadcasters]]\n", "name_user": "Owenpeterson", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eSports programming:Mentioned the station's coverage of the Dolphins first Super Bowl victory.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/WSVN"}
