{"title_page": "Emmanuel Nii Okai Laryea", "text_new": "{{Infobox officeholder\n| honorific-prefix =\n| name = Emmanuel Nii Okai Laryea\n| honorific-suffix =\n| image = \n| alt = \n| constituency_MP = [[Amasaman (Ghana parliament constituency)|Amasaman Constituency]]\n| parliament = Ghana\n| majority =\n| predecessor =\n| successor = \n| term_start =\n| term_end =\n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|1983|8|16}}\n| birth_place =\n| death_date =\n| death_place =\n| nationality = Ghanaian\n| spouse =\n| party = [[National Democratic Congress (Ghana)|National Democratic Congress]]\n| relations =\n| children =\n| residence =\n| alma_mater =\n| occupation =\n| profession =\n| signature =\n| signature_alt =\n| website =\n| footnotes =\n}}\n\n'''Emmanuel Nii Okai Laryea''' is a Ghanaian politician and member of the [[MPs elected in the Ghanaian parliamentary election, 2016|Seventh Parliament of the Fourth Republic of Ghana]] representing the [[Amasaman (Ghana parliament constituency)|Amasaman Constituency]] in the [[Greater Accra Region]] on the ticket of the [[National Democratic Congress (Ghana)|National Democratic Congress]].<ref name=\":0\">{{cite web|url=https://www.parliament.gh/mps?mp=36|title=Parliament of Ghana|website=Parliament.gh|accessdate=26 February 2019}}</ref><ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.ghanamps.com/mps/details.php?id=5454|title=Ghana MPs - MP Details - Laryea, Emmanuel Nii Okai|website=www.ghanamps.com|access-date=2020-02-08}}</ref>\n\n== Personal Life and  Education ==\nLaryea was born on 16 August, 1983 in a town called Gbese-Accra in his region. He had his Bachelor of Arts degree in Political Science and Information Studies from the [[University of Ghana]], [[Legon]]. Prior to his appointment into parliament, he was the Chief Executive Officer at Commanex Investment Limited. <ref name=\":0\" /><ref name=\":1\" /> \n\n== Political Career ==\nHe was first elected into parliament on 7 January 2013 after the completion of the 2012 Ghanaian General Elections. He was then reelected on 7 January 2016 after the completion of the 2016 Ghanaian General Elections where he obtained 49.83% of the valid votes cast<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.ghanamps.com/mps/details.php?id=5454|title=Ghana MPs - MP Details - Laryea, Emmanuel Nii Okai|website=www.ghanamps.com|access-date=2020-02-08}}</ref>.\n\n== Personal life ==\nHe is a Christian and single.<ref name=\":0\" /><ref name=\":1\" />\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Laryea, Emmanuel Nii Okai}}\n[[Category:1983 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Ghanaian MPs 2017\u2013]]\n[[Category:National Democratic Congress (Ghana) politicians]]\n\n\n{{Ghana-politician-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox officeholder\n| honorific-prefix =\n| name = Emmanuel Nii Okai Laryea\n| honorific-suffix =\n| image = \n| alt = \n| constituency_MP = [[Amasaman (Ghana parliament constituency)|Amasaman Constituency]]\n| parliament = Ghana\n| majority =\n| predecessor =\n| successor = \n| term_start =\n| term_end =\n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|1983|8|16}}\n| birth_place =\n| death_date =\n| death_place =\n| nationality = Ghanaian\n| spouse =\n| party = [[National Democratic Congress (Ghana)|National Democratic Congress]]\n| relations =\n| children =\n| residence =\n| alma_mater =\n| occupation =\n| profession =\n| signature =\n| signature_alt =\n| website =\n| footnotes =\n}}\n\n'''Emmanuel Nii Okai Laryea''' is a Ghanaian politician and member of the [[MPs elected in the Ghanaian parliamentary election, 2016|Seventh Parliament of the Fourth Republic of Ghana]] representing the [[Amasaman (Ghana parliament constituency)|Amasaman Constituency]] in the [[Greater Accra Region]] on the ticket of the [[National Democratic Congress (Ghana)|National Democratic Congress]].<ref name=\":0\">{{cite web|url=https://www.parliament.gh/mps?mp=36|title=Parliament of Ghana|website=Parliament.gh|accessdate=26 February 2019}}</ref><ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.ghanamps.com/mps/details.php?id=5454|title=Ghana MPs - MP Details - Laryea, Emmanuel Nii Okai|website=www.ghanamps.com|access-date=2020-02-08}}</ref>\n\n== Personal Life and  Education ==\nLaryea was born on 16 August, 1983 in a town called Gbese-Accra in his region. He had his Bachelor of Arts degree in Political Science and Information Studies from the [[University of Ghana]], [[Legon]]. Prior to his appointment into parliament, he was the Chief Executive Officer at Commanex Investment Limited. <ref name=\":0\" /><ref name=\":1\" /> \n\n== Political Career ==\nHe was first elected into parliament on 7 January 2013 after the completion of the 2012 Ghanaian General Elections. He was then reelected on 7 January 2016 after the completion of the 2016 Ghanaian General Elections where he obtained 49.83% of the valid votes cast<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.ghanamps.com/mps/details.php?id=5454|title=Ghana MPs - MP Details - Laryea, Emmanuel Nii Okai|website=www.ghanamps.com|access-date=2020-02-08}}</ref>.\n\n== Personal life ==\nHe is a christian and single.<ref name=\":0\" /><ref name=\":1\" />\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Laryea, Emmanuel Nii Okai}}\n[[Category:1983 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Ghanaian MPs 2017\u2013]]\n[[Category:National Democratic Congress (Ghana) politicians]]\n\n\n{{Ghana-politician-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Iridescent", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200ePersonal life:Cleanup andtypo fixing,typo(s) fixed: christian \u2192 Christian", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Emmanuel_Nii_Okai_Laryea"}
{"title_page": "Falguni Roy", "text_new": "{{more citations needed|date=October 2018}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2018}}\n{{Use Indian English|date=October 2018}}\n'''Falguni Roy''' ({{IPAc-en|\u02c8|f|\u00e6|l|g|\u028a|n|i}}; 1945\u20131981) was an anti-establishment [[Bengali people|Bengali]] poet born in Kolkata, West Bengal, India. Along with [[Shakti Chattopadhyay]], [[Malay Roy Choudhury]], [[Samir Roychoudhury]], [[Subimal Basak]], Debi Roy (Haradhon Dhara), Utpal Kumar Basu, [[Binoy Majumdar]], [[Sandipan Chattopadhyay]], [[Basudeb Dasgupta]], Roy was also associated with the [[Hungryalist]] movement.<ref>{{cite news |title=Nostalgia nest, new notes |url=http://www.telegraphindia.com/1041121/asp/calcutta/story_4031257.asp |work=[[The Telegraph (Kolkata)|The Telegraph]] |date=21 November 2004 |accessdate=14 February 2010 }}</ref> Anti-establishment poet Tushar Roy was his brother.\n\n==Film on Falguni==\nAn experimental short film about Roy, ''Ebang Falguni (The Lost Lines Of A Beauty Monster)'', was shown at foreign film festivals. Entirely shot on DVcam, score is composed by Monomix, and run time is 21 min 06 sec. This film had two screenings at the [[River to River. Florence Indian Film Festival|River To River Florence Indian Film Festival]], Florence, Italy on Wednesday 8 December 2004 at 23:00 hrs and on Saturday 11 December 2004 at 18:00 hrs. It featured in Indian Short Shorts section with English and Italian subtitles. It was produced by Subhankar Das (A Graffiti Expressions Presentation, 54 Jatin Das Road, Kolkata-29) and directed by Sharmi Pandey.<ref>{{cite news |title=Asian premiere of the experimental short Ebang Falguni. \n|url=http://press.xtvworld.com/modules.php?name=News&file=article&sid=3358 |work=XTVWorld.Com |date=29 November 2004 |accessdate=14 February 2010 }}</ref>\n\n==Famous poems==\nHe is famous for his book ''Nashto Atmar Television'' ([\u09a8\u09b7\u09cd\u099f \u0986\u09a4\u09cd\u09ae\u09be\u09b0 \u099f\u09c7\u09b2\u09bf\u09ad\u09bf\u09b8\u09a8] literally means: \"Television of The Rotten Soul\"<ref>{{cite book |last1=Ratul |first1=Tanvir |title=Television of the Rotten Soul : poems of Falguni Ray |date= 1 February 2016 |publisher=Antivirus Publication |isbn=978-1326414726 |edition=Second |url=https://www.amazon.co.uk/Television-Rotten-Soul-Falguni-Ray/dp/1326414720/ref=tmm_pap_swatch_0?_encoding=UTF8&qid=&sr=}}</ref>) published on the Independence Day of 1973, a day considered to be the date signifying the end of Modernism in Bengali Poetry. Some of his poems published in the anthology '''Amar Rifel Amar Bible athoba Falguni Royer Falguni Roy''' are:\n\n*''Amar Rifle amar Bible'' (\u0986\u09ae\u09be\u09b0 \u09b0\u09be\u0987\u09ab\u09c7\u09b2 \u0986\u09ae\u09be\u09b0 \u09ac\u09be\u0987\u09ac\u09c7\u09b2)\n*''Manik Bandyopadhyayer Choshma'' (\u09ae\u09be\u09a8\u09bf\u0995 \u09ac\u09a8\u09cd\u09a6\u09cd\u09af\u09cb\u09aa\u09be\u09a7\u09cd\u09af\u09be\u09af\u09bc\u09c7\u09b0 \u099a\u09b6\u09ae\u09be)\n*''Kritrim Saap'' (\u0995\u09c3\u09a4\u09cd\u09b0\u09bf\u09ae \u09b8\u09be\u09aa)\n*''Aamader Swapno'' (\u0986\u09ae\u09be\u09a6\u09c7\u09b0 \u09b8\u09cd\u09ac\u09aa\u09cd\u09a8)\n*''Kobita Bullet'' (\u0995\u09ac\u09bf\u09a4\u09be \u09ac\u09c1\u09b2\u09c7\u099f)\n*''Biplober Gaan'' (\u09ac\u09bf\u09aa\u09cd\u09b2\u09ac\u09c7\u09b0 \u0997\u09be\u09a8)\n*''Aami Aamar Moton'' (\u0986\u09ae\u09bf \u0986\u09ae\u09be\u09b0 \u09ae\u09a4\u09a8)\n*''Manusher songe kono Birodh Nei'' (\u09ae\u09be\u09a8\u09c1\u09b7\u09c7\u09b0 \u09b8\u0999\u09cd\u0997\u09c7 \u0995\u09cb\u09a8\u09cb \u09ac\u09bf\u09b0\u09cb\u09a7 \u09a8\u09c7\u0987)\n*''Nashto Atmar Television'' (\u09a8\u09b7\u09cd\u099f \u0986\u09a4\u09cd\u09ae\u09be\u09b0 \u099f\u09c7\u09b2\u09bf\u09ad\u09bf\u09b8\u09a8)\n*''Sesh Bibriti'' (\u09b6\u09c7\u09b7 \u09ac\u09bf\u09ac\u09c3\u09a4\u09bf)\n*''Baektigato Bichhana'' (\u09ac\u09cd\u09af\u0995\u09cd\u09a4\u09bf\u0997\u09a4 \u09ac\u09bf\u099b\u09be\u09a8\u09be)\n\n==See also==\n{{Div col|colwidth=30em}}\n* [[Shakti Chattopadhyay]]\n* [[Malay Roy Choudhury]]\n* [[Subimal Basak]]\n* [[Basudeb Dasgupta]]\n* [[Tridib Mitra]]\n* [[Samir Roychoudhury]]\n* [[Sandipan Chattopadhyay]]\n* [[Hungry generation]]\n* [[Binoy Majumdar]]\n* [[Sandipan Chattopadhyay]]\n{{div col end}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*'''[https://www.amazon.co.uk/Television-Rotten-Soul-Tanvir-Ratul-ebook/dp/B01AZACTLW/ref=sr_1_2?s=digital-text&ie=UTF8&qid=1484171115&sr=1-2 Television of the Rotten Soul]''' Edited by ''[https://www.facebook.com/tanvir.ratul Tanvir Ratul]''\n*[http://www.time.com/time/magazine/article/0,9171,830799,00.html News published in TIME magazine about Hungry generation movement]\n*[http://www.kaurab.com/english/bengali_poetry/Hungry-Generation Photographs of the participants of the movement]\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Roy, Falguni}}\n[[Category:Bengali-language poets]]\n[[Category:1981 deaths]]\n[[Category:1945 births]]\n[[Category:Bengali male poets]]\n[[Category:University of Calcutta alumni]]\n[[Category:Writers from Kolkata]]\n[[Category:Indian male poets]]\n[[Category:Hungry generation]]\n[[Category:20th-century Indian poets]]\n[[Category:Poets from West Bengal]]\n[[Category:20th-century Indian male writers]]\n", "text_old": "{{moresources|date=October 2018}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2018}}\n{{Use Indian English|date=October 2018}}\n'''Falguni Roy''' ({{IPAc-en|\u02c8|f|\u00e6|l|g|\u028a|n|i}}; 1945\u20131981) was an anti-establishment [[Bengali people|Bengali]] poet born in Kolkata, West Bengal, India. Along with [[Shakti Chattopadhyay]], [[Malay Roy Choudhury]], [[Samir Roychoudhury]], [[Subimal Basak]], Debi Roy (Haradhon Dhara), Utpal Kumar Basu, [[Binoy Majumdar]], [[Sandipan Chattopadhyay]], [[Basudeb Dasgupta]], Roy was also associated with the [[Hungryalist]] movement.<ref>{{cite news |title=Nostalgia nest, new notes |url=http://www.telegraphindia.com/1041121/asp/calcutta/story_4031257.asp |work=[[The Telegraph (Kolkata)|The Telegraph]] |date=21 November 2004 |accessdate=14 February 2010 }}</ref> Anti-establishment poet Tushar Roy was his brother.\n\n==Film on Falguni==\nAn experimental short film about Roy, ''Ebang Falguni (The Lost Lines Of A Beauty Monster)'', was shown at foreign film festivals. Entirely shot on DVcam, score is composed by Monomix, and run time is 21 min 06 sec. This film had two screenings at the [[River to River. Florence Indian Film Festival|River To River Florence Indian Film Festival]], Florence, Italy on Wednesday 8 December 2004 at 23:00 hrs and on Saturday 11 December 2004 at 18:00 hrs. It featured in Indian Short Shorts section with English and Italian subtitles. It was produced by Subhankar Das (A Graffiti Expressions Presentation, 54 Jatin Das Road, Kolkata-29) and directed by Sharmi Pandey.<ref>{{cite news |title=Asian premiere of the experimental short Ebang Falguni. \n|url=http://press.xtvworld.com/modules.php?name=News&file=article&sid=3358 |work=XTVWorld.Com |date=29 November 2004 |accessdate=14 February 2010 }}</ref>\n\n==Famous poems==\nHe is famous for his book ''Nashto Atmar Television'' ([\u09a8\u09b7\u09cd\u099f \u0986\u09a4\u09cd\u09ae\u09be\u09b0 \u099f\u09c7\u09b2\u09bf\u09ad\u09bf\u09b8\u09a8] literally means: \"Television of The Rotten Soul\"<ref>{{cite book |last1=Ratul |first1=Tanvir |title=Television of the Rotten Soul : poems of Falguni Ray |date= 1 February 2016 |publisher=Antivirus Publication |isbn=978-1326414726 |edition=Second |url=https://www.amazon.co.uk/Television-Rotten-Soul-Falguni-Ray/dp/1326414720/ref=tmm_pap_swatch_0?_encoding=UTF8&qid=&sr=}}</ref>) published on the Independence Day of 1973, a day considered to be the date signifying the end of Modernism in Bengali Poetry. Some of his poems published in the anthology '''Amar Rifel Amar Bible athoba Falguni Royer Falguni Roy''' are:\n\n*''Amar Rifle amar Bible'' (\u0986\u09ae\u09be\u09b0 \u09b0\u09be\u0987\u09ab\u09c7\u09b2 \u0986\u09ae\u09be\u09b0 \u09ac\u09be\u0987\u09ac\u09c7\u09b2)\n*''Manik Bandyopadhyayer Choshma'' (\u09ae\u09be\u09a8\u09bf\u0995 \u09ac\u09a8\u09cd\u09a6\u09cd\u09af\u09cb\u09aa\u09be\u09a7\u09cd\u09af\u09be\u09af\u09bc\u09c7\u09b0 \u099a\u09b6\u09ae\u09be)\n*''Kritrim Saap'' (\u0995\u09c3\u09a4\u09cd\u09b0\u09bf\u09ae \u09b8\u09be\u09aa)\n*''Aamader Swapno'' (\u0986\u09ae\u09be\u09a6\u09c7\u09b0 \u09b8\u09cd\u09ac\u09aa\u09cd\u09a8)\n*''Kobita Bullet'' (\u0995\u09ac\u09bf\u09a4\u09be \u09ac\u09c1\u09b2\u09c7\u099f)\n*''Biplober Gaan'' (\u09ac\u09bf\u09aa\u09cd\u09b2\u09ac\u09c7\u09b0 \u0997\u09be\u09a8)\n*''Aami Aamar Moton'' (\u0986\u09ae\u09bf \u0986\u09ae\u09be\u09b0 \u09ae\u09a4\u09a8)\n*''Manusher songe kono Birodh Nei'' (\u09ae\u09be\u09a8\u09c1\u09b7\u09c7\u09b0 \u09b8\u0999\u09cd\u0997\u09c7 \u0995\u09cb\u09a8\u09cb \u09ac\u09bf\u09b0\u09cb\u09a7 \u09a8\u09c7\u0987)\n*''Nashto Atmar Television'' (\u09a8\u09b7\u09cd\u099f \u0986\u09a4\u09cd\u09ae\u09be\u09b0 \u099f\u09c7\u09b2\u09bf\u09ad\u09bf\u09b8\u09a8)\n*''Sesh Bibriti'' (\u09b6\u09c7\u09b7 \u09ac\u09bf\u09ac\u09c3\u09a4\u09bf)\n*''Baektigato Bichhana'' (\u09ac\u09cd\u09af\u0995\u09cd\u09a4\u09bf\u0997\u09a4 \u09ac\u09bf\u099b\u09be\u09a8\u09be)\n\n==See also==\n{{Div col|colwidth=30em}}\n* [[Shakti Chattopadhyay]]\n* [[Malay Roy Choudhury]]\n* [[Subimal Basak]]\n* [[Basudeb Dasgupta]]\n* [[Tridib Mitra]]\n* [[Samir Roychoudhury]]\n* [[Sandipan Chattopadhyay]]\n* [[Hungry generation]]\n* [[Binoy Majumdar]]\n* [[Sandipan Chattopadhyay]]\n{{div col end}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*'''[https://www.amazon.co.uk/Television-Rotten-Soul-Tanvir-Ratul-ebook/dp/B01AZACTLW/ref=sr_1_2?s=digital-text&ie=UTF8&qid=1484171115&sr=1-2 Television of the Rotten Soul]''' Edited by ''[https://www.facebook.com/tanvir.ratul Tanvir Ratul]''\n*[http://www.time.com/time/magazine/article/0,9171,830799,00.html News published in TIME magazine about Hungry generation movement]\n*[http://www.kaurab.com/english/bengali_poetry/Hungry-Generation Photo